  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Gut opened, controlled conditions: Clean-contaminated.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is \"Clean contaminated\" because an elective right hemicolectomy involves opening the gastrointestinal tract under controlled conditions, which is the hallmark of this wound classification. This type of surgery carries a moderate risk of surgical site infection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA clean-contaminated wound is defined as one where the alimentary, respiratory, or genitourinary tract is entered under controlled conditions, without unusual contamination. Examples include elective bowel resections, cholecystectomies, and lung resections. Despite controlled entry, these tracts contain endogenous flora, necessitating prophylactic antibiotics and careful surgical technique to minimize the risk of surgical site infection, as evidenced by the patient's post-operative pyrexia.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Clean) (Incorrect): This classification applies to elective, non-traumatic wounds without inflammation, where the respiratory, alimentary, or genitourinary tracts are not entered. Examples include hernia repair or breast biopsy.\nOption C (Contaminated) (Incorrect): This classification involves gross spillage from the gastrointestinal tract, acute non-purulent inflammation, or major breaks in sterile technique. An elective hemicolectomy, even with bowel opening, is performed under controlled conditions.\nOption D (Dirty) (Incorrect): This classification applies to wounds with pre-existing clinical infection, perforated viscera, or devitalized tissue. The patient's elective surgery for a caecal tumor does not fit this description.\nOption E (Clean dirty) (Incorrect): This is not a recognized surgical wound classification category.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Classification | Definition | Examples | Infection Rate (%) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Clean | Elective, non-traumatic, no inflammation, no entry into tracts | Hernia repair, breast biopsy | 1-2 |\n| Clean-Contaminated | Controlled entry into respiratory, alimentary, or genitourinary tract | Elective bowel resection, cholecystectomy | 3-7 |\n| Contaminated | Gross spillage, acute inflammation, major break in technique | Appendectomy for acute appendicitis, penetrating trauma | 10-17 |\n| Dirty | Pre-existing infection, perforated viscus, devitalized tissue | Abscess drainage, perforated diverticulitis | >20 |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bowel surgery is always at least clean-contaminated.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the operating room, a right hemicolectomy involves resecting the terminal ileum, cecum, ascending colon, and hepatic flexure, followed by an ileocolic anastomosis. The caecal tumor would be directly visualized. No imaging was provided in the question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCDC Guidelines for the Prevention of Surgical Site Infection (2017) recommend appropriate prophylactic antibiotics based on the wound classification and type of surgery to reduce infection risk.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Clean | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Clean contaminated | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Contaminated | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Dirty | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Clean dirty | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
