  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Always consider DVT in post-op patients with new leg pain and swelling.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Deep Vein Thrombosis (DVT). The patient's recent major surgery (abdominoperineal resection), advanced age, and classic symptoms of unilateral leg pain, erythema, and edema strongly point towards DVT as the most likely diagnosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDVT is a common and serious complication, especially after major surgery. The patient's history aligns perfectly with Virchow's triad: surgical trauma causes endothelial injury, post-operative immobility leads to venous stasis, and the post-operative state itself is often hypercoagulable. These factors, combined with her age, significantly increase her risk for DVT, making it the primary concern for new-onset unilateral leg symptoms.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Cellulitis) (Incorrect): While presenting with erythema and pain, cellulitis usually has a clear portal of entry (e.g., wound, scratch) and often systemic signs (fever, chills), which are not mentioned. DVT is a much higher risk in this post-operative patient.\nOption C (Ruptured Baker’s cyst) (Incorrect): A ruptured Baker's cyst typically causes acute pain in the posterior calf, often mimicking DVT, but is usually associated with underlying knee pathology (e.g., arthritis) and less likely to present with diffuse erythema.\nOption D (Muscle rupture) (Incorrect): Muscle rupture usually has an acute, identifiable traumatic event or sudden exertion, which is not described here. The diffuse nature of the symptoms also makes it less likely.\nOption E (Arterial insufficiency) (Incorrect): Arterial insufficiency would typically present with pallor, coolness, diminished or absent pulses, and pain with exertion (claudication). The patient's intact peripheral pulses and erythematous, edematous leg contradict this diagnosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Deep Vein Thrombosis (DVT) | Cellulitis | Arterial Insufficiency |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Symptoms** | Unilateral leg pain, swelling, erythema, warmth | Localized redness, warmth, pain, swelling; often fever/chills | Pain with exertion (claudication), pallor, coolness, diminished pulses |\n| **Risk Factors** | Recent surgery, immobility, cancer, age, hypercoagulable states | Skin breach, lymphedema, obesity, diabetes | Atherosclerosis, smoking, diabetes, hypertension, hyperlipidemia |\n| **Key Findings** | Positive Homan's sign (unreliable), palpable cord, pitting edema | Spreading erythema with ill-defined borders, tenderness | Absent/diminished pulses, trophic changes, prolonged capillary refill |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unilateral leg swelling post-op is DVT until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuplex ultrasound would show non-compressible veins, intraluminal thrombus, and absent or altered flow within the affected deep veins.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Chest Physicians (ACCP) Guidelines 2016: Recommend pharmacologic prophylaxis (e.g., LMWH) for most surgical patients at moderate to high risk of VTE.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cellulitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Deep vein thrombosis | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Ruptured Baker’s cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Muscle rupture | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Arterial insufﬁciency | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
