  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Burn patients get cold, not hot!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Hyperthermia. Severe burns typically lead to significant heat loss and subsequent hypothermia, not hyperthermia, due to the extensive disruption of the skin's barrier function and increased evaporative cooling.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSevere burns destroy the skin's protective barrier, leading to massive evaporative water loss from the wound surface. This evaporation is a highly efficient cooling mechanism, causing substantial heat loss from the body. Additionally, the systemic inflammatory response syndrome (SIRS) associated with severe burns can dysregulate thermoregulation, often contributing to a lower core body temperature. The body struggles to maintain normothermia against this constant heat drain, making hypothermia a common and dangerous complication.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Hypovolemia) (Incorrect): Severe burns cause massive fluid shifts due to capillary leak and increased evaporative losses, leading to profound hypovolemia and burn shock.\nOption B (Sepsis) (Incorrect): The loss of the skin barrier, coupled with immunosuppression, makes burn patients highly susceptible to bacterial and fungal infections, frequently leading to sepsis.\nOption C (Doudenal ulcer) (Incorrect): Stress ulcers, specifically Curling's ulcers, are a well-known complication of severe burns, resulting from the systemic stress response and splanchnic vasoconstriction.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Mechanism | Clinical Manifestation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Hypovolemia | Capillary leak, fluid shift, evaporative loss | Tachycardia, hypotension, decreased urine output |\n| Sepsis | Loss of skin barrier, immunosuppression | Fever/hypothermia, leukocytosis/leukopenia, organ dysfunction |\n| Curling's Ulcer | Stress response, splanchnic vasoconstriction | GI bleeding, abdominal pain, hematemesis |\n| Hypothermia | Evaporative heat loss, impaired thermoregulation | Core body temp < 35°C, shivering, altered mental status |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Severe burns cause massive heat loss, leading to hypothermia.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile not directly an imaging finding, intraoperatively or during initial assessment, one would observe extensive tissue damage, fluid exudation, and often a patient struggling with core body temperature regulation, necessitating aggressive warming measures.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Burn Association (ABA) Practice Guidelines for Burn Care (2018): Recommends aggressive fluid resuscitation for hypovolemia, strict infection control to prevent sepsis, and measures to prevent hypothermia, emphasizing the critical role of thermoregulation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hypovolemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Sepsis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Doudenal ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hyperthermia | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
