  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't miss the clot, or the patient will be shot (hypotension).**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nPulmonary embolism is the most appropriate diagnosis. The acute onset of nausea, chest pain, tachycardia, hemoptysis, and hypotension is a classic presentation for a massive or submassive pulmonary embolism, indicating significant hemodynamic compromise.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA pulmonary embolism (PE) occurs when a thrombus obstructs the pulmonary arterial tree, leading to increased pulmonary vascular resistance and right ventricular strain. This can cause acute chest pain (due to pulmonary infarction or pleurisy), tachycardia (compensatory), and hypotension (due to reduced cardiac output from right ventricular failure). Hemoptysis can result from pulmonary infarction or hemorrhage. The combination of these symptoms, particularly with hypotension, points to a life-threatening PE.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Hemorrhage) (Incorrect): While hemorrhage causes hypotension and tachycardia, it typically presents with signs of blood loss and not primarily with acute chest pain and hemoptysis unless it's a massive pulmonary hemorrhage, which is a distinct clinical entity.\nOption C (Septic shock) (Incorrect): Septic shock involves hypotension and tachycardia but is characterized by signs of infection and systemic inflammatory response, not typically acute chest pain and hemoptysis as primary presenting symptoms.\nOption D (Chest infection) (Incorrect): A chest infection can cause chest pain and hemoptysis, but severe hypotension and acute tachycardia to this degree are less common unless it progresses to septic shock, and the acute onset described points away from a typical infection.\nOption E (Gastroenteritis) (Incorrect): Gastroenteritis causes nausea, but its primary symptoms are vomiting and diarrhea, and it does not typically cause chest pain, hemoptysis, or severe hypotension unless profound dehydration occurs, which is not the primary presentation here.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Symptoms | Hemoptysis | Hypotension |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Pulmonary Embolism | Acute chest pain, dyspnea, tachycardia, syncope | Common | Common (massive PE) |\n| Myocardial Infarction | Crushing chest pain, radiation, dyspnea, diaphoresis | Rare | Possible (cardiogenic shock) |\n| Aortic Dissection | Tearing chest/back pain, pulse deficit, neurological deficits | Rare | Common |\n| Pneumonia | Cough, fever, sputum, pleuritic chest pain | Possible | Possible (sepsis) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute chest pain, dyspnea, tachycardia, and hypotension demand PE exclusion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nCT pulmonary angiography (CTPA) is the gold standard for diagnosis, revealing a filling defect in the pulmonary arteries. Chest X-ray may be normal or show non-specific findings like Westermark sign or Hampton's hump.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2019 ESC Guidelines for the diagnosis and management of acute pulmonary embolism. Recommends CTPA for diagnosis in patients with high or intermediate probability.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pulmonary embolism | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Hemorrhage | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Septic shock | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Chest infection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Gastroenteritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
