  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hypercalcemia has many causes, but TB isn't one of them.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Tuberculosis is the correct answer because, unlike the other options, it is not a typical cause of hypercalcemia. The other conditions listed are well-established etiologies for elevated serum calcium levels.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHypercalcemia is a common metabolic derangement with a broad differential. Primary hyperparathyroidism leads to hypercalcemia through excessive PTH secretion, increasing bone resorption and renal calcium reabsorption. Malignancy-associated hypercalcemia, seen in bone metastases and multiple myeloma, results from osteolytic activity or parathyroid hormone-related peptide (PTHrP) secretion. Sarcoidosis, a granulomatous disease, causes hypercalcemia due to activated macrophages producing 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D, leading to increased intestinal calcium absorption.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Primary hyperparathyroidism is a very common cause of hypercalcemia, characterized by inappropriately high PTH levels.\nOption B (Incorrect): Bone metastases, particularly from breast, lung, and renal cancers, frequently cause hypercalcemia through osteolytic destruction.\nOption C (Incorrect): Multiple myeloma is a plasma cell dyscrasia that causes hypercalcemia by activating osteoclasts and suppressing osteoblasts, leading to extensive bone destruction.\nOption E (Incorrect): Sarcoidosis is a granulomatous disease where activated macrophages produce calcitriol (1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D), leading to increased intestinal calcium absorption and hypercalcemia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause of Hypercalcemia | Mechanism | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|\n| Primary Hyperparathyroidism | Excess PTH production | Elevated PTH, often asymptomatic or \"stones, bones, groans, psychiatric overtones\" |\n| Malignancy (e.g., bone mets, myeloma) | PTHrP secretion, osteolysis | Rapid onset, often severe, associated with advanced cancer |\n| Granulomatous Diseases (e.g., Sarcoidosis) | Macrophage 1-alpha hydroxylase activity | Elevated 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D, often chronic |\n| Thiazide Diuretics | Increased renal calcium reabsorption | Mild, often unmasks underlying hyperparathyroidism |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: When considering hypercalcemia, think \"CHIMPANZEES\" for the differential, but remember not all granulomas cause it.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging for hypercalcemia often involves neck ultrasound or Sestamibi scan for parathyroid adenomas, or skeletal surveys/CT scans to identify lytic bone lesions in malignancy. In the OR, a parathyroid adenoma would appear as an enlarged, often darker gland.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Association of Endocrine Surgeons (AAES) Guidelines for the Management of Primary Hyperparathyroidism (2016) provide recommendations for diagnosis and surgical intervention.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Primary hyperparathyroidism | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Bone metastases | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Multiple myeloma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Tuberculosis | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Sarcoidosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
