  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Deep duct, superficial gland: know your salivary geography!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption B is the incorrect statement regarding the anatomy of the submandibular salivary gland. The submandibular duct, also known as Wharton's duct, primarily arises from the deep part of the gland, not the superficial part. This distinction is crucial for understanding gland drainage and surgical approaches.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe submandibular gland is uniquely positioned, wrapping around the posterior free border of the mylohyoid muscle, which effectively divides it into a larger superficial part and a smaller deep part. The submandibular duct (Wharton's duct) originates from this deep part, which lies superior to the mylohyoid muscle. The duct then courses anteriorly, passing medial to the sublingual gland, to open at the sublingual papilla near the frenulum of the tongue. This deep origin and its intricate course are critical for surgical planning, especially during submandibulectomy or duct exploration, to avoid injury to adjacent vital structures like the lingual and hypoglossal nerves.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The mylohyoid muscle does indeed divide the submandibular gland into superficial and deep parts, making this a true statement.\nOption C (Incorrect): The deep part of the gland is intimately related to the hypoglossal nerve (CN XII), which passes inferior to it, making this a true statement.\nOption D (Incorrect): The submandibular duct is closely related to the lingual nerve, which typically loops inferiorly and medially to the duct before crossing it superiorly, making this a true statement.\nOption E (Incorrect): The facial artery typically grooves the posterior and superior aspects of the submandibular gland before ascending onto the face, making this a true statement.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Superficial Part | Deep Part | Submandibular Duct (Wharton's) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Location** | Inferior to mylohyoid muscle | Superior to mylohyoid muscle | Arises from deep part, runs anteriorly on mylohyoid |\n| **Relations** | Facial artery (posterior), Mylohyoid (superior) | Lingual nerve (lateral then superior), Hypoglossal nerve (inferior) | Lingual nerve (crosses superiorly), Hypoglossal nerve (inferior) |\n| **Function** | Main glandular body | Extension, primary duct origin | Drains saliva into oral cavity at sublingual papilla |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Wharton's duct emerges from the deep part, not superficial.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/MRI), the mylohyoid muscle can be identified as the key anatomical landmark separating the superficial and deep lobes of the submandibular gland. Intraoperatively, the deep part of the gland and the origin of Wharton's duct are found superior to the mylohyoid, with the lingual nerve often seen looping around the duct, requiring careful dissection to preserve its integrity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology—Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Sialolithiasis (2016) emphasizes the importance of precise anatomical knowledge for safe and effective surgical management of submandibular gland pathologies, including ductal stones.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The mylohyoid muscle divide the gland into superficial and deep part | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The submandibular duct arises from superficial part of the gland | ✅ Correct |\n| C | The deep part of the gland is related to hypoglossal nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | The submandibular duct is related closely related to the lingual nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | The fascial artery is related to the posterior aspect of the gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
