  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, parotid lump means pleomorphic adenoma out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Pleomorphic adenoma. This is the most frequently encountered benign tumor of the parotid gland, accounting for the majority of discrete parotid lumps encountered in clinical practice.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPleomorphic adenoma, also known as a mixed tumor, is the most common salivary gland tumor overall, with approximately 80% occurring in the parotid gland. These tumors are characterized by their slow-growing, painless, firm, and mobile nature, presenting as well-circumscribed, discrete masses. Their mixed epithelial and mesenchymal components contribute to their characteristic histological appearance and clinical presentation as the commonest discrete parotid lump.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Mucoepidermoid carcinoma) (Incorrect): While it is the most common malignant salivary gland tumor, malignant tumors are significantly less frequent than benign ones, making it not the commonest overall discrete lump.\nOption C (Mumps) (Incorrect): Mumps causes diffuse, often bilateral, painful parotid gland swelling due to viral infection, not a discrete, localized lump.\nOption D (Parotid gland stone) (Incorrect): A parotid gland stone (sialolithiasis) causes swelling, often intermittent and painful, due to ductal obstruction, but it is not typically described as a discrete parenchymal lump in the same way a tumor is.\nOption E (Tuberculosis of parotid lymph node) (Incorrect): Tuberculosis of parotid lymph nodes is a rare cause of parotid swelling and is an inflammatory/infectious process, not a discrete tumor, and certainly not the commonest.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Pleomorphic Adenoma | Warthin's Tumor | Mucoepidermoid Carcinoma | Acute Sialadenitis |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Nature** | Benign epithelial/mesenchymal | Benign, lymphoid stroma | Malignant epithelial | Inflammatory/Infectious |\n| **Prevalence** | Most common salivary tumor | 2nd most common benign | Most common malignant | Common, especially post-op |\n| **Presentation** | Slow-growing, painless, discrete lump | Painless, often bilateral, smokers | Variable, can be aggressive | Acute pain, swelling, fever |\n| **Risk of Malignant Transformation** | ~1.5-10% (carcinoma ex pleomorphic adenoma) | Very low | Inherent malignancy | None |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pleomorphic adenoma is the king of parotid lumps.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a pleomorphic adenoma typically appears as a well-circumscribed, hypoechoic, solid mass. CT/MRI often show a well-defined, lobulated mass with variable enhancement. Intraoperatively, it is usually encapsulated, firm, and can have a glistening, myxoid cut surface.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Head and Neck Cancers (e.g., Version 1.2024 - Salivary Gland Tumors) recommend surgical excision with clear margins for pleomorphic adenomas to prevent recurrence and potential malignant transformation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pleomorphic adenoma | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Mucoepidermoid carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Mumps | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Parotied gland stone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Tuberculosis of parotid lymph node | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
