  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 NG tubes: cheap to place, but watch for the cough and the burn!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 'High cost' because, while nasogastric (NG) tube feeding carries several potential complications, its cost-effectiveness compared to other nutritional support methods like parenteral nutrition or prolonged hospitalization is generally considered an advantage, not a disadvantage. The other options represent well-documented complications directly related to the presence and function of an NG tube.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNasogastric tubes are foreign bodies that traverse the nasal cavity, pharynx, and esophagus. This anatomical pathway explains local irritation leading to pharyngitis, esophagitis, and nasal obstruction. The tube can also compromise the lower esophageal sphincter, increasing the risk of gastroesophageal reflux and subsequent aspiration pneumonia, especially in patients with impaired gag reflex or altered mental status. These are direct physiological and mechanical consequences, whereas cost is an economic factor.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Pharyngitis is a common local irritation due to the presence of the tube in the pharynx.\nOption C (Incorrect): Aspiration pneumonia is a serious complication, as the tube can compromise airway protection and facilitate reflux.\nOption D (Incorrect): Esophagitis can result from mechanical irritation or reflux induced by the tube.\nOption E (Incorrect): Nasal obstruction is a direct mechanical effect of the tube occupying space in the nasal passage.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication Type | Example | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| Mechanical | Nasal obstruction, Esophagitis, Pharyngitis | Direct irritation from tube |\n| Infectious | Aspiration pneumonia, Sinusitis | Compromised airway protection, bacterial colonization |\n| Gastrointestinal | Diarrhea, Nausea, Vomiting | Formula intolerance, rapid infusion, reduced motility |\n| Metabolic | Refeeding syndrome, Electrolyte imbalance | Inappropriate formula or rate of administration |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: NG tubes are cost-effective, but mechanical and aspiration risks are real.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray, the NG tube should be seen coiled in the stomach, below the diaphragm, confirming correct placement and ruling out tracheal intubation or esophageal coiling.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Parenteral and Enteral Nutrition (ASPEN) Guidelines (2016). They recommend early enteral nutrition via NG tube when oral intake is insufficient and the GI tract is functional.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | High cost | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Pharyngitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Possibility of aspiration pneumonia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Esophagitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Nasal obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
