  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Old blood gives you hyperkalemia, not hypokalemia.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. Banked blood is deficient in many components, but potassium levels actually increase over time due to red blood cell lysis during storage, leading to hyperkalemia, not a deficiency.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nStored blood undergoes several changes. Platelets lose their function within hours to a few days, making them deficient. White blood cells (WBCs) are either removed by leukoreduction or become non-functional. While red blood cells maintain oxygen-carrying capacity, levels of 2,3-bisphosphoglycerate (2,3-BPG) decrease, shifting the oxygen dissociation curve to the left and impairing oxygen release to tissues. Antihemophilic globulin (Factor VIII) is a labile clotting factor that degrades rapidly during storage. Conversely, red blood cell lysis releases intracellular potassium into the plasma, causing potassium levels to rise significantly, especially in older units of blood.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Platelets lose their viability and function within a few hours to days of blood collection, making banked blood deficient in functional platelets.\nOption B (Incorrect): White blood cells (WBCs) are either removed by leukoreduction to prevent transfusion reactions and disease transmission, or they become non-functional during storage.\nOption C (Incorrect): While red blood cells are present, the oxygen-carrying capacity is impaired due to decreased 2,3-BPG levels, which shifts the oxygen dissociation curve to the left, reducing oxygen release to tissues.\nOption E (Incorrect): Antihemophilic globulin (Factor VIII) is a labile clotting factor that degrades rapidly in stored blood, leading to its deficiency.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Component | Fresh Blood | Stored Blood (e.g., >7 days) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Platelets | Functional | Non-functional/Deficient |\n| WBCs | Functional | Non-functional/Removed |\n| Factor V & VIII | Normal | Decreased/Deficient |\n| 2,3-BPG | Normal | Decreased |\n| Potassium | Normal | Increased (Hyperkalemia) |\n| pH | Normal | Decreased (Acidosis) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Banked blood is low on factors and 2,3-BPG, but high on potassium and acid.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn cases of massive transfusion with older blood, an ECG might show signs of hyperkalemia (peaked T waves, widened QRS), requiring immediate intervention.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Blood Banks (AABB) Guidelines (e.g., 2023). These guidelines provide recommendations for blood collection, processing, storage, and transfusion practices to ensure patient safety and product efficacy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Platelet | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | WBCs | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Oxygen carrying capacity | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Potassium | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Antihemophilic globulin | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
