  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Full thickness, full dermis, full resistance to contraction.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Full thickness. Full-thickness skin grafts (FTSG) exhibit the least amount of contraction compared to split-thickness skin grafts (STSG) because they contain the entire dermal layer, which provides structural integrity and resists contractile forces.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFull-thickness skin grafts include the epidermis and the entire dermis, which is rich in collagen and elastic fibers, as well as adnexal structures like hair follicles and sweat glands. This robust dermal component acts as a scaffold, resisting the contractile forces exerted by myofibroblasts during the wound healing process. The presence of a complete dermal layer minimizes both primary contraction (immediate recoil upon harvest) and secondary contraction (post-grafting shrinkage), leading to a more stable and aesthetically pleasing result, especially in areas like the face or joints where contraction can be functionally debilitating.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Split-thickness skin grafts contain only a portion of the dermis, which has fewer collagen and elastic fibers. This allows for greater myofibroblast activity and significantly more primary and secondary contraction.\nOption C (Incorrect): The amount of contraction is distinctly different between full-thickness and split-thickness grafts, with FTSG having substantially less.\nOption D (Incorrect): This option is incorrect as only one type of graft has the least contraction.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Full-Thickness Skin Graft (FTSG) | Split-Thickness Skin Graft (STSG) |\n| :---------------- | :------------------------------- | :-------------------------------- |\n| **Contraction** | Least (5-10%) | Most (20-50%) |\n| **Take Rate** | Lower (more demanding bed) | Higher (less demanding bed) |\n| **Donor Site** | Requires primary closure | Heals by re-epithelialization |\n| **Aesthetic** | Better color/texture match | Poorer color/texture match |\n| **Durability** | More durable, less fragile | Less durable, more fragile |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: FTSG = Full Dermis, Full Resistance to Contraction, Full Aesthetic.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a full-thickness skin graft appears thicker and often requires meticulous defatting to ensure optimal take. It is typically harvested with a scalpel and has a more robust, less translucent appearance compared to a split-thickness graft, which is harvested with a dermatome and can be meshed to expand its surface area.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNot applicable for this fundamental concept in reconstructive surgery.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Full thickness | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Split thickness | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Both have equal contraction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | All of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
