  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Listen and look first; labs come second.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, History and examination. This is the most fundamental and universally helpful step in evaluating any patient before an operative procedure, as it guides all subsequent decisions and investigations.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA thorough history and physical examination allows the surgeon and anesthesiologist to identify existing comorbidities, assess functional status, uncover potential risk factors for complications, and establish a baseline for post-operative comparison. It is crucial for risk stratification and tailoring the pre-operative workup to the individual patient's needs, rather than relying on a 'one-size-fits-all' approach. This comprehensive initial assessment is paramount for patient safety and optimizing surgical outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): A Chest X-ray is not routinely indicated for all patients; it is reserved for those with pulmonary symptoms, significant cardiac disease, or specific high-risk surgeries. \nOption C (Incorrect): An ECG is not a routine pre-operative test for all patients; it is typically indicated for patients with known cardiac disease, significant risk factors, or those undergoing high-risk procedures. \nOption D (Incorrect): Liver function tests are not routinely performed pre-operatively unless there is a history of liver disease, symptoms suggestive of hepatic dysfunction, or use of hepatotoxic medications. \nOption E (Incorrect): Renal function tests are not routine for all patients; they are indicated for those with a history of kidney disease, hypertension, diabetes, or use of nephrotoxic medications.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Pre-operative Study | Routine for all? | Primary Indication |\n|---|---|---|\n| History & Examination | Yes | All patients, cornerstone of assessment |\n| Chest X-ray | No | Pulmonary symptoms, cardiac disease, high-risk surgery |\n| ECG | No | Cardiac risk factors, known cardiac disease, high-risk surgery |\n| LFTs/RFTs | No | History of hepatic/renal disease, specific medications, symptoms |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: History and physical exam is the cornerstone of pre-operative assessment.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThe question does not contain an image. However, if a Chest X-ray were indicated, one might look for signs of cardiomegaly, pulmonary edema, effusions, or infiltrates that could impact anesthetic management or surgical recovery.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Anesthesiologists (ASA) 2012 Practice Advisory for Preanesthesia Evaluation recommends a focused history and physical examination as the primary assessment for all patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | History and examination | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Chester X-ray | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | ECG | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Liver function test | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Renal function test | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
