  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Classify wounds by bugs, not by bumps!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, \"Lacerated wound,\" because surgical wound classifications categorize wounds by bacterial contamination level and infection risk, not by the mechanism of injury. Lacerated wound describes a type of traumatic injury, not a standard surgical wound classification.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSurgical wound classification is a critical component of surgical practice, guiding decisions on antibiotic prophylaxis, wound closure, and postoperative care. The four main categories—Clean, Clean-Contaminated, Contaminated, and Dirty-Infected—reflect a progressive increase in bacterial load and, consequently, the risk of surgical site infection. This standardized system allows surgeons to assess risk, communicate effectively, and implement appropriate infection prevention strategies, ultimately improving patient outcomes and reducing morbidity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"Clean wound\" is a primary classification for surgical wounds with minimal infection risk, typically involving non-penetrating procedures.\nOption B (Incorrect): \"Clean contaminated wound\" is a primary classification for surgical wounds involving controlled entry into contaminated tracts like the GI, GU, or respiratory systems.\nOption C (Incorrect): \"Dirty infected wound\" is a primary classification for surgical wounds with pre-existing infection, pus, or devitalized tissue.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Classification | Description | Infection Rate | Example |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Clean | Uninfected, no inflammation, no entry into tracts | 1-2% | Hernia repair, thyroidectomy |\n| Clean-Contaminated | Controlled entry into tracts, minor technique break | 3-7% | Cholecystectomy, elective colon resection |\n| Contaminated | Gross spillage from tracts, major technique break, fresh trauma | 10-17% | Appendectomy for ruptured appendix, major spillage during bowel surgery |\n| Dirty-Infected | Pre-existing infection, pus, devitalized tissue | >27% | Incision and drainage of abscess, debridement of necrotic tissue |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Surgical wound classification predicts infection risk, not injury type.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the operating room, a \"clean\" wound appears healthy with minimal tissue trauma and no signs of infection. Conversely, a \"dirty infected\" wound would visibly show pus, erythema, and devitalized tissue, often necessitating extensive debridement and potentially delayed primary closure.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCenters for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) Guideline for the Prevention of Surgical Site Infection (2017). It provides comprehensive recommendations for surgical wound classification and infection prevention strategies.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Clean wound | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Clean contaminated wound | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Dirty infected wound | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lacerated wound | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
