  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Feed the malnourished, but don't drown them in calories!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 30 kcal/kg body weight/day. This caloric intake is an appropriate starting point for nutritional support in a severely malnourished patient with esophageal carcinoma, aiming for repletion without immediately risking severe refeeding syndrome.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMalnourished patients, especially those with cancer, have increased metabolic demands due to the disease process and the need for tissue repair and repletion. A general guideline for nutritional repletion in non-critically ill, malnourished adults is typically 25-30 kcal/kg/day. This level provides sufficient energy to reverse catabolism, promote anabolism, and support immune function and wound healing, without overwhelming the metabolic system, which could lead to refeeding syndrome if initiated too aggressively.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 1 kcal/kg/day is grossly insufficient for any adult, let alone a malnourished cancer patient, and would lead to further catabolism.\nOption B (Incorrect): 5 kcal/kg/day is still far too low for nutritional repletion and would not meet the patient's metabolic needs.\nOption C (Incorrect): 15 kcal/kg/day is likely insufficient for significant repletion in a severely malnourished patient with cancer, who has increased metabolic needs. This might be an initial cautious starting point for patients at very high risk of refeeding syndrome, but not a general repletion target.\nOption E (Incorrect): 100 kcal/kg/day is dangerously high. This level of intake would almost certainly lead to severe refeeding syndrome, characterized by profound electrolyte shifts (hypophosphatemia, hypokalemia, hypomagnesemia), fluid overload, and cardiac/respiratory compromise.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nutritional State/Condition | Caloric Intake (kcal/kg/day) | Notes |\n| :-------------------------- | :--------------------------- | :---- |\n| Maintenance (healthy adult) | 20-25                        | Basal metabolic needs |\n| Moderate Stress/Repletion   | 25-30                        | Malnourished, post-op, cancer |\n| Severe Stress/Critical Illness | 30-35 (often lower initially) | Trauma, sepsis, burns; avoid overfeeding |\n| Refeeding Syndrome (initial) | 10-15 (gradual increase)     | Start low, go slow, monitor electrolytes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For malnourished patients, aim for 25-30 kcal/kg/day, but 'start low, go slow' if refeeding risk is high.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (CT, PET) would show the extent of the esophageal carcinoma, potential metastases, and signs of cachexia (muscle wasting, reduced fat stores). Endoscopy would visualize the tumor directly. Intraoperatively, one might observe a friable, obstructive tumor and signs of severe malnutrition like poor tissue quality and muscle atrophy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASPEN Guidelines for the Provision and Assessment of Nutrition Support Therapy in the Adult Cancer Patient (2017) recommend 25-30 kcal/kg/day for malnourished cancer patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 1 kcal/kg body weight / day | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 5 kcal/ kg body weight/ day | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 15 kcal/ kg body weight/ day | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 30 kcal/ kg body weight / day | ✅ Correct |\n| E | 100 kcal/ kg body weight/ day | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
