  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let a submandibular stone stone your patient's mealtime!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption A is correct because submandibular duct stones, especially those palpable in the distal duct, are typically removed transorally. This approach involves an incision in the floor of the mouth to directly access Wharton's duct and extract the calculus.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSialolithiasis most commonly affects the submandibular gland (80-90%), with stones frequently lodging in Wharton's duct. For stones palpable in the distal duct, a transoral sialolithotomy is the preferred surgical approach. This involves a small incision in the floor of the mouth, often with marsupialization of the duct, to extract the stone while preserving gland function. This technique leverages the superficial anatomical location of the distal submandibular duct, making it a minimally invasive and effective treatment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Submandibular stones *within the gland parenchyma* typically necessitate submandibular gland excision (sialoadenectomy) due to the complex anatomy and high recurrence rates if only the stone is removed. An incision in the neck is used for gland excision, not just stone extraction from within the gland.\nOption C (Incorrect): Submandibular calculi are significantly more common (80-90%) than parotid calculi (10-20%). This is attributed to the longer, tortuous, and upward-sloping Wharton's duct, and the higher mucin content and alkalinity of submandibular saliva.\nOption D (Incorrect): A parotid duct stone (sialolith) primarily causes obstructive symptoms like pain and swelling, especially during meals, and can lead to recurrent sialadenitis. While chronic obstruction can lead to ductal dilation, it does not typically cause true cysts of the parotid gland parenchyma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Submandibular Gland Sialolithiasis | Parotid Gland Sialolithiasis |\n| :------------------ | :--------------------------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Prevalence** | Most common (80-90% of all salivary stones) | Less common (10-20% of all salivary stones) |\n| **Duct Anatomy** | Wharton's duct: long, tortuous, upward-sloping, alkaline saliva | Stensen's duct: shorter, straighter, acidic saliva |\n| **Stone Location** | Often in duct (distal most common), less often in gland | More often in duct, sometimes in gland |\n| **Transoral Tx** | Common for distal duct stones (sialolithotomy) | Less common, often requires endoscopic or external approaches |\n| **Gland Excision** | Sialoadenectomy for large intraparenchymal stones or recurrent disease | Parotidectomy (superficial) for intraparenchymal stones or recurrent disease |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Submandibular duct stones are often transorally accessible; gland stones require excision.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT without contrast is gold standard, US can be useful), a submandibular duct stone appears as a hyperdense focus within Wharton's duct, often causing ductal dilation proximal to the obstruction. Intraoperatively, a palpable stone in the floor of the mouth can be milked anteriorly, and a small incision made directly over it, often with a stay suture placed posterior to the stone to prevent migration.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology—Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Sialolithiasis (2019). This guideline recommends transoral sialolithotomy for accessible submandibular duct stones and considers sialoendoscopy or gland excision for more complex cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Submandibular stones in the duct are removed via the floor of the mouth | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Submandibular stones in the gland are extracted from the gland through an i | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Parotid calculi are more common than submandibular calculi | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | A parotid duct stone causes cysts of parotid | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
