  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 First-degree burns? Think sunburn, not burn unit.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A. This question asks to identify the false statement regarding burn patients. First-degree burns are superficial and typically do not require admission to a specialized burn unit, making statement A incorrect and thus the correct answer to the 'except' question.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFirst-degree burns, also known as superficial burns, involve only the epidermis. They present with redness, pain, and no blistering, similar to a sunburn. These burns heal spontaneously within a few days without scarring and can usually be managed with outpatient care, pain relief, and moisturizing. Admission to a burn unit is reserved for more severe burns, such as partial-thickness burns over a significant body surface area, full-thickness burns, burns involving critical areas (face, hands, feet, perineum, major joints), electrical or chemical burns, or burns with associated trauma or comorbidities.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Pain relief is absolutely essential for all burn patients, regardless of burn depth, as burns are inherently painful injuries.\nOption C (Incorrect): A 40% total body surface area (TBSA) burn is considered a major burn and unequivocally requires admission to a specialized burn unit for comprehensive management, fluid resuscitation, and wound care.\nOption D (Incorrect): Tetanus prophylaxis (ATS or Td/TIG) is crucial for all burn patients due to the high risk of tetanus infection in contaminated burn wounds.\nOption E (Incorrect): Third-degree (full-thickness) burns destroy nerve endings in the affected area, rendering the center of the burn wound insensate and painless, although the surrounding partial-thickness areas may still be painful.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Burn Degree | Depth | Appearance | Pain | Healing | Burn Unit Admission |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| First | Epidermis | Red, dry, no blisters | Painful | 3-6 days, no scar | No |\n| Second (Superficial Partial) | Epidermis + superficial dermis | Red, moist, blisters | Very painful | 7-21 days, minimal scar | Possible, depending on TBSA/location |\n| Second (Deep Partial) | Epidermis + deep dermis | Red/white, wet/dry, blisters | Less painful, pressure sensation | 3 weeks - months, scar | Yes |\n| Third (Full Thickness) | Epidermis + dermis + subcutaneous tissue | White, leathery, charred, dry | Painless (center) | Requires grafting, significant scar | Yes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: First-degree burns are superficial, painful, and do not require burn unit admission.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nVisual assessment is key for burn depth and extent. First-degree burns appear red and blanch with pressure, without blistering. No specific imaging is typically used for diagnosis of burn depth.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Burn Association (ABA) Practice Guidelines for Burn Care (latest edition). These guidelines provide criteria for burn center referral and admission.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | All patients with first burn degree require admission to the burn unite | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Pain relief is essential | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 40% burn must be admitted to the burn unite | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | ATS must be given to all patients | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Third degree burn is painless | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
