  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Left node, bad news: Troisier's sign, a cancer clue.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nTroisier's sign, often misspelled as Trosier's, refers to the enlargement of the left supraclavicular lymph node. This finding is a critical indicator of metastatic malignancy, particularly from abdominal or pelvic primary cancers.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe lymphatic drainage from most abdominal and pelvic organs eventually converges into the thoracic duct, which empties into the left subclavian vein. Before entering the vein, lymph can drain into the supraclavicular lymph nodes, with the left side being the primary recipient due to the thoracic duct's termination. Therefore, an enlarged left supraclavicular node (Virchow's node) suggests retrograde lymphatic spread from an underlying malignancy, making it a crucial diagnostic clue for advanced cancer.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Right supraclavicular lymph node enlargement is less commonly associated with abdominal or pelvic malignancies. While possible, it typically suggests malignancy in the right lung, esophagus, or head and neck region.\nOption C (Incorrect): Carpopedal spasm is Trousseau's sign of latent tetany, which indicates hypocalcemia, not a metastatic lymph node.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Sign/Node | Description | Clinical Significance | Primary Association |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Troisier's Sign (Virchow's Node) | Enlarged left supraclavicular lymph node | Metastatic malignancy (abdominal/pelvic) | Gastric, pancreatic, ovarian cancer |\n| Trousseau's Sign of Latent Tetany | Carpopedal spasm induced by sphygmomanometer cuff | Hypocalcemia | Hypoparathyroidism, vitamin D deficiency |\n| Sister Mary Joseph Nodule | Periumbilical nodule | Metastatic malignancy (abdominal/pelvic) | Gastric, pancreatic, ovarian, colon cancer |\n| Irish Node | Enlarged anterior axillary lymph node (left) | Metastatic gastric cancer | Gastric cancer |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Left supraclavicular node (Troisier's/Virchow's) = abdominal cancer until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/PET), an enlarged, often hypermetabolic, left supraclavicular lymph node would be identified. Intraoperatively, this node would appear firm, fixed, and potentially matted, requiring biopsy for definitive diagnosis of metastatic disease.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines (2023) for Gastric Cancer recommend thorough physical examination, including lymph node assessment, as part of initial staging workup.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Right supraclavicular lymph node enlargement | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Left supraclavicular lymph node enlargement | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Carpopedal spasm | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
