  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Everted edge on tongue? Think cancer, biopsy is mandatory.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Malignant ulcer. An everted edge is a classic clinical sign highly suggestive of an infiltrative malignant process, particularly squamous cell carcinoma, which is the most common malignancy of the tongue.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMalignant ulcers, especially squamous cell carcinomas, are characterized by their infiltrative growth pattern. As the tumor cells proliferate and invade surrounding tissues, they push the tissue outwards, creating a raised, indurated, and often everted or rolled edge. This contrasts with the punched-out or undermined appearance of other ulcer types. The central portion of a malignant ulcer may be necrotic or fungating, contributing to its irregular and often non-healing nature, driven by uncontrolled cellular proliferation and angiogenesis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Aphthous ulcer) (Incorrect): Aphthous ulcers are typically painful, shallow, well-demarcated, and have a red halo, but do not exhibit everted edges.\nOption B (Tuberculosis ulcer) (Incorrect): Tuberculous ulcers often have undermined or 'mouse-eaten' edges, are typically irregular, and can be painful, but not everted.\nOption D (Dental ulcer) (Incorrect): Dental or traumatic ulcers are usually caused by mechanical irritation (e.g., sharp tooth, denture) and present with an irregular, often inflamed border, but lack the characteristic everted edge of malignancy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Ulcer Type | Edge Characteristic | Pain Level | Other Features |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Malignant | Everted, indurated, rolled | Variable (often late) | Non-healing, fungating, central necrosis |\n| Aphthous | Well-demarcated, flat | High | Small, shallow, red halo, recurrent |\n| Tuberculous | Undermined, irregular | Moderate to High | 'Mouse-eaten' appearance, often chronic |\n| Traumatic (Dental) | Irregular, inflamed | Moderate to High | Associated with local irritant, resolves with removal of irritant |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: An everted edge on a tongue ulcer is highly suspicious for malignancy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn clinical examination, a malignant tongue ulcer will appear as an indurated lesion with raised, rolled, or everted edges, often with a central crater or fungating mass. Intraoperatively, the lesion will feel firm and fixed to underlying structures, and a biopsy is crucial for definitive diagnosis, typically revealing squamous cell carcinoma.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Head and Neck Cancers (Version 1.2024) recommend prompt biopsy and imaging (e.g., MRI, CT) for suspicious oral lesions, including those with everted edges, to stage and guide treatment for oral cavity squamous cell carcinoma.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Aphatus ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Tuberculosis ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Malignant ulcer | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Dental ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
