  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Nodular BCC: The pearly, ulcerated king of skin cancer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption A, \"Rodent ulcer,\" is the correct answer. This term is a classic descriptive name for nodular basal cell carcinoma, which is indeed the most prevalent subtype of BCC, accounting for the majority of cases.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNodular basal cell carcinoma (BCC) is the most common form, representing 50-80% of all BCCs. It typically presents as a pearly papule or nodule with rolled borders and often visible telangiectasias. The term \"rodent ulcer\" specifically refers to the characteristic central ulceration that can develop within these lesions, which, if left untreated, can slowly enlarge and cause significant local tissue destruction, resembling the gnawing damage of a rodent.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Turhan ulce) (Incorrect): This is not a recognized medical term or classification for basal cell carcinoma.\nOption C (Pigment type) (Incorrect): Pigmented BCC is a variant of other BCC subtypes (like nodular or superficial) where melanin is present, giving it a darker appearance. While common, it is not the most common *type* overall; nodular BCC is more prevalent.\nOption D (Field free type) (Incorrect): This is not a recognized classification or subtype of basal cell carcinoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| BCC Subtype | Description | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Nodular (Rodent Ulcer)** | Most common type (50-80%), often on head/neck. | Pearly papule/nodule, rolled borders, telangiectasias, central ulceration. |\n| Superficial | Second most common (15-30%), often on trunk/extremities. | Erythematous, scaly patch, often mistaken for eczema/psoriasis. |\n| Pigmented | Variant of nodular/superficial. | Contains melanin, appears dark brown/black, can mimic melanoma. |\n| Morpheaphorm/Sclerosing | Aggressive, infiltrative growth, often on face. | Scar-like plaque, ill-defined borders, difficult to delineate clinically. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Nodular BCC, also known as Rodent Ulcer, is the most common type.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nClinically, a nodular BCC appears as a pearly papule or nodule with rolled borders and often central ulceration and telangiectasias. Intraoperatively, it typically has a firm, well-defined but often friable texture, and its borders may be more extensive than clinically apparent.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Basal Cell and Squamous Cell Skin Cancers (2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis, staging, and treatment of BCC, emphasizing surgical excision as the primary treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Rodent ulcer | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Turhan ulce | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pigment type | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Field free type | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
