  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Adult intussusception: rare, always suspect a lead point!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. Ileocolic intussusception is indeed not a common cause of small bowel obstruction (SBO) in adults. While intussusception is a significant cause of SBO in children, adult intussusception is rare and typically has a pathological lead point, making it an uncommon primary cause of SBO.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe vast majority of adult SBOs are caused by postoperative adhesions, followed by incarcerated hernias and malignancies. These three etiologies account for over 75% of all adult SBO cases. Intussusception, particularly the ileocolic type, is far less frequent in adults, often representing only 1-5% of adult SBOs, and usually indicates an underlying pathology like a tumor or polyp acting as a lead point, rather than being idiopathic as in children.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Hernias (inguinal, femoral, incisional) are a very common cause of SBO in adults, second only to adhesions.\nOption B (Incorrect): Tumors, both primary and metastatic, are a significant cause of SBO in adults, often presenting as a lead point or extrinsic compression.\nOption C (Incorrect): Volvulus, particularly of the small bowel, can occur in adults, though less frequently than adhesions or hernias, and is a recognized cause of SBO.\nOption D (Incorrect): Adhesions, usually postoperative, are the single most common cause of SBO in adults, accounting for 60-70% of cases.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause | Adults (Common) | Children (Common) |\n| :-------------------- | :---------------- | :---------------- |\n| Adhesions             | Yes (most common) | No                |\n| Hernia                | Yes (2nd most common) | No                |\n| Tumor                 | Yes (3rd most common) | No                |\n| Intussusception       | No (rare, lead point) | Yes (idiopathic)  |\n| Volvulus              | Yes (less common) | Yes (midgut)      |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think 'A-H-T' for adult SBO causes: Adhesions, Hernia, Tumor.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, SBO typically shows dilated proximal bowel loops with air-fluid levels and a transition point. Ileocolic intussusception would appear as a 'target sign' or 'sausage-shaped mass' on cross-sectional imaging, where one segment of bowel telescopes into another, often with a lead point visible in adults.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Small Bowel Obstruction (2017) recommends initial non-operative management for most adhesive SBOs.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hernia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Tumor | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Volvulus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Adhesions | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | ileocolic intussusception | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
