  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Lump and blood, think haemorrhoid, not dread!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Haemorrhoids. This diagnosis is strongly supported by the classic presentation of bright red blood per rectum (BRBPR) and a prolapsing 'lump' during straining, especially in a young patient.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHaemorrhoids are engorged vascular cushions within the anal canal. Internal haemorrhoids, located above the dentate line, are typically painless but can bleed (manifesting as bright red blood on paper or in the pan) and prolapse with straining, leading to the sensation of a 'lump coming down.' The bright red color of the blood indicates a fresh, lower gastrointestinal source, consistent with haemorrhoidal bleeding.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Colonic carcinoma): Incorrect. While colon cancer can cause BRBPR, it's less likely in a young man presenting with a prolapsing lump. Carcinoma often presents with changes in bowel habits, weight loss, or occult blood, and is more common in older age groups.\nOption B (Fissure): Incorrect. Anal fissures cause severe pain during and after defecation, often with streaks of bright red blood, but typically do not present with a 'lump come down.'\nOption D (Diverticular disease): Incorrect. Diverticular bleeding is usually painless and can be profuse, but it's more common in older patients and does not typically present with a prolapsing lump.\nOption E (Ulcerative colitis): Incorrect. Ulcerative colitis causes bloody diarrhea, abdominal pain, and tenesmus, but not typically a prolapsing lump. It is an inflammatory condition, not a structural prolapse.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Symptoms | Prolapsing Lump | Pain |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Haemorrhoids | BRBPR, lump with straining | Yes | Usually none (unless thrombosed) |\n| Anal Fissure | Severe pain with defecation, streaks of BRBPR | No | Yes |\n| Colonic Carcinoma | BRBPR, change in bowel habits, weight loss, occult blood | No | Variable |\n| Diverticular Bleeding | Painless, profuse BRBPR | No | No |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: BRBPR + prolapsing lump = Haemorrhoids until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn digital rectal examination and anoscopy, prolapsed internal haemorrhoids would be visible or palpable, especially during straining. No specific imaging is typically required for diagnosis, but colonoscopy may be considered to rule out other pathologies, particularly in older patients or those with atypical symptoms.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Hemorrhoids (2018). It recommends initial conservative management with dietary fiber, fluid intake, and topical agents, reserving surgical intervention for higher-grade or refractory cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Colonic carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Fissure | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Haemorrhoids | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Diverticular disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Ulcerative colitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
