  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the gallbladder's a balloon, but the patient's not in pain, malignancy's the villain.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Courvoisier's law. This law states that in the presence of jaundice, a palpable, non-tender gallbladder is unlikely to be caused by gallstones and is more likely due to a malignant obstruction of the common bile duct, such as pancreatic head cancer. The patient's presentation of painless jaundice with a RUQ mass fits this description perfectly.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCourvoisier's law is a crucial clinical observation in surgical oncology. When a gallstone obstructs the common bile duct, the gallbladder has usually been inflamed and fibrotic over time, preventing it from distending. In contrast, a malignant obstruction (e.g., pancreatic head adenocarcinoma) typically occurs in a previously healthy gallbladder, allowing it to distend significantly and become palpable. The \"pain-free\" aspect further supports a malignant cause over an inflammatory one.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Trousseau's sign) (Incorrect): Trousseau's sign of malignancy refers to migratory thrombophlebitis, a paraneoplastic syndrome, not a physical exam finding for obstructive jaundice.\nOption B (Homans' sign) (Incorrect): Homans' sign is calf pain on dorsiflexion of the foot, associated with deep vein thrombosis (DVT), and is not relevant to this patient's presentation.\nOption D (Rovsing's sign) (Incorrect): Rovsing's sign is pain in the right lower quadrant upon palpation of the left lower quadrant, indicative of appendicitis, which is unrelated to the patient's symptoms.\nOption E (Murphy's sign) (Incorrect): Murphy's sign is inspiratory arrest during palpation of the right upper quadrant, characteristic of acute cholecystitis, which typically presents with pain, not painless jaundice.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Sign/Law | Clinical Presentation | Implication |\n|---|---|---|\n| Courvoisier's Law | Painless jaundice + palpable, non-tender gallbladder | Malignant obstruction (e.g., pancreatic head cancer) |\n| Murphy's Sign | RUQ pain + inspiratory arrest on palpation | Acute cholecystitis |\n| Charcot's Triad | RUQ pain, fever, jaundice | Acute cholangitis |\n| Trousseau's Sign of Malignancy | Migratory thrombophlebitis | Paraneoplastic syndrome, often associated with pancreatic cancer |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Painless jaundice + palpable gallbladder = Courvoisier's Law, think malignancy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (e.g., ultrasound, CT, MRI/MRCP) would likely show a dilated common bile duct, an enlarged gallbladder, and a mass in the head of the pancreas or distal common bile duct. Intraoperatively, a distended, thin-walled gallbladder would be observed, along with a tumor obstructing the bile duct.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Pancreatic Adenocarcinoma (2023). These guidelines recommend imaging and biopsy for suspected pancreatic head masses causing obstructive jaundice.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Trousseau's sign | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Homans' sign | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Courvoisier's law | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Rovsing's sign | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Murphy's sign | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
