  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Lesser curvature ulcers: Don't just treat, *biopsy*!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Lesser curvature. This anatomical location is the most frequent site for gastric ulcer formation, and consequently, it is where gastric ulcers are most commonly found to be malignant or to undergo malignant transformation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe lesser curvature of the stomach is particularly vulnerable to ulceration due to its direct exposure to gastric acid and pepsin, and its relatively less robust blood supply compared to other gastric regions. Chronic inflammation, cellular changes like intestinal metaplasia, and the high incidence of ulcers in this area collectively contribute to its elevated risk for developing gastric adenocarcinoma. Therefore, any ulcer found here warrants a high index of suspicion for malignancy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): While ulcers on the greater curvature are rare, when they do occur, they have a very high likelihood of being malignant from the outset, rather than transforming. However, the overall incidence of ulcers here is low, making it less common for a malignant ulcer to be found here compared to the lesser curvature.\nOption C (Incorrect): The antrum is a common site for gastric ulcers, often associated with H. pylori infection or NSAID use. However, the lesser curvature still surpasses the antrum in terms of the overall frequency of malignant ulcers.\nOption D (Incorrect): The pylorus is a less common site for gastric ulcers compared to the lesser curvature or antrum, and thus, malignant ulcers are also less frequently found here.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Lesser Curvature | Greater Curvature | Antrum |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Ulcer Frequency | Most Common | Least Common | Common |\n| Malignancy Risk (if ulcer present) | Highest (due to frequency) | High (often primary malignancy) | Moderate |\n| Predisposing Factors | Acid exposure, poorer blood supply | Often primary malignancy | H. pylori, NSAIDs |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Lesser curvature ulcers are the most common site for gastric malignancy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopic evaluation of a malignant gastric ulcer on the lesser curvature would typically reveal an irregular, raised, or nodular lesion with friable tissue, often with heaped-up margins. Multiple biopsies from the ulcer base and margins are essential for histological diagnosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Gastric Cancer 2023: Recommend endoscopic evaluation with biopsy of all gastric ulcers, emphasizing the higher incidence of malignancy in ulcers located on the lesser curvature, necessitating thorough sampling.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lesser curvature. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Greater curvature. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Antrum. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | pylorus | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
