  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pyloric stenosis: Vomit acid, get alkalosis!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Metabolic acidosis. Pyloric stenosis is characterized by gastric outlet obstruction leading to persistent vomiting, which results in a specific electrolyte imbalance, making metabolic acidosis an incorrect feature.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInfantile hypertrophic pyloric stenosis involves hypertrophy of the pyloric muscle, causing gastric outlet obstruction. The hallmark clinical feature is non-bilious, projectile vomiting. This persistent loss of gastric contents, rich in hydrochloric acid (HCl), leads to a characteristic hypochloremic, hypokalemic metabolic alkalosis. The body attempts to compensate by retaining bicarbonate and excreting potassium and hydrogen ions in the urine, further exacerbating the alkalosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Abdominal lump) (Incorrect): A palpable 'olive' mass in the epigastrium is a classic physical finding in pyloric stenosis, representing the hypertrophied pylorus.\nOption B (Constipation) (Incorrect): Due to persistent vomiting and inability to retain feeds, infants with pyloric stenosis often have scant stool output or constipation.\nOption C (Weight loss) (Incorrect): Inability to absorb nutrients due to persistent vomiting inevitably leads to significant weight loss and failure to thrive.\nOption D (Metabolic acidosis) (Correct): Pyloric stenosis causes a loss of gastric acid, leading to hypochloremic, hypokalemic metabolic alkalosis, not acidosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Pyloric Stenosis | Distal Intestinal Obstruction |\n|---|---|---|\n| Vomiting Type | Non-bilious, projectile | Bilious (if distal to ampulla of Vater) |\n| Electrolyte Imbalance | Hypochloremic, hypokalemic metabolic alkalosis | Variable, often metabolic acidosis if significant fluid loss |\n| Abdominal Exam | Palpable 'olive' mass | Distension, tenderness, variable masses |\n| Stool | Scant/Constipation | Variable, may have meconium plug or no stool |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pyloric stenosis = projectile vomit + olive mass + metabolic alkalosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound is the diagnostic imaging modality of choice, revealing a thickened pyloric muscle (>3-4 mm) and an elongated pyloric channel (>14-17 mm), often described as the 'target sign' or 'cervix sign' in transverse view.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis (2017) recommends ultrasound as the primary diagnostic tool.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Abdominal lump | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Constipation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Weight loss | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Metabolic acidosis | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
