  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pyloric stenosis: Vomit, alkalosis, olive, fix it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. This answer is correct because congenital hypertrophic pyloric stenosis (CHPS) typically manifests in infants between 2 weeks and 3 months of age, with a peak incidence around 3-6 weeks. Option A accurately reflects this common presentation window.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCongenital hypertrophic pyloric stenosis involves hypertrophy and hyperplasia of the circular and longitudinal muscular layers of the pylorus, leading to a narrowed pyloric channel. This gastric outlet obstruction prevents food from passing into the duodenum, causing progressive, non-bilious, projectile vomiting. The hypertrophy is thought to be multifactorial, involving genetic predisposition and environmental factors, leading to the characteristic 'olive' mass palpable in the epigastrium.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Pyloric stenosis causes gastric outlet obstruction *proximal* to the ampulla of Vater, meaning bile does not enter the stomach to be vomited. Therefore, the vomiting is characteristically non-bilious.\nOption C (Incorrect): CHPS is significantly more common in male infants, with a male-to-female ratio of approximately 4:1. It is not common in female children.\nOption D (Incorrect): The persistent vomiting of gastric acid (hydrochloric acid) leads to a loss of hydrogen and chloride ions. This results in a characteristic hypochloremic, hypokalemic metabolic *alkalosis*, not acidosis, as the body attempts to compensate for the acid loss.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Congenital Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis | Malrotation with Volvulus | Duodenal Atresia |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Onset** | 2-8 weeks (peak 3-6 weeks) | First month of life (often first week) | First 24-48 hours of life |\n| **Vomiting** | Non-bilious, projectile | Bilious, often sudden onset | Bilious (usually), non-projectile |\n| **Abdominal Exam** | Palpable 'olive' mass | Distension, tenderness (late) | Scaphoid abdomen (early), distension (late) |\n| **Metabolic Derangement** | Hypochloremic, hypokalemic metabolic alkalosis | Variable, often dehydration/shock | Dehydration, electrolyte imbalance |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Non-bilious projectile vomiting in a 4-week-old is pyloric stenosis until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, the pyloric muscle thickness will be >3-4 mm, and the pyloric channel length will be >14-17 mm. Intraoperatively, a Ramstedt pyloromyotomy involves incising the hypertrophied circular muscle down to the submucosa, allowing the mucosa to bulge through the incision.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Pediatric Surgical Association (APSA) guidelines emphasize early diagnosis and correction of electrolyte abnormalities prior to surgical pyloromyotomy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Present at 2-3 months of age | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Produce bilius vomiting | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Common in female children | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Produce hypochlorimic hypokalimic metabolic acidosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
