  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Gut arteries are visceral; iliacs are for your legs!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. The external iliac artery is primarily responsible for supplying the lower limbs and parts of the anterior abdominal wall, not the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Understanding the distinct vascular territories of the abdominal arteries is fundamental to surgical practice.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe gastrointestinal tract receives its primary arterial supply from three major unpaired branches of the abdominal aorta: the celiac artery, the superior mesenteric artery (SMA), and the inferior mesenteric artery (IMA). These arteries are specifically adapted to perfuse the foregut, midgut, and hindgut, respectively. In contrast, the external iliac artery branches off the common iliac artery and continues as the femoral artery, supplying structures entirely outside the GIT, such as the lower extremities and superficial abdominal wall.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The Superior mesenteric artery supplies the midgut, which includes the small intestine (jejunum, ileum), cecum, ascending colon, and proximal two-thirds of the transverse colon.\nOption B (Incorrect): The Inferior mesenteric artery supplies the hindgut, encompassing the distal one-third of the transverse colon, descending colon, sigmoid colon, and superior part of the rectum.\nOption C (Incorrect): The Celiac artery supplies the foregut, including the stomach, liver, spleen, pancreas, and the proximal duodenum.\nOption E (Incorrect): The Internal iliac artery supplies pelvic organs, including the distal rectum and anal canal, which are parts of the gastrointestinal tract.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Artery | GIT Region Supplied | Other Major Branches |\n|---|---|---|\n| Celiac Artery | Foregut (stomach, duodenum, liver, spleen, pancreas) | Hepatic, Splenic, Left Gastric |\n| Superior Mesenteric Artery | Midgut (duodenum to transverse colon) | Jejunal, Ileal, Ileocolic, Right Colic, Middle Colic |\n| Inferior Mesenteric Artery | Hindgut (distal transverse colon to upper anal canal) | Left Colic, Sigmoid, Superior Rectal |\n| External Iliac Artery | None (GIT) | Inferior Epigastric, Deep Circumflex Iliac, Femoral |\n| Internal Iliac Artery | Distal Rectum, Anal Canal | Superior Gluteal, Inferior Gluteal, Obturator, Pudendal |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Celiac, SMA, IMA feed the gut; Iliacs feed the legs and pelvis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT angiography, the celiac, SMA, and IMA can be clearly visualized originating from the aorta, branching to supply the bowel. The external iliac arteries are seen diverging laterally to supply the lower limbs, distinct from the visceral circulation. Intraoperatively, these vessels are identified by their anatomical position and the organs they perfuse.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Surgical Education and Training Guidelines (2023) emphasize foundational knowledge of abdominal vascular anatomy for all surgical residents.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Superior mesenterie artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Inferior mesenteric artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Celiac artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | External Iliac artery | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Internal iliac artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
