  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Sudden, severe pain + rigid belly = think perforation, act fast!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. Perforated ulcer. The patient's history of abdominal pain relieved by food/soda (classic for peptic ulcer disease) followed by acute onset of severe abdominal pain, vomiting, and a tender, rigid abdomen (peritonitis) is highly indicative of a perforated peptic ulcer.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA perforated peptic ulcer occurs when the ulcer erodes through the entire wall of the stomach or duodenum, leading to spillage of gastric or duodenal contents into the peritoneal cavity. This spillage causes chemical peritonitis, which rapidly progresses to bacterial peritonitis. The classic presentation includes sudden, severe, generalized abdominal pain, often described as 'knife-like,' accompanied by vomiting and signs of shock. On examination, the abdomen is typically rigid and board-like due to involuntary guarding, a hallmark of diffuse peritonitis, which aligns perfectly with the patient's presentation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Pyloric stenosis) (Incorrect): Pyloric stenosis causes gastric outlet obstruction, leading to chronic, non-bilious vomiting, epigastric fullness, and weight loss, not acute peritonitis with a rigid abdomen.\nOption B (Cancer stomach) (Incorrect): While stomach cancer can cause pain and vomiting, the initial symptom of pain relieved by food is less typical, and it usually presents with chronic symptoms like weight loss or early satiety, not an acute peritonitis unless it has perforated, which is less common than ulcer perforation.\nOption C (Bleeding ulcer) (Incorrect): A bleeding ulcer presents with signs of gastrointestinal hemorrhage, such as hematemesis (vomiting blood) or melena (black, tarry stools), and symptoms of hypovolemia, not acute peritonitis with a rigid abdomen.\nOption E (Penetrating ulcer) (Incorrect): A penetrating ulcer erodes into an adjacent organ (e.g., pancreas) and causes severe, constant pain, often radiating to the back. While serious, it typically does not cause generalized peritonitis with a rigid abdomen unless it subsequently perforates into the free peritoneal cavity.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication of PUD | Key Symptoms | Physical Exam Findings | Imaging Findings |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Perforation** | Sudden, severe, generalized abdominal pain; vomiting | Rigid, board-like abdomen; rebound tenderness | Free air under diaphragm on X-ray/CT |\n| **Bleeding** | Hematemesis, melena, weakness, dizziness | Tachycardia, hypotension, pallor | Endoscopy shows active bleeding/stigmata |\n| **Penetration** | Severe, constant pain (often radiating to back); less acute than perforation | Localized tenderness; sometimes palpable mass | CT shows ulcer extending into adjacent organ |\n| **Obstruction** | Post-prandial vomiting; early satiety; weight loss | Succussion splash; epigastric distension | Endoscopy/CT shows gastric outlet narrowing/dilation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute onset of severe abdominal pain with a rigid abdomen in a patient with ulcer history equals perforation until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, an upright chest X-ray or CT scan of the abdomen would typically show free air (pneumoperitoneum) under the diaphragm, which is pathognomonic for a perforated viscus. Intraoperatively, one would find gastric or duodenal contents in the peritoneal cavity and a visible perforation, usually on the anterior wall of the duodenum or stomach.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Perforated Peptic Ulcer (2020) recommend prompt diagnosis and emergency surgical repair (e.g., Graham patch) for most cases, along with appropriate resuscitation and antibiotic therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pyloric stenosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cancer stomach | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Bleeding ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Perforated ulcer | ✅ Correct |\n| E | penetrating ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
