  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the colon bleeds big, think diverticula first.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Diverticulosis. Diverticulosis is the most common cause of significant lower gastrointestinal bleeding (LGIB) in adults, accounting for approximately 30-50% of cases. The bleeding typically results from erosion of the vasa recta within the diverticular sac.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDiverticular bleeding occurs when the vasa recta, small arteries that penetrate the muscularis propria to supply the mucosa, become draped over the dome or neck of a diverticulum. Chronic injury from luminal contents or increased intraluminal pressure can lead to erosion and rupture of these vessels. This mechanism often results in painless, acute, and sometimes profuse arterial bleeding, which can be life-threatening.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Colonic cancer) (Incorrect): While colonic cancer can cause LGIB, it typically presents as chronic, occult, or intermittent bleeding, often leading to iron deficiency anemia, and is less common as a cause of acute, significant LGIB compared to diverticulosis.\nOption C (Anal fissure) (Incorrect): Anal fissures cause bright red blood per rectum, usually in small amounts, associated with defecation and pain, and are not considered a cause of significant LGIB requiring hospitalization or transfusion.\nOption D (Angiodysplasia) (Incorrect): Angiodysplasia is a common cause of LGIB, particularly in the elderly and those with specific comorbidities, but it is less prevalent than diverticulosis as the overall leading cause of significant LGIB.\nOption E (Hemorrhoid) (Incorrect): Hemorrhoids are the most common cause of any bright red blood per rectum, but the bleeding is typically small volume, self-limiting, and rarely leads to hemodynamic instability, distinguishing it from the significant bleeding seen in diverticulosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause | Typical Presentation | Bleeding Severity | Location |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Diverticulosis | Painless, acute, often profuse | Moderate to severe | Colon (right colon diverticula bleed more often) |\n| Angiodysplasia | Painless, recurrent, often occult or intermittent | Mild to moderate | Right colon most common |\n| Hemorrhoids | Bright red blood per rectum, with defecation, often painless | Mild, self-limiting | Anorectal junction |\n| Colonic Cancer | Occult, chronic, intermittent, change in bowel habits | Mild to moderate, often iron deficiency anemia | Any part of colon |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Diverticulosis is the most common cause of significant lower GI bleeding.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn colonoscopy, diverticula appear as outpouchings, sometimes with stigmata of recent hemorrhage (e.g., adherent clot, visible vessel). CT angiography can detect active extravasation of contrast in brisk bleeding. Nuclear scintigraphy can localize slower bleeding. Angiography can both localize and embolize the bleeding vessel.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guideline on Management of Patients With Acute Lower Gastrointestinal Bleeding (2016). This guideline recommends early colonoscopy after adequate bowel preparation for diagnosis and therapeutic intervention in patients with acute LGIB.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Colonic cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Diverticulosis | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Anal fissure | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Angiodysplasia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Hemorrhoid | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) (B)** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
