  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Primary peritonitis: spontaneous, not source-less.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, indicating that the statement \"Primary peritonitis has no documented source of contamination\" is false. Primary peritonitis, while not having an obvious surgical source, does have a source of contamination, typically hematogenous or transmural bacterial translocation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPeritonitis is broadly classified into primary, secondary, and tertiary types. Primary peritonitis, also known as spontaneous bacterial peritonitis (SBP), is characterized by bacterial infection of the peritoneal cavity without an obvious intra-abdominal source, commonly seen in patients with cirrhosis and ascites where bacteria translocate from the gut. Secondary peritonitis, the most common form, results from contamination due to a breach in the gastrointestinal or genitourinary tract (e.g., perforated appendicitis, diverticulitis). Tertiary peritonitis is a persistent or recurrent infection after adequate treatment of primary or secondary peritonitis, often involving resistant organisms or immunocompromised hosts. Understanding these distinctions is crucial for appropriate diagnosis and management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (True Statement): Peritonitis is indeed defined as inflammation of the peritoneum, often in response to infection or irritation.\nOption B (True Statement): The vast majority of surgical peritonitis cases (e.g., from perforated appendicitis, diverticulitis, or bowel ischemia) are caused by bacterial contamination from the gastrointestinal tract.\nOption D (True Statement): Tuberculous peritonitis is a chronic form of peritonitis that can present with various clinical patterns, including the \"wet\" type with significant ascites or the \"dry\" type characterized by adhesions and peritoneal nodules without prominent ascites.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Peritonitis | Source of Contamination | Typical Clinical Scenario |\n|--------------------|-------------------------|---------------------------|\n| Primary (SBP)      | Hematogenous/Transmural | Cirrhosis with ascites    |\n| Secondary          | Intra-abdominal breach  | Perforated viscus         |\n| Tertiary           | Persistent/Recurrent    | Immunocompromised, resistant organisms |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Primary peritonitis has a source, just not a surgical one.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (CT scan) for peritonitis often reveals free fluid, bowel wall thickening, inflammatory stranding, and sometimes free air (indicating perforation). Intraoperatively, one would observe purulent exudate, fibrin deposits, and inflamed peritoneal surfaces.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Peritonitis (2017) recommends tailored antibiotic therapy and source control based on the type and severity of peritonitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Peritonitis is defined as inflammation of the peritoneum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Most surgical peritonitis is secondary to bacterial contamination | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Primary peritonitis has no documented source of contamination | ✅ Correct |\n| D | T.B. peritonitis can be present with or without ascites | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) (C)** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
