  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pyloric stenosis: Projectile vomit, olive-shaped mass, surgical fix!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis. This diagnosis perfectly aligns with the classic presentation of a 3-week-old male infant experiencing non-bilious projectile vomiting, which is pathognomonic for gastric outlet obstruction due to pyloric muscle hypertrophy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHypertrophic pyloric stenosis involves thickening of the pyloric muscle, leading to a narrowed gastric outlet. This obstruction prevents gastric contents from passing into the duodenum, causing the stomach to distend and eventually forcefully expel its contents as projectile, non-bilious vomit. The condition typically manifests between 2-8 weeks of age, with a higher incidence in first-born males, making the patient's age and gender highly suggestive.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Esophageal atresia) (Incorrect): This condition presents at birth with immediate feeding difficulties, choking, coughing, and respiratory distress, often with frothing at the mouth, not projectile vomiting at 3 weeks.\nOption B (Gastroesophageal reflux) (Incorrect): While common in infants, GER typically causes spitting up or non-projectile vomiting, often without the forceful, projectile nature seen in HPS, and usually responds to conservative measures.\nOption C (Duodenal atresia) (Incorrect): Duodenal atresia presents shortly after birth with bilious vomiting (due to obstruction distal to the ampulla of Vater) and is characterized by the \"double bubble\" sign on imaging, not non-bilious projectile vomiting at 3 weeks.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Age of Onset | Vomit Character | Associated Symptoms | Key Diagnostic |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis | 2-8 weeks | Non-bilious, projectile | Palpable olive, dehydration, weight loss | Pyloric ultrasound |\n| Duodenal Atresia | Birth | Bilious | Abdominal distension | \"Double bubble\" sign on X-ray |\n| Esophageal Atresia | Birth | Choking, coughing, frothing | Respiratory distress | Inability to pass NG tube |\n| GER | Infancy | Non-projectile, non-bilious | Spitting up, irritability | Clinical, pH probe (severe) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Non-bilious projectile vomiting in a 3-week-old male = Pyloric Stenosis until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, hypertrophic pyloric stenosis is diagnosed by measuring the pyloric muscle thickness (>3-4 mm) and pyloric channel length (>14-17 mm), often showing an elongated, narrowed pyloric channel.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis (2012). It recommends ultrasound as the primary diagnostic modality and pyloromyotomy as the definitive treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Esophageal atresia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Gastroesophageal reflux. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Duodenal atresia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hypertrophic pyloric stenosis. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Answer : D** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
