  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pyloric stenosis: Vomit acid, get alkalosis, fix electrolytes before you cut!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B because infantile hypertrophic pyloric stenosis (IHPS) is characterized by persistent, non-bilious vomiting, leading to significant loss of gastric acid and subsequent metabolic alkalosis, hypokalemia, and hypochloremia.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe repeated vomiting in IHPS results in a profound loss of hydrogen chloride (HCl) from the stomach, directly causing metabolic alkalosis. To compensate for volume depletion, the kidneys conserve sodium, often at the expense of potassium and hydrogen ions, leading to hypokalemia and paradoxical aciduria. The significant loss of chloride ions contributes to hypochloremia, which further impairs the kidney's ability to excrete bicarbonate and correct the alkalosis, perpetuating the metabolic derangement.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Metabolic acidosis is incorrect as the primary loss is gastric acid (HCl), leading to alkalosis, not acidosis.\nOption C (Incorrect): Metabolic acidosis is incorrect, and hypernatremia is not typically seen; rather, hyponatremia can occur due to free water intake or excessive ADH release in response to hypovolemia, though hypochloremia is correct.\nOption D (Incorrect): Hyperkalemia is incorrect; the loss of potassium through vomiting and renal compensation mechanisms invariably leads to hypokalemia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Metabolic Derangement | Cause in IHPS | Key Electrolyte Changes |\n| :------------------- | :------------ | :---------------------- |\n| Metabolic Alkalosis  | Loss of HCl   | High pH, High HCO3      |\n| Hypokalemia          | Renal K+ loss | Low K+                  |\n| Hypochloremia        | Loss of Cl-   | Low Cl-                 |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pyloric stenosis vomiting leads to loss of acid, causing alkalosis, hypokalemia, and hypochloremia.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, the classic 'target sign' or 'doughnut sign' is seen, indicating a thickened pyloric muscle (typically >4mm thickness and >14mm length). Intraoperatively, a hypertrophied, firm pyloric muscle is evident, requiring a Ramstedt pyloromyotomy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis (2017). Recommends surgical pyloromyotomy after correction of fluid and electrolyte imbalances.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Metabolic acidosis with hypokalemia hypochloremia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Metabolic alkalosis with hypokalemia hypochloremia | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Metabolic acidosis with hypernatremia hypochloremia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Metabolie alkalosis with hyperkalemia hypochloremia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
