  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the duodenum bleeds, the GDA is the culprit to seize!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is the Gastroduodenal artery (GDA). In a hemodynamically unstable patient with refractory duodenal bulb ulcer bleeding, surgical ligation of the GDA is the definitive intervention to control hemorrhage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe duodenal bulb is primarily supplied by branches of the gastroduodenal artery, specifically the anterior and posterior superior pancreaticoduodenal arteries. When an ulcer erodes into the posterior wall of the duodenal bulb, it often involves the gastroduodenal artery, which lies immediately posterior to the first part of the duodenum. Ligation of the GDA, typically performed after a duodenotomy and direct suture ligation of the bleeding vessel, effectively controls the blood flow to the ulcer site, preventing further hemorrhage and stabilizing the patient.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): The posterior superior pancreaticoduodenal artery is a branch of the GDA. While it directly supplies the posterior duodenal wall, ligating the main GDA trunk is a more definitive and reliable approach to control significant bleeding from a duodenal bulb ulcer.\nOption C (Incorrect): The left gastric artery supplies the lesser curvature of the stomach and the distal esophagus, not the duodenum. Ligation of this artery would not address duodenal bleeding.\nOption D (Incorrect): The right gastroepiploic artery supplies the greater curvature of the stomach and the greater omentum. It is not involved in the blood supply to the duodenal bulb.\nOption E (Incorrect): The supraduodenal artery (or artery of Wilkie) is a small, inconsistent branch, usually from the GDA or common hepatic artery, supplying a small area superior to the duodenum. It is not the primary source of major hemorrhage from a duodenal bulb ulcer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Artery | Primary Supply Area | Clinical Relevance |\n|---|---|---|\n| Gastroduodenal Artery | Duodenal bulb, head of pancreas | Most common source of bleeding for posterior duodenal ulcers |\n| Left Gastric Artery | Lesser curvature of stomach, distal esophagus | Source of bleeding for gastric ulcers on lesser curvature, esophageal varices |\n| Right Gastroepiploic Artery | Greater curvature of stomach, greater omentum | Source of bleeding for gastric ulcers on greater curvature |\n| Posterior Superior Pancreaticoduodenal Artery | Duodenum, head of pancreas | Direct branch of GDA, often involved in duodenal ulcer bleeding |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unstable duodenal ulcer bleed? Find the GDA, ligate it.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, after a duodenotomy, the bleeding ulcer will be visible on the posterior wall of the duodenal bulb. The gastroduodenal artery lies directly posterior to this area and can be suture ligated directly or by ligating the main trunk after mobilizing the duodenum.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Patients With Acute Upper Gastrointestinal Bleeding (2021) recommends surgical intervention for refractory bleeding after failed endoscopic therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Gastroduodenal artery | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Posterior superior pancreaticoduodenal artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Left gastric artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Right gastroepiploic artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Supraduodenal artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
