  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When you see a central scar, think FNH, not fear!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Focal Nodular Hyperplasia (FNH). This benign liver lesion is classically characterized by a central stellate scar, which is a a key diagnostic feature on imaging, making it distinct from other hepatic masses.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFocal nodular hyperplasia is believed to arise from a congenital arterial malformation within the liver, leading to localized hyperperfusion. This increased blood flow stimulates hepatocyte proliferation around a central fibrous core, which contains abnormal blood vessels and bile ducts. The resulting stellate central scar is a hallmark of FNH, distinguishing it from other hepatic masses and is crucial for non-invasive diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Hepatic adenoma) (Incorrect): Hepatic adenomas are benign tumors often associated with oral contraceptive use and do not typically feature a central scar; they are prone to hemorrhage.\nOption C (Hemangioma) (Incorrect): Hemangiomas are benign vascular tumors that show characteristic peripheral nodular enhancement with centripetal fill-in on imaging, but they lack a central scar.\nOption D (Hydatid cyst) (Incorrect): Hydatid cysts are parasitic infections caused by Echinococcus, presenting as cystic lesions with potential daughter cysts, not a central scar.\nOption E (Amebic abscess) (Incorrect): Amebic abscesses are infectious lesions caused by Entamoeba histolytica, appearing as hypodense lesions with rim enhancement, and do not have a central scar.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Focal Nodular Hyperplasia (FNH) | Hepatic Adenoma | Hemangioma | Hepatocellular Carcinoma (HCC) |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Central Scar** | **Yes (classic)** | No | No | No (sometimes central necrosis) |\n| **Risk Factors** | Congenital vascular malformation | Oral contraceptives, anabolic steroids | Congenital vascular malformation | Cirrhosis, Hep B/C, alcohol, NAFLD |\n| **Imaging** | Arterial enhancement, isodense/hyperdense on portal venous, central scar | Arterial enhancement, rapid washout, no scar, hemorrhage risk | Peripheral nodular enhancement with centripetal fill-in | Arterial enhancement, portal venous washout |\n| **Malignant Potential** | None | Low (risk of transformation) | None | High |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Central scar equals FNH, think 'FNH has a Fancy Scar.'\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn contrast-enhanced CT or MRI, FNH typically shows strong arterial phase enhancement with a characteristic non-enhancing central stellate scar. The scar may show delayed enhancement on later phases.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Study of Liver Diseases (AASLD) Practice Guidance 2021: Diagnosis and Management of Focal Liver Lesions. It recommends characteristic imaging features (e.g., central scar) for non-invasive diagnosis of FNH.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Focal nodular hyperplasia | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Hepatic adenoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hemangioma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hydatid cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Amebic abscess | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
