  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, it's probably a hemangioma.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Hemangioma. Hepatic hemangiomas are the most frequently encountered benign liver tumors, often discovered incidentally during imaging for other conditions, making them the most common benign lesion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHemangiomas are congenital vascular malformations, essentially a tangle of dilated blood vessels within the liver parenchyma. They are typically asymptomatic and do not carry a risk of malignant transformation. Their high prevalence, estimated to be found in up to 20% of the population, firmly establishes them as the most common benign liver lesion, a fundamental fact in hepatobiliary surgery.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Hamartomas are disorganized overgrowths of mature cells and tissues normally found in the liver, but they are significantly less common than hemangiomas.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hepatic adenomas are benign epithelial tumors that, while important due to their risk of hemorrhage and malignant transformation, are much less common than hemangiomas.\nOption D (Incorrect): Focal nodular hyperplasia (FNH) is the second most common benign liver tumor after hemangioma, characterized by a central scar, but it is still less frequent than hemangiomas.\nOption E (Incorrect): Angiomyolipomas are rare benign mesenchymal tumors composed of fat, smooth muscle, and blood vessels, making them far less common than hemangiomas.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Lesion | Key Feature | Malignant Potential | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Hemangioma | Most common benign liver lesion, vascular malformation | None | Observation, rarely resection for symptoms/size |\n| Focal Nodular Hyperplasia (FNH) | Second most common, central scar, normal hepatocytes | None | Observation |\n| Hepatic Adenoma | Associated with OCPs, risk of hemorrhage/malignancy | Low but present (HCC) | Resection often recommended due to risks |\n| Hepatic Cyst | Simple fluid-filled sac, very common | None | Observation, rarely drainage/deroofing for symptoms |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hemangioma is the most common benign liver lesion, often an incidental finding.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, hemangiomas typically show peripheral nodular enhancement with progressive centripetal fill-in on delayed phases. On MRI, they are characteristically T2 hyperintense (bright) and demonstrate similar enhancement patterns.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAASLD Practice Guidance: The Diagnosis and Management of Benign Liver Lesions (2021). This guideline recommends observation for typical hemangiomas, with imaging follow-up only if atypical features are present or if the diagnosis is uncertain.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hamartoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hemangioma | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Adenoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Focal nodular hyperplasia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Angiomyolipoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
