  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Superficial invasion, not nodal spread, defines early gastric cancer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer, D, accurately defines early gastric cancer (EGC) as cancer limited to the mucosa or submucosa, irrespective of lymph node involvement. This definition is crucial for prognosis and treatment planning, distinguishing it from advanced gastric cancer.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEarly gastric cancer is a distinct entity characterized by its limited depth of invasion. By definition, the tumor cells have not penetrated beyond the submucosal layer into the muscularis propria. This superficial invasion is the primary determinant, and the presence or absence of lymph node metastases does not alter the classification of a tumor as EGC. This distinction is vital because EGC generally carries an excellent prognosis, with 5-year survival rates often exceeding 90%, even if regional lymph nodes are involved.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Lymph node negative. While many EGCs are lymph node negative, the definition of EGC does not exclude cases with positive lymph nodes.\nOption B (Incorrect): Limited to mucosa. This describes a subset of EGC (T1a), but EGC also includes tumors invading the submucosa (T1b).\nOption C (Incorrect): Limited to mucosa and submucosa with negative lymph node. The \"negative lymph node\" criterion is incorrect for the definition of EGC; lymph node status does not define EGC.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Early Gastric Cancer (EGC) | Advanced Gastric Cancer (AGC) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Depth of Invasion** | Limited to mucosa (T1a) or submucosa (T1b) | Invades muscularis propria (T2) or deeper (T3, T4) |\n| **Lymph Node Status** | Can be N0 or N+ | Can be N0 or N+ |\n| **Prognosis (5-yr survival)** | Excellent (>90%) | Variable, significantly lower than EGC |\n| **Treatment Approach** | Endoscopic resection (for select T1a), gastrectomy with lymphadenectomy | Gastrectomy with lymphadenectomy, often with neoadjuvant/adjuvant therapy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: EGC is defined by depth (mucosa/submucosa), not lymph node status.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy might reveal subtle mucosal changes like discoloration, erosion, or a slightly elevated/depressed lesion. Endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) can precisely determine the depth of invasion (mucosa vs. submucosa vs. muscularis propria), which is critical for staging and treatment planning.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAJCC Cancer Staging Manual, 8th Edition (2017). It defines T1 gastric cancer as tumor invading lamina propria, muscularis mucosae, or submucosa, which is synonymous with early gastric cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lymph node negative | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Limited to mucosa | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Limited to mucosa and submucosa with negative lymp node | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Limited to mucosa and submucosa regardless the lymph node | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
