  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't wait until 50; 45 is the new prime for your colon's debut!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 45, reflecting updated guidelines from major medical societies. This change was driven by an increasing incidence of colorectal cancer (CRC) in younger populations and the proven benefit of earlier detection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nColorectal cancer is the third most common cancer and a leading cause of cancer-related death. Screening colonoscopy allows for the detection and removal of precancerous polyps, thereby preventing cancer development, or detecting early-stage cancer when it is most treatable. The shift to age 45 for average-risk individuals aims to capture a larger proportion of early-onset CRCs, improving overall survival and reducing disease burden.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Age 40 is generally too early for average-risk screening, though it might be considered for those with a strong family history or specific risk factors.\nOption C (Incorrect): Age 50 was the long-standing recommendation but has been updated by major societies due to rising incidence of CRC in younger adults.\nOption D (Incorrect): Age 55 is too late for initial screening according to current guidelines for average-risk individuals.\nOption E (Incorrect): Age 60 is significantly past the recommended initial screening age for average-risk patients.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Risk Category | Recommended Screening Age | Screening Modality | Frequency |\n| :------------ | :------------------------ | :----------------- | :-------- |\n| Average Risk  | 45                        | Colonoscopy        | Every 10 years |\n| Family History (1st degree relative <60) | 40 or 10 years before youngest case | Colonoscopy | Every 5 years |\n| Lynch Syndrome | 20-25                     | Colonoscopy        | Every 1-2 years |\n| FAP           | 10-12                     | Colonoscopy        | Every 1 year |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Average risk CRC screening starts at 45, not 50.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring colonoscopy, the endoscopist visualizes the colonic mucosa, identifying and removing polyps. Polyps can range from small sessile lesions to larger pedunculated masses, with adenomatous polyps being the most common precursor to colorectal cancer.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Cancer Society (ACS) 2018 and U.S. Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF) 2021 recommend starting colorectal cancer screening at age 45 for average-risk individuals.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 40 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 45 | ✅ Correct |\n| C | 50 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 55 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | 60 | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
