  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pyloric stenosis: Vomit acid, get alkalotic!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, indicating metabolic alkalosis with hypokalemia and hypochloremia. This metabolic derangement is the classic presentation in infants with hypertrophic pyloric stenosis due to persistent vomiting of gastric contents.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInfantile hypertrophic pyloric stenosis (IHPS) leads to persistent, non-bilious projectile vomiting. The stomach secretes hydrochloric acid (HCl), so continuous vomiting results in a significant loss of hydrogen ions (H+) and chloride ions (Cl-). The loss of H+ directly causes metabolic alkalosis. The kidneys attempt to compensate by retaining H+ and excreting potassium (K+) and sodium (Na+) in the urine, leading to hypokalemia. Furthermore, the loss of Cl- contributes to the alkalosis and impairs renal compensation, as chloride is needed for bicarbonate excretion.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Metabolic acidosis is incorrect because the loss of gastric acid (H+) leads to alkalosis, not acidosis.\nOption C (Incorrect): Metabolic acidosis is incorrect for the reasons stated above. While dehydration can occur, hypernatremia is not the primary or typical electrolyte disturbance; hypochloremia is central.\nOption D (Incorrect): Hyperkalemia is incorrect. Due to renal compensation for alkalosis, potassium is excreted, leading to hypokalemia, not hyperkalemia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Primary Metabolic Derangement | Key Electrolyte Changes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Infantile Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis | Metabolic Alkalosis | Hypokalemia, Hypochloremia |\n| Severe Diarrhea | Metabolic Acidosis | Hypokalemia, Hyponatremia |\n| Diabetic Ketoacidosis (DKA) | Metabolic Acidosis | Variable K+ (often total body depletion despite normal/high serum K+), Hyponatremia |\n| Adrenal Insufficiency | Metabolic Acidosis | Hyperkalemia, Hyponatremia |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pyloric stenosis = Vomiting HCl = Alkalosis, low K, low Cl.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, the classic 'target sign' or 'doughnut sign' is seen, indicating a thickened pyloric muscle (pyloric muscle thickness >4mm, pyloric channel length >14mm). Intraoperatively, a markedly hypertrophied, firm, and elongated pyloric muscle is observed, which is incised during a Ramstedt pyloromyotomy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis (2017): Recommends correction of fluid and electrolyte abnormalities prior to surgical intervention.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Metabolic acidosis with hypokalemia hypochloremia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Metabolic alkalosis with hypokalemia hypochloremia | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Metabolic acidosis with hypernatremia hypochloremia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Metabolic alkalosis hyperkalemia hypochloremia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) (B)** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
