  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 EGC: Shallow invasion, deep impact on survival!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. Early gastric cancer (EGC) is fundamentally defined by its depth of invasion, specifically being limited to the mucosa or submucosa, irrespective of lymph node involvement. This definition is critical for staging and treatment planning.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe definition of Early Gastric Cancer (EGC) is an anatomical one, based purely on the depth of tumor invasion. It signifies that the cancer has not penetrated beyond the submucosal layer into the muscularis propria. This distinction is paramount because EGC generally carries an excellent prognosis with high cure rates, often amenable to less aggressive surgical or even endoscopic interventions, unlike advanced gastric cancer which involves deeper layers and typically requires more extensive treatment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (L.N negative): Incorrect. Lymph node status is a prognostic factor and part of the staging system, but it does not define EGC. EGC can have positive lymph nodes.\nOption B (Limited mucosa): Incorrect. While EGC includes lesions limited to the mucosa, it also encompasses those invading the submucosa. This option is too restrictive.\nOption C (Limited mucous and submucosa with negative L.N): Incorrect. The depth of invasion (mucosa and submucosa) is correct, but the inclusion of 'negative L.N' makes this option incorrect as nodal status is not part of the definition of EGC.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Early Gastric Cancer (EGC) | Advanced Gastric Cancer (AGC) |\n| :---------------- | :------------------------------------------------------- | :---------------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Definition** | Invasion limited to mucosa or submucosa | Invasion extending into or beyond muscularis propria |\n| **Lymph Nodes** | Can be positive or negative (does not change definition) | Can be positive or negative (impacts staging and prognosis) |\n| **Prognosis** | Generally excellent (5-year survival >90%) | Varies widely, generally poorer than EGC |\n| **Treatment** | Endoscopic resection (select cases), gastrectomy | Gastrectomy, often with neoadjuvant/adjuvant therapy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: EGC is defined by depth, not nodes.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, EGC can appear as subtle changes (elevated, depressed, or flat lesions) that may be difficult to distinguish from benign conditions without biopsy. Endoscopic Ultrasound (EUS) is crucial for pre-operative assessment of invasion depth (mucosa vs. submucosa) and regional lymph node status. Intraoperatively, EGC may not be grossly palpable if very superficial, necessitating careful adherence to pre-operative localization and planned resection margins.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe NCCN Guidelines for Gastric Cancer (e.g., 2023) define EGC as adenocarcinoma with invasion limited to the mucosa or submucosa, regardless of lymph node metastasis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | L.N negative | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Limited mucosa | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Limited mucous and submucosa with negative L.N | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Limited to and submucosa regardless of nodes | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
