  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't operate on a stone that isn't causing a stir!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, \"Most people with a gallstone are asymptomatic.\" This statement is fundamentally true regarding the natural history of cholelithiasis, as a significant majority of individuals with gallstones never develop symptoms or complications.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallstones are a common finding, affecting 10-15% of the adult population in Western countries. However, approximately 80% of these individuals will remain asymptomatic throughout their lives. Only a minority will develop biliary colic, and an even smaller percentage will experience complications such as acute cholecystitis, choledocholithiasis, cholangitis, or pancreatitis. This asymptomatic period can last for decades, highlighting that the mere presence of gallstones does not necessitate intervention unless symptoms or high-risk features are present.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Approximately 90% of gallstones are visible on plane abdominal x-ray. This is incorrect. Only about 10-20% of gallstones are sufficiently calcified to be visible on plain abdominal X-ray; the vast majority are cholesterol stones, which are radiolucent.\nOption B (Incorrect): CT is the imaging of choice in diagnoses of gallstones. This is incorrect. Ultrasound is the imaging modality of choice for diagnosing gallstones due to its high sensitivity, specificity, and lack of radiation exposure.\nOption D (Incorrect): Gallstone ileus occur when gallstone travels through the bile duct into small bowel and causes obstruction. This is incorrect. Gallstone ileus occurs when a large gallstone erodes through a cholecystoenteric fistula (typically into the duodenum) and then causes mechanical obstruction, most commonly in the terminal ileum, not by traveling through the bile duct.\nOption E (Incorrect): Mirizzi's syndrome is caused by stone in the common bile duct. This is incorrect. Mirizzi's syndrome is caused by an impacted gallstone in the cystic duct or gallbladder neck compressing the common hepatic duct, leading to obstruction and potentially a cholecystocholedochal fistula, not by a stone directly within the common bile duct.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Location of Stone | Key Feature | Imaging of Choice |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Cholelithiasis | Gallbladder | Asymptomatic or biliary colic | Ultrasound |\n| Choledocholithiasis | Common Bile Duct | Jaundice, cholangitis, pancreatitis | MRCP / EUS / ERCP |\n| Gallstone Ileus | Small Bowel (usually ileum) | Mechanical bowel obstruction, pneumobilia | CT abdomen |\n| Mirizzi's Syndrome | Cystic duct/Gallbladder neck | Compression of common hepatic duct | MRCP / ERCP |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Most gallstones are silent passengers, not troublemakers.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, gallstones typically appear as echogenic foci within the gallbladder lumen, often mobile, and casting a characteristic posterior acoustic shadow. Plain abdominal X-rays are generally unhelpful for diagnosing gallstones due to their radiolucent nature. CT scans are useful for detecting complications like cholecystitis or gallstone ileus (Rigler's triad: pneumobilia, small bowel obstruction, ectopic gallstone).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Gastroenterological Association (AGA) Institute Technical Review on the Epidemiology and Natural History of Gallstones (2006) recommends watchful waiting for asymptomatic gallstones.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Approximately 90% of gallstones are visible on plane abdominal x- ray | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | CT is the imaging of choice in diagnoses of gallstones | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Most people with a gallstone are asymptomatic | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Gallstone ileus occur when gallstone travels through the bile duct into sma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Mirizzi's syndrome is caused by stone in the common bile duct | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
