  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Nodes mean bad news, Duke's C confirms it.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nDuke's classification is a historical but foundational staging system for colorectal cancer. The correct answer accurately identifies the defining characteristic of Duke's C stage, which is the presence of regional lymph node involvement.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuke's classification, though largely superseded by the TNM system, remains a critical concept in surgical oncology. Duke's C specifically denotes metastatic disease in regional lymph nodes, which is a major prognostic factor. This nodal involvement signifies a higher risk of systemic disease and recurrence, necessitating adjuvant systemic therapy (chemotherapy) post-resection to improve survival outcomes. Understanding this distinction is crucial for treatment planning.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Duke's classification describes the extent of disease, which *informs* operability, but its primary purpose is not to 'detect' operability. Operability is determined by patient fitness, tumor resectability, and absence of distant metastases.\nOption B (Incorrect): Duke's B means the tumor has invaded through the muscularis propria but without nodal involvement. While it's still confined to the bowel wall and surrounding tissues without distant spread, the phrase 'limited to colon' is less precise than the definition of Duke's B, which specifies transmural invasion. Duke's A is limited to the submucosa/muscularis propria.\nOption D (Incorrect): Duke's classification is a *pathologic* classification, based on the microscopic examination of the resected specimen. Clinical staging (cTNM) is based on pre-operative findings, but Duke's is a post-operative, pathologic system.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Duke's Stage | Description (Colorectal Cancer) | TNM Equivalent (simplified) | Prognosis (5-year survival) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| A | Tumor confined to muscularis propria | T1-T2 N0 M0 | ~90% |\n| B | Tumor invades through muscularis propria, no nodal involvement | T3-T4 N0 M0 | ~70-80% |\n| C | Any depth of tumor invasion with regional nodal involvement | Any T N1-N2 M0 | ~30-60% |\n| D | Distant metastases | Any T Any N M1 | <10% |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Duke's C means Cancer in nodes, requiring Chemo.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn pre-operative CT or MRI, enlarged or suspicious regional lymph nodes (e.g., >1cm, irregular borders, central necrosis) would raise suspicion for Duke's C. Intraoperatively, palpably firm or enlarged nodes would also suggest nodal involvement, though definitive staging requires pathologic examination of resected nodes.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Colon Cancer (e.g., 2023/2024). These guidelines recommend adjuvant chemotherapy for Stage III (Duke's C) colon cancer, typically with FOLFOX or CAPOX regimens, due to the high risk of recurrence associated with nodal involvement.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Helps to detect operability of the case | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Duke's B means tumor limited to colon | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Duke's C means nodal involvement | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | It's clinicopathologic classification | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) Answer** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
