  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pyloric stenosis: hungry baby, non-bilious puke, easy fix!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Pyloric Stenosis. This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the classic triad of non-bilious, projectile vomiting, and immediate hunger after emesis in an infant.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInfantile hypertrophic pyloric stenosis (IHPS) involves hypertrophy and hyperplasia of the muscular layers of the pylorus, leading to gastric outlet obstruction. This obstruction prevents gastric contents from passing into the duodenum, resulting in non-bilious vomiting. The vomiting is often projectile due to the force required to overcome the obstruction. Despite vomiting, the infant remains hungry because nutrients are not absorbed, leading to a compensatory drive to feed.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Intussusception typically presents with bilious vomiting, intermittent abdominal pain, and \"currant jelly\" stools, not immediate hunger after vomiting.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hirschsprung's disease primarily causes constipation and abdominal distension, with bilious vomiting occurring in severe cases of enterocolitis or obstruction, and not typically associated with immediate hunger.\nOption D (Incorrect): Volvulus presents as an acute surgical emergency with sudden onset of bilious vomiting, abdominal pain, and distension, and the infant would be acutely ill, not hungry.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Vomiting Type | Hunger After Vomiting | Stool | Other Key Features |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Pyloric Stenosis | Non-bilious, projectile | Yes | Normal | Palpable olive mass, visible peristalsis |\n| Intussusception | Bilious | No | \"Currant jelly\" | Intermittent abdominal pain, lethargy |\n| Hirschsprung's | Bilious (late/severe) | No | Constipation, failure to pass meconium | Abdominal distension |\n| Volvulus | Bilious | No | Bloody (late) | Acute abdominal pain, rapid deterioration |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Non-bilious projectile vomiting + hungry infant = Pyloric Stenosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nAbdominal ultrasound would reveal a thickened pyloric muscle (typically >3-4 mm) and an elongated pyloric channel (typically >14-17 mm). Intraoperatively, a hypertrophied, firm pylorus would be observed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Pediatric Surgical Association (APSA) guidelines on gastric outlet obstruction recommend ultrasound as the primary diagnostic modality for pyloric stenosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Intussusception | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pyloric stenosis | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Hirschsprung's disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Volvulus | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
