  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Esophageal adenocarcinoma is on the rise, not decline!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B because the question asks for the statement that is *not* true. Adenocarcinoma of the esophagus has shown a significant *increase* in incidence over the past several decades, particularly in Western countries, not a decrease.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe epidemiology of esophageal cancer has undergone a dramatic shift. Historically, Squamous Cell Carcinoma (SCC) was overwhelmingly the most common type worldwide, strongly linked to smoking, alcohol, and nutritional deficiencies. However, in Western populations, the incidence of Adenocarcinoma has risen sharply, now often surpassing SCC, primarily due to its association with Barrett's esophagus, GERD, and obesity. This epidemiological shift is a critical concept in understanding esophageal cancer.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Globally, Squamous Cell Carcinoma (SCC) remains the most common type of esophageal cancer, especially in regions like Asia and Africa. While adenocarcinoma is rising in the West, this statement is generally considered true in a worldwide context.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hyperkeratosis of the palm and sole (Tylosis) is a well-established genetic syndrome (Tylosis with Esophageal Cancer, TOC) that significantly increases the risk of developing esophageal squamous cell carcinoma. This statement is true.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Squamous Cell Carcinoma (SCC) | Adenocarcinoma |\n| :------------------ | :----------------------------------------------------------- | :-------------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Epidemiology** | Most common worldwide; decreasing in Western countries | Increasing rapidly in Western countries |\n| **Risk Factors** | Smoking, alcohol, hot beverages, nutritional deficiencies, achalasia, tylosis | Barrett's esophagus, GERD, obesity, smoking (lesser extent) |\n| **Location** | Proximal and mid-esophagus | Distal esophagus and gastroesophageal junction (GEJ) |\n| **Histology** | Squamous epithelium | Glandular epithelium |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Adenocarcinoma is rising, SCC is still global king.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, esophageal cancer may appear as an ulcerated, friable, or fungating mass, or a stricture. Barium swallow can show irregular narrowing or a \"rat-tail\" appearance. CT scans help stage the disease by identifying local invasion, lymphadenopathy, and distant metastases.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Esophageal and Esophagogastric Junction Cancers (e.g., 2024). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis, staging, and treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Most common type is SCC | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Adenocarcinoma show decrease in frequency | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Associated with hyperkeratosis of palm and sole | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Answer : B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
