  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Diabetics with gallstones: better out than in!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, indicating that asymptomatic gallstones in an insulin-dependent patient are an indication for cholecystectomy. This is a crucial prophylactic measure due to the significantly increased risk of severe complications and poorer outcomes in diabetic patients.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDiabetic patients, especially those who are insulin-dependent, are at a higher risk for developing complications from gallstones, such as acute cholecystitis, gangrenous cholecystitis, perforation, and sepsis. Their impaired immune response, autonomic neuropathy affecting gallbladder motility, and microvascular disease contribute to these severe outcomes, often with atypical or delayed symptom presentation. Prophylactic cholecystectomy is recommended in this population to prevent these life-threatening complications, even in the absence of symptoms, as the morbidity and mortality associated with emergent cholecystectomy in diabetics are substantially higher.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): While intermittent right upper quadrant pain (biliary colic) is a common indication for cholecystectomy, the question likely seeks a specific prophylactic indication in a high-risk group, which option A provides. Option B describes symptomatic disease, whereas option A describes a prophylactic intervention for an asymptomatic condition in a vulnerable patient.\nOption C (Incorrect): Angina is a symptom of coronary artery disease and has no direct bearing on the indication for cholecystectomy for asymptomatic gallstones. The presence of angina does not increase the risk of gallstone complications or necessitate prophylactic removal.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Indication Type | Description | Cholecystectomy Recommendation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Symptomatic Gallstones | Biliary colic, acute cholecystitis, gallstone pancreatitis, choledocholithiasis | Recommended |\n| Asymptomatic Gallstones (Low Risk) | Incidental finding, no symptoms | Observation |\n| Asymptomatic Gallstones (High Risk) | Insulin-dependent diabetes, porcelain gallbladder, gallstones >3cm, planned bariatric surgery | Prophylactic Cholecystectomy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Asymptomatic gallstones in insulin-dependent diabetics warrant prophylactic cholecystectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, gallstones appear as echogenic foci within the gallbladder lumen, typically casting an acoustic shadow and demonstrating mobility with patient position changes. In diabetic patients, the gallbladder wall may appear thickened even without acute inflammation, and signs of complications like pericholecystic fluid or gas may be subtle.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Gastroenterological Association (AGA) Institute Guidelines 2019: Recommends considering prophylactic cholecystectomy for asymptomatic gallstones in patients with diabetes mellitus, especially if they are insulin-dependent, due to increased risk of complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Asymptomatic gallstone in insulin dependent patient | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Old patient with intermittent right upper quadrant | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Asymptomatic gallstone with angina | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Answer: A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
