  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 No stones, no cholelithiasis complication.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. Acute acalculous cholecystitis is, by definition, inflammation of the gallbladder in the absence of gallstones, making it the only option not a direct complication of cholelithiasis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCholelithiasis refers to the presence of gallstones, which can cause a spectrum of complications by obstructing bile flow, migrating into ducts, or eroding into adjacent structures. These complications range from biliary colic to severe conditions like cholangitis, pancreatitis, and gallstone ileus. Understanding the pathophysiology of each complication helps differentiate those directly caused by stones from those that occur independently.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Obstructive jaundice is a direct complication when gallstones migrate into the common bile duct, causing choledocholithiasis and subsequent obstruction.\nOption B (Incorrect): Acute pancreatitis can be caused by gallstones obstructing the ampulla of Vater, leading to biliary reflux into the pancreatic duct or direct pancreatic duct obstruction.\nOption C (Incorrect): Emphysematous cholecystitis is a severe form of acute cholecystitis, which is most commonly caused by gallstones obstructing the cystic duct.\nOption E (Incorrect): Gallstone ileus occurs when a large gallstone erodes through a cholecystoenteric fistula into the bowel, causing mechanical obstruction, a direct complication of cholelithiasis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Cause by Cholelithiasis | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|\n| Obstructive Jaundice | Yes (choledocholithiasis) | Bile duct obstruction, elevated bilirubin |\n| Acute Pancreatitis | Yes (ampullary obstruction) | Epigastric pain, elevated amylase/lipase |\n| Emphysematous Cholecystitis | Yes (secondary to calculous cholecystitis) | Gas in gallbladder wall/lumen, severe infection |\n| Acute Acalculous Cholecystitis | No | Inflammation without stones, often in critically ill |\n| Gallstone Ileus | Yes (cholecystoenteric fistula) | Mechanical bowel obstruction by stone |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acalculous cholecystitis is defined by the *absence* of gallstones.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, acute calculous cholecystitis shows gallstones, gallbladder wall thickening (>3mm), pericholecystic fluid, and a sonographic Murphy's sign. Acute acalculous cholecystitis would show similar inflammatory signs but *without* stones.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018 for the management of acute cholecystitis. They provide diagnostic criteria and severity grading for acute cholecystitis, including calculous and acalculous forms.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Obstructive jaundice | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Acute pancreatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Emphysematous cholecystitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Acute acalculous cholecystitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Gall stone ileus | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
