  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pyloric stenosis: Vomit acid, get alkalotic, low K, low Cl.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B. Infantile hypertrophic pyloric stenosis (IHPS) causes persistent, projectile non-bilious vomiting, leading to significant loss of gastric acid (HCl) and potassium, resulting in a characteristic metabolic derangement.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe hallmark metabolic disturbance in IHPS is metabolic alkalosis, primarily due to the loss of hydrogen ions (H+) from the stomach. Concurrently, there is a significant loss of chloride ions (Cl-) in the vomitus, leading to hypochloremia. The continuous vomiting also depletes potassium stores, exacerbated by renal compensation mechanisms (aldosterone-mediated K+ excretion in exchange for Na+ to maintain volume), resulting in hypokalemia. This triad of metabolic alkalosis, hypochloremia, and hypokalemia is crucial to recognize for proper preoperative resuscitation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Metabolic acidosis is incorrect; the loss of gastric acid leads to alkalosis.\nOption C (Incorrect): Metabolic acidosis is incorrect. Hypernatremia is not a typical finding; volume depletion is common, but not necessarily hypernatremia.\nOption D (Incorrect): Hyperkalemia is incorrect; vomiting causes significant potassium loss, leading to hypokalemia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Metabolic Derangement | Cause in IHPS | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|\n| Metabolic Alkalosis | Loss of gastric HCl (H+ ions) | Can lead to respiratory depression, seizures |\n| Hypochloremia | Loss of gastric HCl (Cl- ions) | Contributes to alkalosis, impairs renal H+ excretion |\n| Hypokalemia | Loss of gastric K+, renal K+ excretion | Can cause cardiac arrhythmias, muscle weakness |\n| Dehydration | Fluid loss from vomiting | Pre-renal azotemia, electrolyte imbalance |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Vomiting = Alkalosis + Hypo-Cl + Hypo-K.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound is the diagnostic modality of choice, showing a thickened pyloric muscle (>3-4 mm) and an elongated pyloric channel (>14-17 mm). Intraoperatively, the hypertrophied pylorus is palpable as an \"olive\" mass.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Infantile Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis (2017). Recommends prompt diagnosis and correction of fluid and electrolyte abnormalities prior to surgical intervention.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Metabolic acidosis with hypokalemia and hypochloremia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Metabolic alkalosis with hypokalemia and hypochloremia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Metabolic acidosis with hypernatremia hypochloremia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Metabolic alkalosis with hyperkalemia and hypochloremia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
