  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Anemia in an adult? Think right colon, not just diet!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The correct answer is A, Microcytic anemia. Right-sided colon carcinomas are often characterized by insidious, chronic blood loss into the stool, which can lead to iron deficiency anemia before other symptoms manifest.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe right colon has a larger luminal diameter and contains more liquid stool, allowing tumors to grow quite large and ulcerate without causing obstructive symptoms. This chronic, low-grade bleeding, often occult, depletes iron stores over time, resulting in microcytic, hypochromic anemia. The anemia is typically the presenting symptom, prompting investigation, whereas left-sided lesions are more likely to cause overt changes in bowel habits or obstruction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Intestinal obstruction is more characteristic of left-sided colon cancers due to the narrower lumen and more solid stool consistency, which makes them more prone to occlude the bowel.\nOption C (Incorrect): Bright red blood in stool (hematochezia) is more commonly associated with left-sided or rectal cancers, as the blood has less time to be digested and altered before excretion.\nOption D (Incorrect): Progressive constipation is a symptom of luminal narrowing and obstruction, which, like intestinal obstruction, is more typical of left-sided colon cancers.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Right-Sided Colon Cancer | Left-Sided Colon Cancer |\n|---|---|---|\n| Lumen Diameter | Wider | Narrower |\n| Stool Consistency | Liquid | Solid |\n| Presentation | Anemia, fatigue, occult bleeding, vague abdominal pain | Obstruction, change in bowel habits (constipation/diarrhea), hematochezia, tenesmus |\n| Tumor Growth | Often exophytic, fungating | Often annular, constricting (\"apple-core\") |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Right-sided colon cancer = anemia; Left-sided = obstruction/bleeding.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn colonoscopy, a right-sided mass may appear fungating or ulcerated. Imaging like CT scan might show a large cecal or ascending colon mass, often with associated lymphadenopathy or signs of metastatic disease, and sometimes evidence of anemia (e.g., splenomegaly from extramedullary hematopoiesis in severe cases).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Colon Cancer (2023). These guidelines emphasize screening for colorectal cancer and thorough workup for iron deficiency anemia, which is a common presentation of right-sided lesions, often necessitating colonoscopy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Microcytic anemia | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Intestinal obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Bright red blood in stool | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Progressive constipation | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) (A)** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
