  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the colon twists, the sigmoid wins the prize for most common.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Sigmoid colon. Sigmoid volvulus accounts for the majority of colonic volvulus cases due to its unique anatomical predisposition, making it the most common site for volvulus overall.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe sigmoid colon is particularly susceptible to volvulus because it often possesses a long, redundant loop of bowel with a narrow mesenteric attachment. This anatomical configuration allows the loop to twist upon its mesentery, leading to obstruction and potential ischemia. Factors like chronic constipation, a high-fiber diet, and institutionalization can contribute to its elongation and mobility, increasing the risk of torsion in elderly patients.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Cecum) (Incorrect): Cecal volvulus is the second most common type of colonic volvulus, but it is significantly less frequent than sigmoid volvulus. It typically involves the cecum and terminal ileum twisting on their mesentery.\nOption B (Proximal jejunum) (Incorrect): Small bowel volvulus, while possible, is rare in adults and usually associated with prior surgery, malrotation, or adhesions. The jejunum is not the most common site for volvulus overall.\nOption D (Stomach) (Incorrect): Gastric volvulus is a rare condition where the stomach twists on its axis. It is far less common than colonic volvulus and often associated with hiatal hernia or diaphragmatic defects.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Volvulus Type | Incidence | Typical Patient | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Sigmoid | Most common (60-75% of colonic) | Elderly, institutionalized, chronic constipation | \"Coffee bean\" sign on X-ray, redundant loop |\n| Cecal | Second most common (15-25% of colonic) | Younger adults, mobile cecum | Kidney-shaped cecum, small bowel dilation |\n| Gastric | Rare | Adults with hiatal hernia, children | Organoaxial or mesenteroaxial twist |\n| Small Bowel | Rare in adults | Prior surgery, adhesions, malrotation | Whirl sign on CT, often acute presentation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sigmoid volvulus: long loop, narrow base, coffee bean.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain abdominal X-ray, sigmoid volvulus classically presents with a large, inverted U-shaped loop of distended colon, often described as a \"coffee bean\" sign, extending from the pelvis towards the diaphragm. CT scan can confirm the diagnosis, showing a \"whirl sign\" of twisted mesentery and vessels. Intraoperatively, a massively distended, often dusky, twisted sigmoid colon would be observed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Colonic Volvulus (2016). Recommends endoscopic detorsion as the initial treatment for sigmoid volvulus in stable patients, followed by elective resection.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cecum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Proximal jejunum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Sigmoid colon | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Stomach | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) (C)** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
