  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Depth defines early, not nodes; prognosis is key.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. Early gastric cancer (EGC) is precisely defined by the depth of tumor invasion, specifically when it is limited to the mucosa or submucosa, irrespective of lymph node involvement.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEarly gastric cancer is a critical concept in surgical oncology, defined by its limited depth of invasion. This means the tumor has not penetrated beyond the submucosal layer into the muscularis propria. This definition is crucial because EGC, even with positive lymph nodes, carries a significantly better prognosis than advanced gastric cancer, which invades the muscularis propria or deeper. The depth of invasion dictates the potential for endoscopic resection versus surgical gastrectomy and influences overall survival rates.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Lymph node status is a prognostic factor, not a defining characteristic of 'early' gastric cancer. EGC can still have positive lymph nodes.\nOption B (Incorrect): This definition is too restrictive. EGC includes invasion into the submucosa, not just the mucosa.\nOption C (Incorrect): While negative lymph nodes are a good prognostic sign, the definition of EGC itself does not require them to be negative. The depth of invasion is the sole defining criterion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Early Gastric Cancer (EGC) | Advanced Gastric Cancer (AGC) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Depth of Invasion | Limited to mucosa or submucosa | Invades muscularis propria or deeper |\n| Nodal Status | Can be positive or negative | Can be positive or negative |\n| Prognosis | Excellent (often >90% 5-year survival) | Poor (variable, often <30% 5-year survival) |\n| Treatment | Endoscopic resection (selected cases), gastrectomy | Gastrectomy, chemotherapy, radiation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: EGC = mucosa/submucosa invasion, nodal status is irrelevant for definition.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy with biopsy is essential for diagnosis. Endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) is crucial for assessing the depth of invasion (T-stage) and regional lymph node involvement, which helps differentiate EGC from AGC and guides treatment planning. EGC can appear as elevated, flat, or depressed lesions on endoscopy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Gastric Cancer (2024). These guidelines define EGC as adenocarcinoma with invasion limited to the mucosa or submucosa, regardless of lymph node status.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lymph node negative | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Limited to mucosa | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Limited to mucosa and submucosa with negative lymph node | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Limited to mucosa and submucosa regardless of node | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) (D)** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
