  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Nodes matter: Duke's C means adjuvant therapy.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nDuke's classification is a historical but fundamental staging system for colorectal cancer. Option C correctly identifies the defining characteristic of Duke's C stage, which is the presence of regional lymph node involvement.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuke's classification was one of the earliest systems to stratify colorectal cancer patients based on tumor invasion and nodal status, directly correlating with prognosis. The presence of regional lymph node metastasis (Duke's C) is a critical indicator of increased risk for systemic disease and recurrence, necessitating adjuvant chemotherapy. This highlights the importance of lymphatic spread as a major pathway for cancer dissemination and a key determinant of patient outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Duke's classification is a post-operative pathologic staging system, primarily used for prognosis and guiding adjuvant therapy, not for determining pre-operative operability. Operability is assessed by resectability.\nOption B (Incorrect): Duke's B specifically means the tumor has invaded through the muscularis propria but without nodal involvement. \"Limited to colon\" is too vague and does not capture the depth of invasion.\nOption D (Incorrect): Duke's classification is primarily a pathologic staging system, determined after surgical resection and histological examination of the resected specimen. While clinical information is always considered, the definitive Duke's stage is based on pathology.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Duke's Stage | Description | Prognosis | Adjuvant Therapy |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| A | Tumor confined to muscularis propria | Excellent | Usually not |\n| B | Tumor invades through muscularis propria, no nodal involvement | Good | Consider for high-risk features |\n| C | Any depth of invasion with regional lymph node involvement | Fair | Recommended |\n| D | Distant metastasis | Poor | Palliative/Systemic |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Duke's C means \"Cancer in nodes,\" requiring adjuvant therapy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, suspicious lymph nodes are resected for pathologic examination to determine nodal status. Pre-operative imaging (CT, MRI) can suggest nodal involvement but definitive Duke's C staging relies on histopathology.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Colon Cancer (e.g., 2023). These guidelines emphasize the critical prognostic role of nodal involvement (equivalent to Duke's C) in determining the need for adjuvant chemotherapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Helps to detect operability of the case | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Duke's B means tumor limited to colon | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Duke's C means nodal involvement | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | It's clinicopathologic classification | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) Answer** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
