  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Chronic wound + heaped edges = biopsy now, it's cancer!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Marjolin's ulcer. The key descriptor 'heaped edges' in a chronic ulcer strongly suggests malignant transformation, specifically squamous cell carcinoma, which is characteristic of a Marjolin's ulcer.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMarjolin's ulcer is a rare but aggressive form of squamous cell carcinoma (SCC) that arises in chronic, non-healing wounds, scars, or burns. The prolonged inflammatory state in these chronic lesions can lead to cellular atypia and eventual malignant transformation. The 'heaped edges' appearance is a classic clinical sign of this proliferative malignant change, indicating an outward growth pattern of the cancerous cells at the ulcer margins, distinguishing it from benign chronic ulcers.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Venous ulcers typically have irregular borders, shallow depth, and often present with surrounding skin changes like hyperpigmentation and lipodermatosclerosis, but not typically 'heaped edges' unless malignant transformation has occurred, which would then be termed a Marjolin's ulcer.\nOption B (Incorrect): Arterial ulcers are usually 'punched out' with a pale base, often located on distal extremities or pressure points, and are painful. They do not present with 'heaped edges'.\nOption D (Incorrect): Curling's ulcer is an acute gastric ulcer associated with severe burns, not a chronic skin ulcer with heaped edges.\nOption E (Incorrect): Cushing's ulcer is an acute gastric ulcer associated with head trauma or central nervous system injury, not a chronic skin ulcer with heaped edges.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Ulcer Type | Key Appearance | Etiology | Location |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Marjolin's Ulcer | Heaped, everted edges; chronic, non-healing | Malignant transformation (SCC) in chronic wounds/scars | Any chronic wound/scar |\n| Venous Ulcer | Irregular, shallow, granulating; hyperpigmentation | Venous insufficiency | Medial malleolus, gaiter area |\n| Arterial Ulcer | Punched-out, pale base, often painful | Arterial insufficiency | Toes, pressure points, distal leg |\n| Diabetic Ulcer | Calloused edges, neuropathic, often painless | Neuropathy, ischemia, pressure | Plantar foot, metatarsal heads |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Heaped edges in a chronic ulcer = Marjolin's until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn biopsy, you would see invasive squamous cell carcinoma. Intraoperatively, wide local excision with clear margins is required, often necessitating reconstructive surgery.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Squamous Cell Carcinoma (2023) recommend biopsy for suspicious chronic wounds and wide local excision for confirmed cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Venous ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Arterial ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Marjolin’s ulcer | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Curling’s ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Cushing’s ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
