  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't remove the escape route if the main road is blocked!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Deep vein thrombosis. Varicose vein surgery is contraindicated in the presence of deep vein thrombosis (DVT) because the superficial veins may be acting as crucial collateral pathways for venous return when the deep system is compromised.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe physiological basis for this contraindication lies in the venous drainage system. Normally, superficial veins drain into the deep venous system. However, if the deep venous system is obstructed by a DVT, the superficial veins can become essential conduits for blood return from the limb. Removing or ablating these superficial veins in such a scenario would severely impair venous outflow, potentially leading to acute limb swelling, pain, and even limb ischemia. Therefore, ensuring the patency of the deep venous system via pre-operative duplex ultrasound is a critical step before any intervention on superficial varicose veins.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Varacoise veins) (Incorrect): Varicose veins are the primary indication for surgery, not a contraindication. The surgery aims to treat them.\nOption C (Pigmentation over limb) (Incorrect): Pigmentation is a sign of chronic venous insufficiency, often associated with varicose veins, indicating disease severity but not precluding surgery. It's a consequence, not a contraindication.\nOption D (Hemorroides) (Incorrect): Hemorrhoids are dilated veins in the anal canal, a separate venous system, and have no direct relevance or contraindication to lower limb varicose vein surgery.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature                 | Varicose Vein Surgery: Indication                               | Varicose Vein Surgery: Contraindication                               |\n| :---------------------- | :-------------------------------------------------------------- | :-------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Purpose**             | Alleviate symptoms, prevent complications, improve cosmesis     | Avoid worsening venous return, prevent limb compromise                |\n| **Clinical Scenario**   | Symptomatic varicose veins, skin changes, ulceration, bleeding  | Acute DVT, severe arterial insufficiency, pregnancy, immobility       |\n| **Key Consideration**   | Patency of deep venous system, patient symptoms                 | Deep venous system integrity, overall patient health                  |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always confirm deep vein patency before superficial vein intervention.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPre-operative duplex ultrasound is essential to assess the deep venous system. In the presence of DVT, the deep veins would show non-compressibility, intraluminal thrombus, and absent or abnormal flow patterns.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety for Vascular Surgery (SVS) and American Venous Forum (AVF) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Varicose Veins and Chronic Venous Disease (2011, updated 2022) recommend pre-operative duplex ultrasound to map the superficial system and assess the deep venous system for patency and reflux.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Varacoise veins | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Deep vein thrombosis | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Pigmentation over limb | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hemorroides | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
