  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 White leg, deep clot, collaterals spared, don't delay!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nPhlegmasia alba dolens is a severe form of deep vein thrombosis characterized by massive occlusion of the major deep venous channels, while initially sparing the collateral venous system. This leads to significant venous outflow obstruction, edema, and arterial spasm, resulting in a painful, pale, and swollen limb.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPhlegmasia alba dolens, also known as \"milk leg,\" represents an advanced stage of deep vein thrombosis, typically involving the iliofemoral segment. The hallmark is extensive thrombosis of the main deep venous channels, leading to profound venous hypertension. Crucially, the collateral veins remain patent, allowing some venous drainage and preventing the complete cessation of arterial inflow seen in phlegmasia cerulea dolens. The resulting edema and reflex arterial spasm contribute to the characteristic pallor and severe pain.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Obliteration of collateral veins of the leg is characteristic of phlegmasia cerulea dolens, a more severe condition where even the collateral venous outflow is compromised, leading to complete limb ischemia and potential gangrene. In phlegmasia alba dolens, collaterals are initially spared.\nOption B (Incorrect): Reperfusion injury occurs after blood flow is restored to ischemic tissue, for example, after embolectomy or thrombolysis for arterial occlusion. Phlegmasia alba dolens is an acute thrombotic event causing venous outflow obstruction, not a reperfusion phenomenon.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Phlegmasia Alba Dolens (PAD) | Phlegmasia Cerulea Dolens (PCD) | Uncomplicated DVT |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Venous Occlusion** | Major deep venous channels (e.g., iliofemoral) | Major deep venous channels AND collateral veins | Partial or complete occlusion of deep veins |\n| **Collateral Veins** | Spared (initially) | Occluded | Patent |\n| **Limb Appearance** | Pale, swollen, painful (\"milk leg\") | Cyanotic, swollen, painful, blistering, potential gangrene | Swollen, tender, warm, erythematous |\n| **Arterial Flow** | Impaired (due to spasm) | Severely impaired/absent | Normal |\n| **Prognosis** | Serious, but better than PCD | High risk of limb loss, systemic complications | Good with anticoagulation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Phlegmasia alba dolens is deep vein occlusion with *spared* collaterals, leading to a pale limb.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuplex ultrasound would show extensive, non-compressible thrombus in the iliofemoral venous segment with absent or severely diminished flow. Venography would demonstrate a \"cut-off\" sign or extensive filling defects in the deep venous system, with contrast potentially flowing through patent collateral veins.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Chest Physicians (ACCP) Guidelines for Antithrombotic Therapy for VTE Disease (10th Edition, 2016). These guidelines recommend anticoagulation as the cornerstone of treatment for DVT, including severe forms like phlegmasia alba dolens, and may consider catheter-directed thrombolysis or surgical thrombectomy in selected cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Obliteration of collateral viens of the leg | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Reperfusion injury following injury of the femoral vein | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Obilteration of the major deep venous channel and sparing of the | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
