  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it's peripheral, think popliteal first!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Popliteal artery. Popliteal artery aneurysms are indeed the most common type of peripheral artery aneurysm, making this a fundamental fact in vascular surgery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPopliteal artery aneurysms account for over 70% of all peripheral aneurysms. They are clinically significant due to their high rates of complications, including thrombosis, distal embolization, and rupture, which can lead to acute limb ischemia and limb loss. Anatomically, the popliteal fossa is a confined space, making these aneurysms prone to compression symptoms and challenging to manage when complicated. Furthermore, they are frequently bilateral (50-70%) and often coexist with abdominal aortic aneurysms (40-60%), necessitating a thorough workup.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Femoral artery aneurysms are the second most common peripheral aneurysms but occur less frequently than popliteal aneurysms.\nOption B (Incorrect): Axillary artery aneurysms are rare and typically associated with trauma or repetitive microtrauma.\nOption D (Incorrect): Brachial artery aneurysms are also uncommon and often iatrogenic or traumatic in origin.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Peripheral Aneurysm Type | Relative Frequency | Key Associations | Complications |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Popliteal | Most common (70%+) | Bilateral (50-70%), AAA (40-60%) | Thrombosis, embolization, rupture, limb loss |\n| Femoral | Second most common (15-20%) | AAA | Thrombosis, embolization |\n| Upper Extremity (Axillary/Brachial) | Rare (<5%) | Trauma, iatrogenic | Thrombosis, embolization, nerve compression |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Popliteal aneurysms are the most common peripheral aneurysm, often bilateral and linked to AAA.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn duplex ultrasound, a popliteal artery aneurysm appears as a focal dilatation of the artery, often with mural thrombus. CT angiography provides detailed anatomical mapping and assessment of thrombus burden and distal runoff. Intraoperatively, a pulsatile mass in the popliteal fossa would be observed, often requiring bypass grafting.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety for Vascular Surgery (SVS) Clinical Practice Guidelines on the Management of Popliteal Artery Aneurysms (2017) recommend repair for symptomatic aneurysms or asymptomatic aneurysms >2 cm.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Femoral artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Axillary artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Popliteal artery | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Brachial artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) C** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
