  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When DVT lurks, ultrasound first, always!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Venous duplex ultrasound. This non-invasive, readily available, and highly accurate imaging modality is the gold standard for the initial diagnosis of deep vein thrombosis (DVT) due to its ability to directly visualize the thrombus and assess venous flow.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDeep vein thrombosis is a common and serious complication following major surgery, especially in cancer patients, due to Virchow's triad (venous stasis, endothelial injury, and hypercoagulability). Venous duplex ultrasound directly visualizes the deep veins, allowing for assessment of compressibility (a non-compressible vein is indicative of thrombus), presence of intraluminal echogenic material, and abnormalities in venous blood flow using Doppler. Its high sensitivity and specificity for proximal DVT make it the preferred first-line diagnostic tool, enabling prompt initiation of anticoagulation and prevention of pulmonary embolism.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Venography) (Incorrect): While historically considered the gold standard, venography is invasive, involves radiation and contrast dye, and carries risks such as contrast-induced nephropathy and allergic reactions. It is reserved for cases where ultrasound is inconclusive or technically difficult, not as an initial test.\nOption C (Impedence plethysmograph) (Incorrect): Impedance plethysmography is a non-invasive physiological test that detects changes in limb blood volume. It has lower sensitivity and specificity compared to ultrasound, particularly for calf DVTs, and has largely been replaced by venous duplex ultrasound.\nOption D (Radiolabeled fibrinogen) (Incorrect): This is an outdated and slow diagnostic method, taking 24-72 hours to yield results. It involves radiation and is not practical for the acute diagnosis of DVT, having been superseded by more rapid and accurate imaging techniques.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Test | Type | Advantages | Disadvantages | Role |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Venous Duplex Ultrasound | Non-invasive imaging | High sensitivity/specificity, no radiation, widely available, real-time visualization | Operator dependent, limited in obese patients or pelvic veins | First-line diagnostic test for DVT |\n| Venography | Invasive imaging | Definitive diagnosis, can visualize entire venous system | Invasive, contrast allergy, radiation, nephrotoxicity, risk of DVT induction | Reserved for inconclusive US or complex cases |\n| Impedance Plethysmography | Non-invasive physiological | Non-invasive, no radiation | Low sensitivity for calf DVT, less specific than US | Largely superseded by US, limited use |\n| Radiolabeled Fibrinogen | Nuclear medicine | Detects active thrombus formation | Slow (24-72h), radiation, not for acute diagnosis | Historical, no longer used clinically |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Venous duplex ultrasound is the initial test for suspected DVT due to its safety and accuracy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn venous duplex ultrasound, a DVT appears as an echogenic mass within the vein lumen, which renders the vein non-compressible with transducer pressure. Doppler flow studies will show absent or abnormal flow patterns distal to the thrombus.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American College of Chest Physicians (ACCP) Guidelines for Antithrombotic Therapy and Prevention of Thrombosis (e.g., 10th or 11th edition) recommend venous duplex ultrasound as the initial diagnostic test for suspected DVT.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Venography | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Venous duplex ultrasound | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Impendence plethysmograph | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Radiolabeled fibrinogen | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
