  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When Hodgkin's knocks, it often starts at the neck.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Cervical. Hodgkin's lymphoma typically presents with painless lymphadenopathy, and the cervical region is the most frequently involved site at initial diagnosis due to its extensive lymphatic drainage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHodgkin's lymphoma is characterized by its orderly, contiguous spread through lymphatic pathways. The cervical and supraclavicular lymph nodes are often the first to be affected, accounting for 60-80% of initial presentations. This predilection is thought to be due to the rich lymphatic drainage of the head and neck region. Patients may also present with \"B symptoms\" (fever, night sweats, weight loss) or pruritus, but localized lymphadenopathy is the hallmark.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Abdominal) (Incorrect): While abdominal (often retroperitoneal) lymphadenopathy can occur, it is less common as the initial presenting site compared to cervical nodes. It often indicates more advanced disease.\nOption C (Axillary) (Incorrect): Axillary lymph node involvement is seen in a significant minority of cases (around 10-20%) but is less frequent than cervical involvement at presentation.\nOption D (Mediastinal) (Incorrect): Mediastinal involvement is very common in Hodgkin's lymphoma, often seen in conjunction with cervical disease, but cervical nodes are still the single most common *initial* site of enlargement. Mediastinal masses can be asymptomatic or cause cough/dyspnea.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hodgkin's Lymphoma | Non-Hodgkin's Lymphoma |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Spread Pattern** | Contiguous, orderly | Non-contiguous, unpredictable |\n| **Common Initial Site** | Cervical/Supraclavicular | Extranodal sites, GI, skin, bone marrow |\n| **B Symptoms** | More common | Less common, but can occur |\n| **Reed-Sternberg Cells** | Present | Absent |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think \"C\" for Cervical, the most common initial site in Hodgkin's.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or PET scans, enlarged, often bulky, metabolically active cervical lymph nodes would be evident. PET-CT is crucial for staging and assessing metabolic activity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Hodgkin Lymphoma (2023): These guidelines recommend comprehensive staging including PET/CT, emphasizing the importance of identifying all involved nodal and extranodal sites, with cervical nodes being a primary focus.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Abdominal | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cervical | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Axillary | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Mediastinal | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
