  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 C-cells in the thyroid secrete calcitonin: Calcium's counter-regulator!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The correct answer is A, Thyroid gland. Calcitonin is a crucial hormone involved in calcium homeostasis, and its primary site of production is the thyroid gland, specifically by specialized cells within it.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCalcitonin is produced by the parafollicular cells, also known as C-cells, which are neuroendocrine cells located within the thyroid gland. These cells are distinct from the follicular cells that produce thyroid hormones (T3 and T4). Calcitonin's main physiological role is to lower blood calcium levels by inhibiting osteoclast activity, thereby reducing bone resorption, and by decreasing renal tubular reabsorption of calcium and phosphate. This mechanism is antagonistic to parathyroid hormone (PTH).\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): The parathyroid glands secrete parathyroid hormone (PTH), which acts to *raise* blood calcium levels, opposite to calcitonin.\nOption C (Incorrect): The adrenal glands produce hormones like cortisol, aldosterone, and catecholamines, none of which are calcitonin.\nOption D (Incorrect): Ovaries produce female sex hormones like estrogen and progesterone, not calcitonin.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hormone | Gland of Origin | Primary Function | Regulation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Calcitonin | Thyroid (C-cells) | Lowers blood Ca2+ | High serum Ca2+ |\n| Parathyroid Hormone (PTH) | Parathyroid | Raises blood Ca2+ | Low serum Ca2+ |\n| Thyroid Hormones (T3/T4) | Thyroid (follicular cells) | Regulate metabolism | TSH from pituitary |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Calcitonin comes from C-cells in the thyroid; PTH from parathyroid glands.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring thyroidectomy, C-cells are microscopically identifiable within the thyroid parenchyma. Medullary thyroid carcinoma, a malignancy of C-cells, is associated with elevated calcitonin levels and can be visualized on imaging as a thyroid nodule.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines (e.g., 2015, 2023 for MTC): These guidelines discuss the importance of calcitonin as a biomarker for medullary thyroid carcinoma, highlighting its origin from thyroid C-cells.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Thyroid gland. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Parathyroid gland. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Adrenal | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Ovaries | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
