  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hard, mobile, 45? Get a cell sample, don't just look.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is FNAC. For a palpable breast lump, the immediate next step after clinical examination is typically to obtain a tissue diagnosis, and FNAC is a minimally invasive and rapid method to achieve this. This approach allows for initial characterization of the lump without resorting to more invasive procedures prematurely.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFNAC (Fine Needle Aspiration Cytology) is a crucial component of the 'triple assessment' for breast lumps, which includes clinical examination, imaging (mammography/USG), and tissue sampling. It involves aspirating cells from the lump using a fine needle, which are then examined under a microscope. This provides a cytological diagnosis, differentiating between benign and malignant lesions, and can guide further management. Its advantages include being quick, relatively painless, and cost-effective, making it an excellent initial tissue sampling method for a palpable mass.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (USG) (Incorrect): USG (ultrasonography) is an imaging modality that helps characterize the lump (e.g., solid vs. cystic, size, margins) but does not provide a definitive tissue diagnosis. While it's part of the triple assessment, it's not the 'next investigation' for tissue sampling.\nOption C (Mammography) (Incorrect): Mammography is also an imaging modality, primarily used for screening and further characterization of breast lesions. In a 45-year-old, breast density might limit its sensitivity, and it does not provide a tissue diagnosis. It would typically be performed alongside or before tissue sampling.\nOption D (Excision biopsy) (Incorrect): Excision biopsy is a surgical procedure to remove the entire lump for histological diagnosis. It is too invasive as the initial 'next investigation' for a palpable lump without prior less invasive tissue sampling (like FNAC or core biopsy) or imaging characterization.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Investigation | Type | Pros | Cons | Role in Breast Lump Assessment |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **FNAC** | Cytology | Minimally invasive, quick, low cost, rapid results | Can have false negatives, limited architectural information | Initial tissue diagnosis for palpable lumps |\n| **Core Biopsy** | Histology | Provides architectural information, higher diagnostic accuracy than FNAC | More invasive than FNAC, requires local anesthetic | Definitive tissue diagnosis, often preferred for suspicious lesions |\n| **USG** | Imaging | Differentiates solid from cystic, guides biopsies, no radiation | Operator dependent, no tissue diagnosis | Characterizes lump, guides FNAC/core biopsy |\n| **Mammography** | Imaging | Detects non-palpable lesions, microcalcifications | Radiation exposure, reduced sensitivity in dense breasts | Screening, further characterization of suspicious lesions |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Palpable breast lump? Get tissue first, then decide on surgery.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn USG, a hard, mobile lump might appear as a solid mass with varying features (e.g., well-circumscribed for fibroadenoma, irregular for malignancy). Mammography might show a mass with or without associated calcifications or architectural distortion. FNAC would involve visualizing the needle entering the lump, often guided by palpation or ultrasound.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Breast Cancer Screening and Diagnosis (e.g., 2023/2024) recommend a 'triple assessment' (clinical examination, imaging, and tissue sampling) for any palpable breast mass.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | FNAC | ✅ Correct |\n| B | USG | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Mammography. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Excision biopsy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
