  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 MRM: Major muscle stays, minor muscle goes.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Pectoralis major. Modified radical mastectomy (MRM) is a surgical procedure for breast cancer that involves the removal of the entire breast, axillary lymph nodes, and pectoralis minor muscle, but importantly, it spares the pectoralis major muscle.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nModified radical mastectomy (MRM) represents an evolution from the Halsted radical mastectomy, aiming to achieve similar oncologic outcomes with less morbidity. The key distinction of MRM is the preservation of the pectoralis major muscle. This preservation significantly improves postoperative shoulder function, reduces arm lymphedema, and offers a better cosmetic outcome compared to the radical mastectomy. The procedure still involves a complete mastectomy (removal of all breast tissue, including the nipple-areola complex) and an axillary lymph node dissection (typically levels I and II, sometimes III), often requiring the division or removal of the pectoralis minor muscle to access the higher axillary nodes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): The pectoralis minor muscle is typically removed or transected during a modified radical mastectomy to provide adequate access for a thorough axillary lymph node dissection.\nOption C (Incorrect): Axillary lymph nodes are a primary target for removal in a modified radical mastectomy, as the procedure includes an axillary lymph node dissection (ALND) to stage the cancer and remove potential metastatic disease.\nOption D (Incorrect): The nipple-areola complex is part of the entire breast tissue removed in a standard modified radical mastectomy, unless a nipple-sparing mastectomy is specifically performed, which is a different procedure.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Mastectomy Type | Breast Tissue | Nipple-Areola Complex | Pectoralis Major | Pectoralis Minor | Axillary Lymph Nodes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Radical Mastectomy | Removed | Removed | Removed | Removed | Removed |\n| Modified Radical Mastectomy | Removed | Removed | Spared | Removed/Divided | Removed |\n| Simple/Total Mastectomy | Removed | Removed | Spared | Spared | Spared (unless sentinel node) |\n| Skin-Sparing Mastectomy | Removed | Removed | Spared | Spared | Spared (unless sentinel node) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: MRM spares the pectoralis major, but removes the minor.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, during a modified radical mastectomy, the pectoralis major muscle is carefully identified and preserved, lying deep to the breast tissue. The pectoralis minor muscle, however, is often encountered and either divided or resected to allow full access to the axillary contents for lymph node dissection. The long thoracic and thoracodorsal nerves, which run along the chest wall and supply the latissimus dorsi and serratus anterior muscles respectively, are meticulously identified and preserved to prevent functional deficits.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (Version 1.2024) recommend modified radical mastectomy as a surgical option for invasive breast cancer, particularly when breast conservation is not feasible or desired.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pectoralis major. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Pectoralis minor. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Axillary lymph nodes. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Nipple. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
