  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Thyroglossal cysts: they move, they're midline, and Sistrunk's is the key!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A because thyroglossal cysts are embryological remnants of the thyroglossal duct, which maintains a connection to the tongue base, causing them to move with deglutition. The question asks for the exception, making the statement \"Does not move with deglutition\" the false one.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThyroglossal cysts arise from the incomplete involution of the thyroglossal duct, which descends from the foramen cecum at the base of the tongue to the thyroid gland. This persistent tract often passes through or intimately associates with the hyoid bone. This anatomical connection explains the characteristic upward movement of the cyst with tongue protrusion and swallowing, a key diagnostic feature.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): This statement is true. The embryological connection of the thyroglossal duct to the tongue base causes the cyst to elevate with tongue protrusion.\nOption C (Incorrect): This statement is true. Sistrunk's operation, which involves excision of the cyst, the central portion of the hyoid bone, and the tract up to the foramen cecum, is the definitive treatment to prevent recurrence.\nOption D (Incorrect): This statement is true. While thyroglossal cysts can occur anywhere along the migratory path of the thyroid gland, the subhyoid region is indeed the most common location.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Thyroglossal Cyst | Branchial Cleft Cyst | Cystic Hygroma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Origin** | Thyroglossal duct remnant | Branchial arch remnant | Lymphatic malformation |\n| **Location** | Midline neck, often subhyoid | Lateral neck, anterior to SCM | Lateral neck, posterior triangle |\n| **Movement** | Moves with deglutition/tongue protrusion | No movement with deglutition | No movement with deglutition |\n| **Treatment** | Sistrunk's operation | Excision | Sclerotherapy/Excision |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Midline neck mass moving with tongue? Think thyroglossal cyst.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or CT, a thyroglossal cyst appears as a well-defined, anechoic or hypoechoic midline neck mass. Intraoperatively, the key is to identify and excise the tract extending through the hyoid bone to the foramen cecum.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology—Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) guidelines for pediatric neck masses (2012). These recommend complete surgical excision, typically Sistrunk's procedure, for symptomatic or infected cysts.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Does not move with deglutition. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Move with protrusion of tongue. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Sistrunk's operation is treatment of choice. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Most common site is Subhyoid region. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
