  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bloody nipple? Don't panic, but do investigate!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Ductal papilloma. This is the most common cause of spontaneous, unilateral, bloody nipple discharge, particularly in premenopausal women. It represents a benign proliferation within a lactiferous duct.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuctal papillomas are benign epithelial growths that arise within the lactiferous ducts, often in the subareolar region. Their friable nature and rich vascular supply make them prone to bleeding into the ductal lumen, leading to the characteristic bloody or serosanguinous discharge. This discharge is typically spontaneous, unilateral, and often originates from a single duct orifice, making it a classic presentation for this condition.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Carcinoma breast): While breast carcinoma can cause bloody nipple discharge, it is less common than ductal papilloma as the primary cause. Malignant discharge is more often associated with a palpable mass, skin changes, or nipple retraction.\nOption C (Paget's disease): Paget's disease of the nipple is a rare form of breast cancer presenting primarily with eczematous changes of the nipple and areola (itching, scaling, crusting). Bloody discharge is not its most common or primary presentation, though it can occur if ulceration is present.\nOption D (Cystosarcoma phylloides): Phylloides tumors are fibroepithelial tumors that typically present as a rapidly growing, palpable breast mass. Nipple discharge, especially bloody discharge, is an extremely rare presentation for these tumors.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Ductal Papilloma | Breast Carcinoma | Paget's Disease of Nipple |\n| :---------------------- | :--------------------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------------- |\n| **Commonness** | Most common cause of bloody discharge | Less common than papilloma for discharge alone | Rare |\n| **Discharge Type** | Spontaneous, unilateral, often bloody/serosang. | Spontaneous, unilateral, bloody, serous, or clear | Less common, may be serous/bloody if ulcerated |\n| **Associated Findings** | No mass, sometimes subareolar mass | Palpable mass, skin changes, retraction | Eczematous changes, itching, scaling, crusting |\n| **Pathology** | Benign epithelial proliferation within duct | Malignant epithelial cells | Intraepithelial adenocarcinoma of nipple |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bloody nipple discharge = think benign papilloma first, but always rule out cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nMammography is often normal or shows non-specific findings. Ultrasound may reveal a dilated duct with an intraductal mass. Ductography (galactography) can visualize the filling defect within the duct. In the OR, microdochectomy (excision of the involved duct) is the definitive diagnostic and therapeutic procedure.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Breast Surgeons (ASBrS) 2016 Consensus Guideline on Nipple Discharge: Recommends evaluation of pathologic nipple discharge (spontaneous, unilateral, persistent, from a single duct, bloody/serous) with imaging and often surgical excision.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Carcinoma breast. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Ductal papilloma. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Paget's disease. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cystosarcoma phylloides | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
