  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 FNAC can't see invasion; surgery reveals follicular cancer's true nature.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nFNAC is a cornerstone in thyroid nodule evaluation, but its utility varies significantly depending on the pathology. This question highlights a critical limitation: FNAC cannot definitively diagnose follicular carcinoma because it cannot assess capsular or vascular invasion, which are the hallmarks of malignancy for follicular lesions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe definitive diagnosis of follicular carcinoma relies on histological examination of the entire lesion to identify capsular and/or vascular invasion. FNAC, by its nature, provides only a cytological sample of cells, not the architectural context of the nodule. Therefore, while FNAC can identify a \"follicular neoplasm\" or \"follicular lesion of undetermined significance,\" it cannot differentiate between a benign follicular adenoma and a malignant follicular carcinoma. This distinction necessitates surgical excision and pathological evaluation of the resected specimen.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Papillary carcinoma is highly amenable to FNAC diagnosis due to characteristic nuclear features like Orphan Annie eye nuclei, nuclear grooves, and intranuclear inclusions.\nOption C (Incorrect): Medullary carcinoma can often be diagnosed by FNAC, which may show neuroendocrine features, amyloid deposition, and positive calcitonin immunostaining.\nOption D (Incorrect): Thyroiditis, such as Hashimoto's or subacute thyroiditis, is frequently diagnosed by FNAC, revealing characteristic inflammatory cells, giant cells, or Hurthle cells.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Thyroid Pathology | FNAC Utility | Definitive Diagnosis |\n| :---------------- | :----------- | :------------------- |\n| Papillary Carcinoma | High         | Cytology often sufficient |\n| Follicular Carcinoma | Limited      | Surgical excision for histology |\n| Medullary Carcinoma | High         | Cytology often sufficient |\n| Thyroiditis         | High         | Cytology often sufficient |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Follicular carcinoma diagnosis requires invasion, which FNAC cannot assess.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, follicular carcinomas often appear as solid, hypoechoic nodules, but these features are not specific. Intraoperatively, a follicular carcinoma may appear encapsulated, similar to an adenoma, necessitating careful pathological examination of the resected specimen for capsular/vascular invasion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines 2015 (updated 2017, 2023): These guidelines emphasize that FNAC results for follicular neoplasms (Bethesda Category IV) require surgical excision (lobectomy or total thyroidectomy) for definitive diagnosis due to the inability of cytology to assess invasion.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Papillary carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Follicular carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Medullary carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Thyroiditis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
