  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Three arteries feed the adrenal, keeping its hormones in the lead!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, as the right suprarenal gland, like its left counterpart, receives a robust arterial supply from three distinct sources. This rich vascularization is essential for its high metabolic activity and continuous hormone production.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe suprarenal glands are uniquely supplied by three sets of arteries: the superior suprarenal arteries (branches of the inferior phrenic artery), the middle suprarenal artery (a direct branch from the aorta), and the inferior suprarenal artery (a branch of the renal artery). This multi-source arterial supply ensures consistent perfusion, critical for the endocrine functions of the adrenal cortex and medulla, regardless of variations in regional blood flow.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The right suprarenal gland is typically pyramidal or triangular in shape, not oval. The left suprarenal gland is more crescentic or semilunar.\nOption B (Incorrect): The right suprarenal gland lies posterior and slightly lateral to the inferior vena cava (IVC), not anterior to it.\nOption C (Incorrect): The right suprarenal vein drains directly into the inferior vena cava (IVC). The left suprarenal vein drains into the left renal vein.\nOption D (Incorrect): The right suprarenal gland is retroperitoneal and lies in direct contact with the bare area of the liver, not completely separated by peritoneum.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Right Suprarenal Gland | Left Suprarenal Gland |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Shape** | Pyramidal/Triangular | Crescentic/Semilunar |\n| **Venous Drainage** | Directly into IVC | Into Left Renal Vein |\n| **Relation to IVC** | Posterior/Lateral | No direct relation |\n| **Arterial Supply** | Superior, Middle, Inferior Suprarenal Arteries (3 sources) | Superior, Middle, Inferior Suprarenal Arteries (3 sources) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember the 'rule of three' for suprarenal arterial supply.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn axial CT imaging, the right adrenal gland typically appears as an inverted 'V' or 'Y' shape, situated posterior to the IVC and medial to the right lobe of the liver. Intraoperatively, its retroperitoneal location and rich vascularity are key considerations during adrenalectomy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Endocrine Surgeons (AAES) Guidelines for the Surgical Management of Adrenal Tumors (2019): These guidelines implicitly rely on a thorough understanding of adrenal anatomy, including vascular supply, for safe and effective surgical planning and execution.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Is oval in shape | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lies anterior to inferior vena cava | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Drains into the right renal vein | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Is usually completely separated from liver by the peritoneum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Is supplied by three arteries | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
