  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 2B has neuromas, 2A has parathyroids!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Hyperparathyroidism. This question tests the specific components of Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia type 2B (MEN 2B) syndrome, highlighting the key differentiating features from MEN 2A.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMEN 2B is a distinct autosomal dominant syndrome characterized by the triad of medullary thyroid carcinoma (MTC), pheochromocytoma, and mucocutaneous ganglioneuromatosis (multiple neuromas on lips, tongue, and oral mucosa). Patients often also exhibit a Marfanoid habitus. Hyperparathyroidism, while a component of MEN 2A, is notably absent in MEN 2B, making it the distinguishing feature in this context.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Multiple neuromas on the lips, tongue, and oral mucosa are a classic and defining feature of MEN 2B, often presenting early in life.\nOption C (Incorrect): Medullary thyroid carcinoma (MTC) is the most aggressive and life-threatening component, present in nearly all MEN 2B patients.\nOption D (Incorrect): Pheochromocytoma is a common component of MEN 2B, occurring in about 50% of patients, and requires careful management due to its potential for hypertensive crises.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | MEN 2A | MEN 2B |\n|---|---|---|\n| Medullary Thyroid Carcinoma (MTC) | Yes | Yes |\n| Pheochromocytoma | Yes | Yes |\n| Primary Hyperparathyroidism | Yes | No |\n| Mucocutaneous Neuromas | No | Yes |\n| Marfanoid Habitus | No | Yes |\n| Cutaneous Lichen Amyloidosis | Yes | No |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: MEN 2B is MTC, pheo, neuromas, Marfanoid; MEN 2A adds hyperparathyroidism.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPreoperative imaging for MEN 2B includes neck ultrasound for MTC, CT/MRI of the adrenals for pheochromocytoma, and careful clinical examination for characteristic neuromas and Marfanoid habitus. Intraoperatively, bilateral adrenalectomy may be required for pheochromocytoma, and total thyroidectomy with central neck dissection is standard for MTC.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for the Management of Medullary Thyroid Carcinoma (2015) recommend genetic testing for RET proto-oncogene mutations in all MTC patients and screening for pheochromocytoma and hyperparathyroidism based on the specific MEN subtype.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Multiple neuromas on the lips , Toungue and oral mucosa | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hyperparathyroidism | ✅ Correct |\n| C | MTC ( medullary thyroid carcinoma) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Pheochromocytoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) primary ‫ من غير تفصيل مثل مااالغلب عارف هي‬MEN 2 ‫مالحظه‬ thyroid carcinoma, hyperparathyroidism, m** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
