  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 MEN 2A: MTC, Pheo, Parathyroid – the classic triad, no pituitary!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. This question tests knowledge of Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia (MEN) syndromes, specifically MEN type 2A. MEN 2A is characterized by a classic triad of medullary thyroid carcinoma, pheochromocytoma, and primary hyperparathyroidism (due to parathyroid hyperplasia or adenoma), making pituitary involvement an incorrect association.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMEN 2A is an autosomal dominant disorder caused by germline mutations in the *RET* proto-oncogene. This gene encodes a receptor tyrosine kinase involved in cell growth and differentiation. Specific mutations in *RET* lead to the unregulated activation of this receptor, driving the development of these neuroendocrine tumors. The presence of medullary thyroid carcinoma (MTC) is nearly universal, pheochromocytoma occurs in about 50% of cases, and primary hyperparathyroidism in 15-30%. Understanding the genetic basis and the specific tumor types is crucial for diagnosis, screening, and management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Medullary thyroid carcinoma is a defining and almost universal component of MEN type 2A.\nOption B (Incorrect): Pheochromocytoma is a common and significant component of MEN type 2A, occurring in approximately 50% of patients.\nOption C (Incorrect): Parathyroid adenoma or hyperplasia, leading to primary hyperparathyroidism, is a recognized component of MEN type 2A.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Syndrome | Components | Gene |\n|---|---|---|\n| MEN 1 | Pituitary adenoma, Parathyroid hyperplasia, Pancreatic tumors (3 Ps) | *MEN1* |\n| MEN 2A | Medullary Thyroid Carcinoma, Pheochromocytoma, Parathyroid hyperplasia | *RET* |\n| MEN 2B | Medullary Thyroid Carcinoma, Pheochromocytoma, Mucosal neuromas, Marfanoid habitus | *RET* |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: MEN 2A is MTC, Pheo, Parathyroid. No pituitary!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor MTC, neck ultrasound is the initial imaging, followed by CT/MRI for staging. Pheochromocytoma is localized with CT/MRI of the abdomen/pelvis and functional imaging like MIBG or PET scans. Parathyroid disease is evaluated with sestamibi scans and neck ultrasound.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for the Management of Patients with Medullary Thyroid Carcinoma (2015). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for screening, diagnosis, and management of MTC, including genetic testing for *RET* mutations in all MTC patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Medullary thyroid carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pheochromocytoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Parathyroid adenoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Pituitary | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
