  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When MTC runs in the family, check the adrenals before the neck!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The correct answer is Pheochromocytoma. A family history of medullary thyroid carcinoma (MTC) strongly suggests Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia type 2 (MEN2), where pheochromocytoma is a common and critical cause of hypertension.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPheochromocytomas are neuroendocrine tumors of the adrenal medulla that secrete excessive catecholamines (epinephrine, norepinephrine), leading to paroxysmal or sustained hypertension. In the context of MEN2, these tumors are often bilateral and multifocal, arising from germline mutations in the RET proto-oncogene. The catecholamine surge causes vasoconstriction, increased heart rate, and cardiac contractility, directly resulting in hypertension.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Renal artery stenosis is a cause of renovascular hypertension but has no direct genetic link to medullary thyroid carcinoma.\nOption B (Incorrect): Glomerulonephritis is a kidney disease that can cause hypertension, but it is not associated with the MEN2 syndrome or MTC.\nOption C (Incorrect): Cushing syndrome involves excessive cortisol production, leading to hypertension, but it is a distinct endocrine disorder not typically part of the MEN2 spectrum.\nOption D (Incorrect): Hyperparathyroidism, specifically primary hyperparathyroidism, can be a component of MEN2A, causing hypercalcemia. While severe hypercalcemia can indirectly affect blood pressure, it is not the primary or most common cause of hypertension in MEN2; pheochromocytoma is.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | MEN2A | MEN2B | Sporadic Pheochromocytoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Components | MTC, Pheochromocytoma, Primary Hyperparathyroidism | MTC, Pheochromocytoma, Mucosal Neuromas, Marfanoid habitus | Isolated tumor, no MTC or hyperparathyroidism |\n| Gene | RET proto-oncogene (germline) | RET proto-oncogene (germline, specific codon) | Often somatic mutations (e.g., RET, VHL, SDHB/D) |\n| Hypertension | Common, due to pheochromocytoma | Common, due to pheochromocytoma | Common, due to catecholamine excess |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: MTC + HTN = MEN2 until proven otherwise. Screen for pheo first!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging for pheochromocytoma typically involves CT or MRI of the adrenal glands, often with functional imaging like MIBG or PET scans (e.g., with 18F-FDOPA). Intraoperatively, careful dissection is crucial to avoid catecholamine release, and bilateral adrenalectomy may be necessary for bilateral tumors.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for Medullary Thyroid Carcinoma (2023): Recommend screening for pheochromocytoma in all patients with MTC, especially those with a family history, prior to thyroidectomy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Renal artery stenosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Glomerulernephritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Cushing syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hyperparathyroidism | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Pheochromocytoma | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
