  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pheochromocytoma: The only thing low is your suspicion if you miss it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies hypoglycemia as not being a typical clinical feature of pheochromocytoma. The excessive catecholamine release characteristic of pheochromocytoma primarily leads to hyperglycemia, not hypoglycemia, due to its profound metabolic effects.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPheochromocytomas are tumors of the adrenal medulla or extra-adrenal paraganglia that secrete excessive amounts of catecholamines, primarily norepinephrine and epinephrine. These hormones exert significant metabolic effects, including increased glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis in the liver, decreased insulin secretion, and peripheral insulin resistance. The net result is an elevation in blood glucose levels, leading to hyperglycemia, which is a common finding in patients with pheochromocytoma. Hypoglycemia, conversely, is not a direct consequence of catecholamine excess and would be an atypical presentation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Headache is a very common symptom, often severe and throbbing, due to paroxysmal or sustained hypertension caused by catecholamine-induced vasoconstriction.\nOption C (Incorrect): Anxiety, panic attacks, and a sense of impending doom are frequent manifestations due to the direct central nervous system effects and systemic sympathetic overstimulation by catecholamines.\nOption D (Incorrect): Palpitations are a classic symptom, resulting from the direct chronotropic and inotropic effects of catecholamines on the heart, leading to tachycardia and increased contractility.\nOption E (Incorrect): Facial plethora, or flushing, can occur due to episodic vasodilation or sustained hypertension, which are common features of catecholamine excess.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Clinical Feature | Pheochromocytoma Presentation | Explanation |\n| :--------------- | :---------------------------- | :---------- |\n| Hypertension     | Paroxysmal or sustained       | Catecholamine-induced vasoconstriction |\n| Palpitations     | Tachycardia, arrhythmia       | Direct cardiac stimulation by catecholamines |\n| Headache         | Severe, throbbing             | Hypertension and cerebral vasoconstriction |\n| Sweating         | Profuse, generalized          | Sympathetic nervous system activation |\n| Anxiety          | Panic attacks, apprehension   | CNS effects of catecholamines |\n| Hyperglycemia    | Common                        | Increased glycogenolysis, gluconeogenesis, insulin resistance |\n| Hypoglycemia     | Atypical/Rare                 | Not directly caused by catecholamine excess; usually hyperglycemia |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember the classic triad: Palpitations, Headache, Episodic Sweating (PHE).\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or MRI, pheochromocytomas typically appear as well-circumscribed adrenal masses, often with high signal intensity on T2-weighted MRI. Intraoperatively, these tumors are often highly vascular, and manipulation can lead to dramatic fluctuations in blood pressure, necessitating careful anesthetic management.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEndocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline for the Diagnosis and Management of Pheochromocytoma and Paraganglioma (2014) recommends biochemical testing for all patients with suspected pheochromocytoma.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Headache | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hypoglycemia | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Anxiety | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Palpatation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Facial plethora | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
