  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't ignore spontaneous nipple discharge; it's often a red flag!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 'A - Not spontaneous' because pathological nipple discharge is, by definition, spontaneous. This characteristic is crucial for differentiating it from benign, physiological discharge which typically requires expression.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPathological nipple discharge arises spontaneously, often from a single duct, and is persistent. Its spontaneous nature, along with other features like unilateral presentation, bloody or serosanguineous appearance, and non-cyclical occurrence, signals an underlying pathological process such as an intraductal papilloma or, more concerningly, carcinoma. This distinction guides the need for further diagnostic workup.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Unilateral: Pathological discharge is typically unilateral, originating from a single breast and often a single duct, making this a characteristic feature.\nOption C (Incorrect): Associated with mass: While not always present, pathological discharge can be associated with a palpable mass, especially in cases of malignancy, and warrants investigation.\nOption D (Incorrect): Positive hem occult test: Pathological discharge is frequently bloody (sanguineous or serosanguineous), so a positive hem occult test is a common finding and indicates its pathological nature.\nOption E (Incorrect): Non-cyclical: Pathological discharge is generally non-cyclical, meaning it does not fluctuate with menstrual cycles, unlike some physiological discharges.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Pathological Nipple Discharge | Physiological Nipple Discharge |\n|---|---|---|\n| Spontaneity | Spontaneous | Requires expression |\n| Laterality | Unilateral, single duct | Bilateral, multiple ducts |\n| Color | Bloody, serous, serosanguineous | Milky, green, yellow, brown |\n| Etiology | Papilloma, duct ectasia, carcinoma | Hormonal, medications, fibrocystic changes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Spontaneous, unilateral, bloody nipple discharge demands thorough investigation for underlying pathology.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging typically involves mammography and targeted ultrasound of the breast and retroareolar region. Ductography (galactography) can delineate intraductal lesions, while microdochectomy is often performed for definitive diagnosis and treatment of persistent pathological discharge.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 164 (2016) on Management of Nipple Discharge. It recommends evaluation for spontaneous, persistent, unilateral, or bloody discharge.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | A Not spontaneous | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Unilateral | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Associated with mass | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Positive hem occult test | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Non-cyclical | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
