  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Papillary loves lymph, follicular loves blood.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, as papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC) primarily metastasizes via lymphatic spread to regional lymph nodes, not hematogenously. Hematogenous spread is characteristic of follicular thyroid carcinoma, making statement C the incorrect one about PTC.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPapillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC) is the most common differentiated thyroid cancer and typically spreads via the lymphatic system to cervical lymph nodes. This propensity for lymphatic metastasis often necessitates therapeutic or prophylactic central and lateral neck dissections during surgery. In contrast, follicular thyroid carcinoma (FTC) is known for its hematogenous spread, often to distant sites like bone, lung, and brain, without necessarily involving regional lymph nodes. Understanding these distinct metastatic patterns is crucial for surgical planning and prognostication.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This statement is true. Papillary thyroid carcinoma is generally the slowest growing malignant tumor of the thyroid, often presenting as an indolent mass.\nOption B (Incorrect): This statement is true. Papillary thyroid carcinoma can dedifferentiate over time, particularly in older patients or with recurrent disease, into a more aggressive anaplastic variety.\nOption D (Incorrect): This statement is true. Papillary thyroid carcinoma cells retain TSH receptors, and their growth is often stimulated by TSH. This is the rationale behind TSH suppression therapy post-thyroidectomy.\nOption E (Incorrect): This statement is true. While generally indolent, PTC tends to exhibit more aggressive features and a worse prognosis in older patients, including a higher likelihood of dedifferentiation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Papillary Thyroid Carcinoma (PTC) | Follicular Thyroid Carcinoma (FTC) | Anaplastic Thyroid Carcinoma (ATC) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Primary Metastasis | Lymphatic (regional nodes) | Hematogenous (bone, lung) | Direct invasion, rapid distant mets |\n| Growth Rate | Slowest | Slow to moderate | Very rapid |\n| TSH Dependence | Yes (most) | Yes (most) | No (dedifferentiated) |\n| Prognosis | Excellent | Good | Very Poor |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Lymphatic spread for papillary, hematogenous for follicular.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, PTC often appears as a hypoechoic nodule with microcalcifications, irregular margins, and increased vascularity. Intraoperatively, enlarged, firm, and often cystic lymph nodes in the central or lateral neck compartments are highly suspicious for metastatic PTC.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines 2015: These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the management of differentiated thyroid cancer, including surgical approaches based on tumor characteristics and nodal involvement.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It's slowest growing malignant tumor of the thyroid | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It may change to anaplastic variety | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | It metastasized primarily by hematogenous spread | ✅ Correct |\n| D | It depends on TSH stimulation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | It has tendecy to become more malignant with age | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
