  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it comes to lung cancer, NSCLC reigns supreme in prevalence.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies Non-Small Cell Lung Carcinoma (NSCLC) as the most common type of lung cancer, which is a fundamental epidemiological fact in oncology. This statement is true, making it the best choice among the given options. Understanding the prevalence of NSCLC is crucial for diagnosis and management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLung cancer is broadly classified into two main types: Non-Small Cell Lung Carcinoma (NSCLC) and Small Cell Lung Carcinoma (SCLC). NSCLC accounts for approximately 85% of all lung cancers, encompassing adenocarcinoma, squamous cell carcinoma, and large cell carcinoma. SCLC, while less common (10-15%), is typically more aggressive and strongly associated with smoking. Understanding this primary classification is crucial for diagnosis, staging, and treatment planning in thoracic surgery and oncology.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Lung cancer is strongly related to various occupational exposures, including asbestos, radon, arsenic, chromium, and nickel, which significantly increase the risk.\nOption C (Incorrect): Smoking is the single most significant risk factor for lung cancer, responsible for about 85-90% of all cases, including both NSCLC and SCLC.\nOption D (Incorrect): Pancoast syndrome, characterized by shoulder pain, Horner's syndrome, and arm weakness, is a classic presentation of a superior sulcus tumor, which is a type of lung cancer (often NSCLC).\nOption E (Incorrect): Treatment for lung cancer is typically aggressive, involving surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, targeted therapy, or immunotherapy, depending on the stage and type. Conservative treatment is generally reserved for palliative care in very advanced stages or for patients with significant comorbidities.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Non-Small Cell Lung Carcinoma (NSCLC) | Small Cell Lung Carcinoma (SCLC) |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------------ | :------------------------------- |\n| **Prevalence** | ~85% of all lung cancers | ~10-15% of all lung cancers |\n| **Histology** | Adenocarcinoma, Squamous, Large Cell | Small, oat-shaped cells |\n| **Growth Rate** | Slower | Rapid |\n| **Smoking Link** | Strong, but less than SCLC | Very strong |\n| **Treatment** | Surgery, Chemo, Radiation, Targeted | Chemo, Radiation (limited stage) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: NSCLC is the most common lung cancer type.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, lung cancer often appears as a solitary pulmonary nodule, mass, or consolidation. Features like spiculated margins, lobulation, and cavitation can suggest malignancy. PET-CT is crucial for staging, showing metabolic activity. Intraoperatively, the tumor's size, location, and involvement of adjacent structures (e.g., chest wall, mediastinum) are assessed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Non-Small Cell Lung Cancer (Version 4.2023)\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Non small lung carcinoma is the most common cause | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Not related to occupation.... | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Not related to the smoking | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Not produce pancotes syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Conservative treatment .... | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
