  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Two for Mitral, Three for the rest – don't get it wrong on the test!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, the Mitral valve, because it is the only heart valve that normally possesses two leaflets, distinguishing it from the other three valves which are typically tricuspid. This fundamental anatomical difference is crucial for understanding cardiac physiology.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe heart's four valves are critical for unidirectional blood flow. The aortic and pulmonary valves are semilunar valves, located at the exits of the ventricles, and both normally have three cusps or leaflets. The tricuspid valve, an atrioventricular valve, separates the right atrium and ventricle and also typically has three leaflets. In contrast, the mitral valve, the other atrioventricular valve, separates the left atrium and ventricle and is uniquely bicuspid, meaning it has only two leaflets. This bicuspid structure is a normal variant and essential for its function in the high-pressure left heart.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The Aortic valve normally has three leaflets, controlling blood flow from the left ventricle to the aorta.\nOption C (Incorrect): The Tricuspid valve normally has three leaflets, regulating blood flow from the right atrium to the right ventricle.\nOption D (Incorrect): The Pulmonary valve normally has three leaflets, directing blood flow from the right ventricle to the pulmonary artery.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Valve Name | Location | Number of Leaflets (Normal) | Type |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Mitral Valve | Between Left Atrium & Left Ventricle | Two (Bicuspid) | Atrioventricular |\n| Tricuspid Valve | Between Right Atrium & Right Ventricle | Three (Tricuspid) | Atrioventricular |\n| Aortic Valve | Between Left Ventricle & Aorta | Three (Tricuspid) | Semilunar |\n| Pulmonary Valve | Between Right Ventricle & Pulmonary Artery | Three (Tricuspid) | Semilunar |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember the \"LAMB\" mnemonic: Left Atrial-Mitral Bicuspid.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn echocardiography, the mitral valve's two leaflets (anterior and posterior) are clearly visible, opening and closing in a fish-mouth appearance. During open-heart surgery, direct visualization confirms the bicuspid nature of the mitral valve, contrasting sharply with the three distinct cusps of the aortic, pulmonary, and tricuspid valves.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2020 ACC/AHA Guideline for the Management of Patients With Valvular Heart Disease recommends specific imaging and management strategies for all heart valves, including assessment of leaflet number and function.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Aortic valve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Mitral valve | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Tricuspid valve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Pulmonary valve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
