  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Calcium stones shine bright on KUB, 90% of the time!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 90%. This high proportion of visibility on plain KUB films is attributed to the predominant composition of most ureteric stones, which are calcium-based and thus radiopaque. Understanding stone composition is key to interpreting imaging.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe vast majority of urinary tract stones, approximately 80-85%, are composed of calcium oxalate or calcium phosphate. These calcium-containing stones have a high atomic number and density, making them readily visible as radiopaque densities on plain radiographs like the KUB. This inherent radiopacity allows for their detection, making KUB a useful initial screening tool or for monitoring known radiopaque stones, despite its lower sensitivity compared to CT.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 5% is far too low; most stones are radiopaque.\nOption B (Incorrect): 10% is significantly underestimated for the visibility of ureteric stones on KUB.\nOption C (Incorrect): 30% is still a substantial underestimation of the proportion of radiopaque stones.\nOption D (Incorrect): 70% is closer but still underestimates the true proportion, which is typically cited as 85-90%.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Stone Type        | Composition                               | Radiopacity on KUB | Notes                                       |\n|-------------------|-------------------------------------------|--------------------|---------------------------------------------|\n| Calcium Oxalate   | Calcium oxalate monohydrate/dihydrate     | Highly Radiopaque  | Most common type (75-80%)                   |\n| Calcium Phosphate | Calcium phosphate (apatite)               | Highly Radiopaque  | Often associated with hyperparathyroidism   |\n| Struvite          | Magnesium ammonium phosphate              | Moderately Radiopaque | Associated with UTIs (urea-splitting bacteria) |\n| Uric Acid         | Uric acid                                 | Radiolucent        | Not visible on KUB, seen on CT/US           |\n| Cystine           | Cystine                                   | Faintly Radiopaque | Genetic disorder, often smooth and multiple |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Most kidney stones are radiopaque on KUB due to calcium content.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a plain KUB film, radiopaque ureteric stones appear as white, dense opacities along the expected course of the ureter. While KUB can detect these, it lacks sensitivity for radiolucent stones (e.g., uric acid) and can be obscured by bowel gas. Non-contrast CT is the gold standard for diagnosing all stone types and assessing their size and location.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) and European Association of Urology (EAU) Guidelines on Urolithiasis (2023). These guidelines recommend non-contrast CT as the imaging modality of choice for acute flank pain suggestive of urolithiasis, but acknowledge KUB's role in follow-up for known radiopaque stones.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 5% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 10% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 30% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 70% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | 90% | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
