  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, scope it out and cut it out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Transurethral Resection of Bladder Tumor (TURBT). This is the essential initial step for any suspected bladder tumor, serving both diagnostic and therapeutic purposes.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTURBT is paramount for obtaining tissue for histopathological diagnosis, determining tumor grade, and assessing the depth of invasion (e.g., non-muscle invasive vs. muscle-invasive). It also serves as the primary treatment for non-muscle invasive bladder cancer by resecting all visible tumor, which is crucial for guiding subsequent management strategies.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Transurethral resection of prostate) (Incorrect): This procedure is indicated for benign prostatic hyperplasia or prostate cancer, not bladder tumors.\nOption C (Intravesicle chemo) (Incorrect): Intravesical chemotherapy is an adjuvant therapy for non-muscle invasive bladder cancer *after* initial TURBT and pathological confirmation. It is not the first diagnostic or therapeutic step.\nOption D (Intravesicle BCG) (Incorrect): Intravesical Bacillus Calmette-Guérin (BCG) is an immunotherapy used for high-risk non-muscle invasive bladder cancer *after* TURBT. It requires a definitive diagnosis and staging from TURBT.\nOption E (Cystectomy) (Incorrect): Cystectomy is a radical surgical procedure for muscle-invasive bladder cancer or recurrent high-risk non-muscle invasive bladder cancer refractory to other treatments. It is not the initial step without prior diagnosis and staging via TURBT.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Procedure | Indication | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|\n| TURBT | Suspected bladder tumor | Diagnosis, staging, primary treatment for NMIBC |\n| Intravesical Therapy (Chemo/BCG) | Adjuvant for NMIBC | Reduce recurrence/progression after TURBT |\n| Radical Cystectomy | Muscle-invasive bladder cancer, refractory NMIBC | Curative resection of bladder and surrounding structures |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: TURBT is the indispensable first step for suspected bladder cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring cystoscopy, one might observe a papillary, sessile, or nodular lesion on the bladder wall. Intraoperatively during TURBT, the surgeon aims to resect all visible tumor down to the detrusor muscle to ensure adequate staging and complete resection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines on Non-Muscle Invasive Bladder Cancer (2020) recommends TURBT as the initial diagnostic and therapeutic procedure for suspected bladder cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Transurethral resection of bladder tumor | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Transurethral resection of prostate | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Intravesicle chemo | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Intravesicle BCG | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Cystectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
