  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Calcium oxalate: The most common reason for a stone-cold stare.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Calcium oxalate. This is the most common type of renal stone, accounting for the vast majority of kidney stone cases encountered in clinical practice.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCalcium oxalate stones form when there is supersaturation of calcium and oxalate in the urine. This can be influenced by dietary factors, metabolic abnormalities such as hypercalciuria or hyperoxaluria, and inadequate fluid intake. The formation process involves crystal nucleation, growth, and aggregation within the renal collecting system, leading to the development of macroscopic stones.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Uric acid) (Incorrect): Uric acid stones are less common than calcium oxalate stones, typically associated with hyperuricemia, low urinary pH, and conditions like gout or myeloproliferative disorders.\nOption C (Cystine) (Incorrect): Cystine stones are rare, accounting for only 1-2% of all stones, and are caused by an inherited metabolic disorder (cystinuria) leading to impaired reabsorption of cystine in the renal tubules.\nOption D (Xanthine) (Incorrect): Xanthine stones are extremely rare, resulting from a genetic deficiency of xanthine oxidase, an enzyme involved in purine metabolism.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Stone Type | Prevalence | Key Characteristics | Risk Factors |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Calcium Oxalate | ~70-80% | Radiopaque, hard, often spiculated | Hypercalciuria, hyperoxaluria, dehydration |\n| Uric Acid | ~5-10% | Radiolucent (not visible on plain X-ray), often yellow/brown | Hyperuricemia, low urinary pH, gout |\n| Cystine | ~1-2% | Moderately radiopaque, hexagonal crystals | Cystinuria (genetic disorder) |\n| Struvite (Infection) | ~10-15% | Radiopaque, often staghorn calculus | Chronic UTIs with urea-splitting bacteria (e.g., Proteus) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Calcium oxalate: the undisputed king of kidney stones.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nCalcium oxalate stones are typically radiopaque and are readily visible on plain X-rays (KUB) and CT scans, appearing as bright white densities within the kidney or ureter. On ultrasound, they cast an acoustic shadow.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on the Medical Management of Kidney Stones (2014, updated 2019): Recommends metabolic evaluation for recurrent stone formers and emphasizes dietary and pharmacologic management based on stone composition, with calcium oxalate being the most common target for prevention strategies.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ca oxalate | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Uric acid | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Cystine | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Xanthine | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
