  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it comes to infant cancer, neuroblastoma is the undisputed king.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Neuroblastoma is indeed the most common malignant neoplasm diagnosed during infancy, often presenting within the first year of life. Its prevalence surpasses other pediatric tumors in this specific age group.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNeuroblastoma originates from neural crest cells, which are precursors to the sympathetic nervous system. This explains its common locations: adrenal medulla (most frequent), paraspinal ganglia in the abdomen, chest, and neck. It often presents as an abdominal mass, sometimes with systemic symptoms, and is unique for its potential for spontaneous regression in some infants, particularly those with favorable biology and stage.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Malignant teratoma) (Incorrect): While teratomas can be malignant and occur in infancy, they are far less common than neuroblastoma. They arise from germ cells and can be found in various locations.\nOption C (Wilms' tumor) (Incorrect): Wilms' tumor (nephroblastoma) is the most common renal malignancy in children, but its peak incidence is typically between 2-5 years of age, making it less common than neuroblastoma specifically in *infancy* (under 1 year).\nOption D (Hepatoblastoma) (Incorrect): Hepatoblastoma is the most common primary malignant liver tumor in children, but it is less common overall than neuroblastoma and Wilms' tumor, and its peak incidence is also slightly later than infancy, typically before age 3.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Type | Origin | Peak Age | Common Presentation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Neuroblastoma | Neural crest cells | Infancy (0-1 year) | Abdominal mass, adrenal mass, paraspinal mass |\n| Wilms' Tumor | Metanephric blastema | 2-5 years | Abdominal mass (renal), hypertension |\n| Hepatoblastoma | Hepatocytes | <3 years | Abdominal mass (liver), elevated AFP |\n| Rhabdomyosarcoma | Mesenchymal cells | Bimodal (0-5, 10-18) | Head/neck, genitourinary, extremities |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think neuroblastoma first for an infant with an abdominal mass.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/MRI), neuroblastoma often appears as an irregular, heterogeneous mass, frequently with calcifications, typically arising from the adrenal gland or retroperitoneum. Intraoperatively, it's a firm, often lobulated mass, sometimes encasing vessels.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nChildren's Oncology Group (COG) Neuroblastoma Treatment Protocols (e.g., ANBL1232, ANBL1531). These guidelines provide risk stratification and treatment recommendations based on age, stage, and biological features.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| a | Malignant teratoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| b | Neuroblastoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| c | Wilim's tumor | ❌ Incorrect |\n| d | Hepatoblastoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
