  "question": "A 55 year old male presented with sever flank pain radiating to the groin associated with nausea and vomiting. Urinalysis reveals a radioopaque 5 mm stone in the area of ureterovesical junction . Which of the following statement is true??",
  "options": {
    "a": "A likely stone composition for this patient would be uric acid",
    "b": "The stone will likely pass spontaneously with aid of increase hydration",
    "c": "Stone analysis of relatively little importance",
    "d": "Should have no Transurethral instrumentation if possible"
  },
  "answer": "D) ",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't scope a stone that's likely to go home alone!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, emphasizing conservative management for a small, distal ureteral stone. A 5mm stone at the ureterovesical junction (UVJ) has a high likelihood of spontaneous passage, making avoidance of unnecessary invasive procedures a prudent initial approach.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFor small ureteral stones, especially those 5mm or less and located distally (like at the UVJ), the spontaneous passage rate is high (up to 80-90%). The principle of \"first, do no harm\" applies here. Transurethral instrumentation, while effective, carries risks such as infection, ureteral injury, stricture formation, and the need for anesthesia. Therefore, if a stone is likely to pass on its own, conservative management with pain control, hydration, and potentially medical expulsive therapy (MET) is preferred, reserving instrumentation for failed passage, intractable pain, or signs of obstruction/infection.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Uric acid stones are typically radiolucent on plain X-ray, not radioopaque. Calcium oxalate and calcium phosphate stones are the most common radioopaque types.\nOption B (Incorrect): While increased hydration is part of conservative management, the statement \"likely pass spontaneously with aid of increase hydration\" is less precise than the need to avoid instrumentation. Medical expulsive therapy (alpha-blockers) is a more specific aid for spontaneous passage. Also, the question asks for the *most* true statement, and avoiding unnecessary instrumentation is a stronger principle here.\nOption C (Incorrect): Stone analysis is of paramount importance. It guides metabolic evaluation and helps tailor preventative strategies (dietary changes, medications) to reduce recurrence rates, which are high for kidney stone formers.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Stone Characteristic | Spontaneous Passage Rate | Management Strategy |\n| :----------------- | :----------------------- | :------------------ |\n| < 5mm, distal ureter | 80-90%                   | Conservative (MET, pain control, hydration) |\n| 5-10mm, distal ureter | 50-70%                   | Conservative vs. Intervention (URS) |\n| > 10mm, any location | < 20%                    | Intervention (URS, SWL, PCNL) |\n| Uric Acid Stone    | Radiolucent              | Alkalinization, hydration |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Small, distal stones often pass; avoid unnecessary scopes.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a KUB X-ray or CT scan, a radioopaque stone appears as a bright white density. At the ureterovesical junction (UVJ), it would be seen near the bladder, often overlying the sacroiliac joint or ischial spine.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) and European Association of Urology (EAU) Guidelines on Urolithiasis (e.g., 2023/2024). These guidelines recommend conservative management for asymptomatic or mildly symptomatic ureteral stones <10mm, especially those <5mm, with medical expulsive therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| a | A likely stone composition for this patient would be uric acid | ❌ Incorrect |\n| b | The stone will likely pass spontaneously with aid of increase hydration | ❌ Incorrect |\n| c | Stone analysis of relatively little importance | ❌ Incorrect |\n| d | Should have no Transurethral instrumentation if possible | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
