  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let a twisted tale turn into a lost testicle; differentiate early!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer, \"Positive Prehn's sign,\" is a clinical indicator that pain is relieved with elevation of the affected testicle, which is characteristic of epididymitis and typically absent or worsens in testicular torsion. This sign helps differentiate the inflammatory process of epididymitis from the ischemic event of torsion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEpididymitis is an inflammatory condition, often infectious, where the epididymis becomes swollen and tender. Elevating the testicle can provide symptomatic relief by reducing scrotal edema and improving venous drainage, thereby decreasing pressure and pain. In contrast, testicular torsion involves the twisting of the spermatic cord, leading to vascular compromise and ischemia. Elevating a torsed testicle does not alleviate the underlying vascular obstruction and may even exacerbate pain due to further manipulation of an ischemic organ. Therefore, a positive Prehn's sign strongly points towards epididymitis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Bell clapper deformity is an anatomical variation that predisposes to testicular torsion, not a sign of epididymitis.\nOption B (Incorrect): An absent cremasteric reflex is a highly sensitive and specific sign for testicular torsion, indicating nerve compromise due to ischemia, and is usually present in epididymitis.\nOption D (Incorrect): While elevated WBCs can be seen in epididymitis due to infection, they can also be elevated in the severe inflammation and tissue necrosis associated with testicular torsion, making it less specific for differentiation.\nOption E (Incorrect): Both epididymitis and testicular torsion can present with acute onset of pain. Torsion typically has a sudden, severe onset, but \"acute onset\" alone does not differentiate.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Testicular Torsion                               | Epididymitis                                     |\n| :------------------ | :----------------------------------------------- | :----------------------------------------------- |\n| Onset of Pain       | Sudden, severe                                   | Gradual, progressive                             |\n| Cremasteric Reflex  | Absent                                           | Present                                          |\n| Prehn's Sign        | Negative (no relief or worsened pain with lift)  | Positive (pain relief with lift)                 |\n| Urinalysis          | Normal                                           | Pyuria, bacteriuria (often)                      |\n| Age Group           | Neonates, adolescents (12-18 years)              | Post-pubertal males, older men                   |\n| Scrotal Swelling    | High-riding, horizontal lie                      | Diffuse, tender epididymis                       |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Prehn's sign positive? Think epididymitis. Cremasteric reflex absent? Think torsion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nScrotal ultrasound with color Doppler is the gold standard. In epididymitis, it shows increased blood flow to the epididymis and testicle. In testicular torsion, it shows absent or markedly decreased blood flow to the testicle, often with a \"whirlpool sign\" of the spermatic cord.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on the Diagnosis and Management of Testicular Torsion (2017). It recommends urgent scrotal exploration for suspected torsion and emphasizes the role of Doppler ultrasound.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Presence of bell clapper deformity | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Absent of cremastric reflex | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Postive perhn's sign | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Elevated WBC | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Acute onset of pain | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
