  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 A numb testis often signals a tumor's presence.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Early and complete loss of testicular sensation is a classic, albeit less common, presentation of a testicular tumor. This occurs due to the tumor's growth within the confined tunica albuginea, leading to compression or direct invasion of the sensory nerve fibers.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTesticular tumors, particularly germ cell tumors, grow expansively within the rigid tunica albuginea. This confined space means that even relatively small tumors can exert significant pressure on the delicate sensory nerve endings and fibers supplying the testis (primarily from the genital branch of the genitofemoral nerve and autonomic plexuses). This compression or direct infiltration can lead to hypesthesia or complete anesthesia, often preceding significant pain or other overt symptoms. The 'early' aspect is crucial, as it distinguishes it from inflammatory or infectious processes where pain and hyperesthesia are more common initial complaints.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Tuberculosis typically causes painful epididymo-orchitis, often with a beaded vas deferens and sinus formation, not early sensory loss.\nOption C (Incorrect): Leprosy can cause orchitis and testicular atrophy, but its primary neurological impact is on peripheral nerves elsewhere, not typically early complete testicular sensory loss.\nOption D (Incorrect): Syphilis can manifest as a painless gummatous orchitis, causing diffuse enlargement and firmness, but not characteristically early complete loss of sensation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Sensation | Pain | Other Key Features |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Testicular Tumour | Early, complete loss (hypesthesia/anesthesia) | Often painless, dull ache/heaviness | Palpable mass, hydrocele |\n| Tuberculosis | Usually intact, or hyperesthesia if inflamed | Painful epididymo-orchitis | Beading of vas, sinus formation, sterile pyuria |\n| Leprosy | Intact (systemic neuropathy elsewhere) | Often painless orchitis | Testicular atrophy, infertility |\n| Syphilis | Intact | Painless gummatous orchitis | Diffuse enlargement, firm, rubbery testis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: A painless testicular mass with early sensory loss is a tumor until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a testicular tumor typically appears as a solid, hypoechoic, often heterogeneous mass within the testicular parenchyma. Intraoperatively, the tumor is usually a firm, irregular mass replacing normal testicular tissue, often with areas of hemorrhage or necrosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines on Testicular Cancer (2019) recommend prompt evaluation of any testicular mass, with ultrasound as the primary imaging modality.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Tuberculosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Tumour | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Leprosy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Syphilis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
