  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Time is testis: Differentiate fast, operate faster!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, as relief of pain on elevation (Prehn's sign) is a classic differentiating feature between epididymoorchitis and testicular torsion. While both conditions present with acute scrotal pain, Prehn's sign is typically positive in epididymoorchitis and negative in testicular torsion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPrehn's sign refers to the alleviation of pain when the affected testicle is elevated. In epididymoorchitis, this maneuver can reduce venous congestion and inflammation, thereby decreasing pain. Conversely, in testicular torsion, elevating the testicle does not relieve the pain, and may even exacerbate it, because the pain is due to ischemia from twisting of the spermatic cord, which is not affected by elevation. This clinical sign, along with the cremasteric reflex, is crucial for rapid differentiation and management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Pain) (Incorrect): Both testicular torsion and epididymoorchitis present with acute scrotal pain, making this a shared feature, not a differentiating one.\nOption B (Fever) (Incorrect): While fever is more common in epididymoorchitis due to infection, a low-grade fever can also be present in testicular torsion, especially if there is associated inflammation or necrosis. Therefore, its presence or absence is not a definitive differentiator.\nOption C (Skin redness) (Incorrect): Both conditions can cause scrotal erythema due to inflammation (epididymoorchitis) or ischemia and inflammation (torsion), making it a shared symptom rather than an exclusive one.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Testicular Torsion | Epididymoorchitis |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Onset** | Sudden, severe | Gradual |\n| **Pain** | Severe, constant | Variable, often less severe |\n| **Prehn's Sign** | Negative (no relief) | Positive (relief with elevation) |\n| **Cremasteric Reflex** | Absent | Present |\n| **Fever** | Uncommon, low-grade possible | Common |\n| **Urinalysis** | Normal | Pyuria, bacteriuria |\n| **Age Group** | Neonates, adolescents | Sexually active adults, older men |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Prehn's sign is positive in epididymoorchitis, negative in torsion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn Doppler ultrasound, testicular torsion shows absent or diminished blood flow to the affected testicle, while epididymoorchitis shows increased blood flow (hyperemia) to the epididymis and/or testis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on the Diagnosis and Management of Testicular Torsion (2017) recommends emergent surgical exploration for suspected torsion.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pain | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Fever | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Skin radness | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Relief of pain on elevation | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
