  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't confuse symptom relief with cancer cure!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify the modality that is NOT a primary treatment for prostate cancer. Transurethral resection of the prostate (TURP) is primarily a symptomatic treatment for prostatic obstruction, most commonly due to benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH), and not a definitive cancer treatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nProstate cancer treatment modalities aim to eradicate the cancer, control its growth, or alleviate symptoms directly related to the cancer's progression. Radical prostatectomy, hormonal therapy, brachytherapy, and external beam radiation therapy are all established methods to achieve these goals, targeting the cancer cells or the hormonal environment that supports their growth. TURP, while it removes prostate tissue, is typically performed to relieve urinary outflow obstruction, which can be caused by BPH or, less commonly, by advanced prostate cancer, but it is not considered a curative treatment for the cancer itself.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Radical prostatectomy is a definitive surgical treatment for localized prostate cancer.\nOption B (Incorrect): Hormonal Therapy is a systemic treatment used to suppress androgen production, which fuels prostate cancer growth.\nOption D (Incorrect): Brachytherapy is a form of internal radiation therapy used to treat localized prostate cancer.\nOption E (Incorrect): External beam radiation therapy is a common form of radiation therapy used to treat localized or locally advanced prostate cancer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Treatment Modality | Primary Indication | Goal |\n|---|---|---|\n| Radical Prostatectomy | Localized prostate cancer | Cure |\n| Hormonal Therapy | Advanced/metastatic prostate cancer, adjuvant to radiation | Disease control, symptom palliation |\n| Brachytherapy | Localized prostate cancer | Cure |\n| TURP | Symptomatic prostatic obstruction (BPH, advanced cancer) | Symptom relief |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: TURP treats symptoms, not the cancer itself.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring a TURP, the surgeon uses a resectoscope to shave away obstructing prostate tissue, creating a wider channel for urine flow. This is distinct from a radical prostatectomy where the entire prostate gland is removed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Prostate Cancer (2023). These guidelines outline the various treatment options for localized, regional, and metastatic prostate cancer, clearly distinguishing between curative intent therapies and palliative interventions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Radical prostatectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hormonal Therapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Transurethral resection of prostate | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Brachytherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | External beam radiation therapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
