  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Uric acid stones: invisible on X-ray, visible on CT.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Pure uric acid. This question tests fundamental knowledge regarding the radiologic properties of different kidney stone compositions. Pure uric acid stones are unique among common renal calculi in their radiolucent nature on plain film radiography.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe radiopacity of kidney stones is directly related to their elemental composition, particularly the presence of calcium. Calcium-containing stones (e.g., calcium oxalate, calcium phosphate) are highly radiopaque because calcium effectively absorbs X-rays. Struvite stones (magnesium ammonium phosphate) are moderately radiopaque due to their mineral content. Cystine stones, composed of an amino acid, are faintly radiopaque but can often be difficult to visualize on plain films, sometimes appearing radiolucent. In contrast, pure uric acid stones are composed entirely of organic material (uric acid) and lack significant mineral content, rendering them completely radiolucent on conventional X-rays, meaning they do not absorb X-rays and thus do not cast a shadow.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption a (Cystine): Incorrect. While often poorly visualized and sometimes appearing radiolucent, cystine stones are faintly radiopaque and can be seen on plain X-ray, unlike pure uric acid stones.\nOption b (Calcium): Incorrect. Calcium oxalate and calcium phosphate stones are the most common types of kidney stones and are highly radiopaque, making them easily visible on plain X-rays.\nOption d (Meganasum ammonium sulfate): Incorrect. This appears to be a misspelling of Magnesium ammonium phosphate (Struvite) stones. Struvite stones are moderately radiopaque and are visible on plain X-rays.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Stone Type | Composition | Radiopacity |\n|---|---|---|\n| Calcium Oxalate/Phosphate | Calcium salts | Highly Radiopaque |\n| Struvite (Magnesium Ammonium Phosphate) | Magnesium, Ammonium, Phosphate | Moderately Radiopaque |\n| Cystine | Amino acid | Faintly Radiopaque (often appears radiolucent) |\n| Uric Acid | Uric acid | Radiolucent |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Uric acid stones are the only truly radiolucent stones on plain X-ray.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain X-ray (KUB), a radiolucent stone will not be visible. Its presence is often inferred by secondary signs or confirmed with cross-sectional imaging like non-contrast CT, where it appears as a distinct density.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAUA Guideline for the Medical Management of Kidney Stones (2014). Recommends non-contrast CT as the imaging modality of choice for stone detection and characterization, especially for radiolucent stones.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| a | Cystine | ❌ Incorrect |\n| b | Calcium | ❌ Incorrect |\n| c | Pure uric acid | ❌ Incorrect |\n| d | Meganasum ammonium sulfate | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
