  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 BPH: Obstructive symptoms make you strain, irritative symptoms make you complain.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. This question accurately identifies the classic obstructive symptoms of benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH), which are directly related to the physical impedance of urine flow from the bladder.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBenign prostatic hyperplasia leads to an enlarged prostate gland, which compresses the prostatic urethra. This compression increases bladder outlet resistance, making it difficult for the bladder to empty effectively. The symptoms listed in option D—weak stream, intermittency, hesitancy, and straining—are all direct manifestations of this increased resistance and the bladder's effort to overcome the obstruction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Frequency, urgency, and dysuria are primarily irritative (storage) symptoms, not obstructive. Dysuria is pain, often associated with infection or inflammation, not direct obstruction.\nOption B (Incorrect): Frequency and urgency are irritative symptoms. While a weak stream is obstructive, this option mixes symptom types, making it an incomplete and incorrect choice for purely obstructive symptoms.\nOption C (Incorrect): Dysuria and nocturia are irritative/storage symptoms. While intermittency and weak stream are obstructive, the inclusion of irritative symptoms makes this option incorrect for a question specifically asking for obstructive symptoms.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Symptom Type | Description | Examples |\n|---|---|---|\n| Obstructive (Voiding) | Symptoms due to increased resistance to urine flow from prostatic enlargement. | Weak stream, hesitancy, intermittency, straining, incomplete emptying, post-void dribbling |\n| Irritative (Storage) | Symptoms due to bladder dysfunction secondary to chronic obstruction or detrusor instability. | Frequency, urgency, nocturia, dysuria (less common, often with infection) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Obstructive symptoms are about flow mechanics; irritative symptoms are about bladder storage and sensation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn transrectal ultrasound (TRUS), an enlarged prostate gland with a volume greater than 30-40 mL would be observed. During cystoscopy, prostatic lobes may be seen encroaching into the urethral lumen, causing significant bladder outlet obstruction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on the Management of Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia (2021) recommends assessing both irritative and obstructive symptoms using validated questionnaires like the AUA Symptom Index.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| a | Frequency , urgency and dysuria | ❌ Incorrect |\n| b | Frequency , urgency and weak stream | ❌ Incorrect |\n| c | Dysuria, nectouria , intermittency and weak stream | ❌ Incorrect |\n| d | Weak stream , intermittency, hesitancy and straining | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
