  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Weak stream means flow's low, not storage woe!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 'Weak stream' because it is a classic voiding (obstructive) lower urinary tract symptom (LUTS), not a storage symptom. Benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) can cause both storage and voiding symptoms, but the question specifically asks for symptoms *not* associated with storage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLower urinary tract symptoms (LUTS) are broadly categorized into storage, voiding (obstructive), and post-micturition symptoms. Storage symptoms, such as urgency, frequency, and nocturia, arise from bladder irritation or reduced functional capacity, often due to detrusor overactivity or incomplete emptying. Voiding symptoms, like weak stream, hesitancy, and straining, are directly related to bladder outlet obstruction caused by prostatic enlargement, impeding urine flow. Understanding this distinction is crucial for accurate diagnosis and management of BPH.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption a (Urgency) (Incorrect): Urgency is a classic storage symptom, characterized by a sudden, compelling desire to void that is difficult to defer.\nOption b (Frequency) (Incorrect): Frequency, or increased daytime voiding, is a common storage symptom, often due to reduced bladder capacity or increased urine production.\nOption c (Nectouria) (Incorrect): Nocturia, or waking up to void at night, is a prominent storage symptom, often caused by incomplete bladder emptying or altered circadian rhythm.\nOption d (Dysuria) (Incorrect): Dysuria, or painful urination, can be a storage symptom, often associated with bladder irritation or inflammation, though less specific to BPH itself than other storage symptoms.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Symptom Category | Description | Examples |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Storage LUTS** | Related to the bladder's ability to hold urine | Urgency, Frequency, Nocturia, Dysuria |\n| **Voiding LUTS** | Related to the bladder's ability to empty urine | Weak stream, Hesitancy, Straining, Intermittency |\n| **Post-Micturition LUTS** | Symptoms experienced immediately after voiding | Post-void dribbling, Sensation of incomplete emptying |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Storage symptoms are about holding, voiding symptoms are about flowing.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn transrectal ultrasound (TRUS), BPH appears as an enlarged prostate with varying echogenicity. During a transurethral resection of the prostate (TURP), the surgeon would visualize the enlarged prostatic tissue obstructing the bladder neck and prostatic urethra, directly correlating with the voiding symptoms like weak stream.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines on the Management of Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia (2021) classify LUTS into storage, voiding, and post-micturition categories for assessment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| a | Urgency | ❌ Incorrect |\n| b | Frequency | ❌ Incorrect |\n| c | Nectouria | ❌ Incorrect |\n| d | Dysuria | ❌ Incorrect |\n| e | Weak stream | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
