  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, untwist the testis out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption D is the correct answer. The question asks for a feature that is NOT shared between testicular torsion and epididymoorchitis. While both conditions present with pain, fever, and skin redness, the relief of pain on elevation (Prehn's sign) is typically positive in epididymitis but negative or worsens in testicular torsion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTesticular torsion is a surgical emergency caused by the twisting of the spermatic cord, leading to vascular compromise and ischemia of the testis. This mechanical obstruction results in sudden, severe pain that is not relieved by elevation. In contrast, epididymoorchitis is an inflammatory or infectious process of the epididymis and/or testis. The pain associated with epididymitis is often more gradual in onset, and elevating the scrotum can reduce venous congestion, thereby alleviating discomfort, a phenomenon known as Prehn's sign. This physiological difference in pain response to elevation is a critical distinguishing factor.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Pain) (Incorrect): Both testicular torsion and epididymoorchitis cause significant scrotal pain, although the onset and character may differ.\nOption B (Fever) (Incorrect): While more common in infectious epididymoorchitis, fever can also be present in cases of severe, necrotic testicular torsion.\nOption C (Skin redness) (Incorrect): Both conditions can lead to scrotal erythema due to inflammation (epididymitis) or ischemia/inflammation (torsion).\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Testicular Torsion                               | Epididymoorchitis                                  |\n|---------------------|--------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------|\n| **Onset of Pain**   | Sudden, severe                                   | Gradual, dull ache                                 |\n| **Prehn's Sign**    | Negative (pain worsens or unchanged with elevation) | Positive (pain relieved with elevation)            |\n| **Cremasteric Reflex**| Absent                                           | Present                                            |\n| **Urinalysis**      | Typically normal                                 | Often shows pyuria/bacteriuria                     |\n| **Doppler US**      | Decreased/absent blood flow                      | Increased blood flow                               |\n| **Management**      | Surgical detorsion (emergency)                   | Antibiotics, NSAIDs, scrotal support               |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Prehn's sign and cremasteric reflex are key clinical differentiators.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn Doppler ultrasound, testicular torsion typically shows absent or significantly diminished blood flow to the affected testis, while epididymoorchitis demonstrates increased blood flow due to inflammation. Intraoperatively for torsion, a twisted spermatic cord and an ischemic, often dusky, testis would be observed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on the Diagnosis and Management of Testicular Torsion (2017). It recommends emergent surgical exploration for suspected testicular torsion.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| a | Pain | ❌ Incorrect |\n| b | Fever | ❌ Incorrect |\n| c | Skin radness | ❌ Incorrect |\n| d | Relief of pain on elevation | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
