  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 VCUG diagnoses PUV; scope treats the flow.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A because posterior urethral valve (PUV) is primarily diagnosed by voiding cystourethrogram (VCUG), not urethroscope. Urethroscopy is typically reserved for the therapeutic intervention of valve ablation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPUV is a congenital obstructive anomaly of the male urethra. The definitive diagnostic study is the VCUG, which characteristically demonstrates a dilated posterior urethra, an abrupt caliber change at the level of the valve, and often bladder neck hypertrophy and vesicoureteral reflux. While urethroscopy can visualize the valves, it is primarily a therapeutic tool for transurethral resection, not the initial diagnostic modality.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): This statement is true. Transurethral resection (ablation) of the valve is the standard and definitive treatment for PUV, relieving the obstruction.\nOption C (Incorrect): This statement is true. PUV causes significant infravesical obstruction, leading to bladder outlet obstruction, which can manifest as acute urinary retention, hydronephrosis, and progressive renal damage.\nOption D (Incorrect): This statement is incorrect because option A is false, meaning not all the preceding statements are true.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Posterior Urethral Valve (PUV) | Urethral Stricture | Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia (BPH) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Etiology** | Congenital (male only) | Acquired (trauma, infection, iatrogenic) | Age-related (hormonal) |\n| **Primary Diagnosis** | Voiding Cystourethrogram (VCUG) | Retrograde Urethrogram (RUG) | Clinical, PSA, Uroflow, PVR |\n| **Treatment** | Transurethral valve ablation | Urethrotomy, Urethroplasty | Medical (alpha-blockers, 5-ARI), TURP |\n| **Age Group** | Neonates, infants, children | Any age, often adult males | Older adult males |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: VCUG diagnoses PUV; urethroscope treats it.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn voiding cystourethrogram (VCUG), characteristic findings include a dilated posterior urethra, an abrupt transition at the level of the valve, and often bladder wall thickening or trabeculation, and vesicoureteral reflux.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nStandard pediatric urology practice, as reflected by major societies like the AUA and AAP, emphasizes voiding cystourethrogram (VCUG) as the primary diagnostic imaging modality for suspected posterior urethral valve.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Is best diagnosed by urethroscope | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Treated by Transurethral resection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Cause of acute urine retention | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | All of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
