  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Blood at the meatus? Don't be a hero, get a RUG, no Foley!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, as bleeding per rectum is not a classic sign of urethral rupture. The question correctly identifies the triad of signs associated with urethral injury, with the exception being rectal bleeding.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUrethral rupture, often resulting from pelvic trauma or straddle injuries, presents with a distinct clinical triad due to the anatomical location and nature of the injury. Perineal hematoma, also known as a butterfly hematoma, occurs from extravasation of blood into the perineal space. Bleeding per urethra is a direct consequence of mucosal and vascular injury within the urethra itself. Retention of urine results from the disruption of the urethral lumen, preventing the bladder from emptying. These signs are critical for prompt diagnosis and management to prevent complications like stricture formation or infection.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Perineal hematoma is a classic sign of urethral rupture, indicating extravasation of blood into the perineal tissues.\nOption B (Incorrect): Bleeding per urethra is a direct and highly indicative sign of urethral injury, often seen as blood at the meatus.\nOption C (Incorrect): Retention of urine is a common sign due to the disruption of the urethral lumen, preventing normal voiding.\nOption D (Correct): Bleeding per rectum is not a sign of urethral rupture; it suggests a concomitant rectal injury, which requires separate evaluation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Sign | Urethral Rupture | Bladder Rupture | Rectal Injury |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Perineal Hematoma | Yes (butterfly) | No (unless extensive pelvic trauma) | No |\n| Bleeding per Urethra | Yes | No (hematuria common) | No |\n| Retention of Urine | Yes | Yes (if extraperitoneal) | No |\n| High-riding Prostate | Yes | No | No |\n| Bleeding per Rectum | No | No | Yes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Blood at the meatus after trauma means no Foley, get a RUG!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThe definitive diagnostic imaging for suspected urethral rupture is a Retrograde Urethrogram (RUG). This study will demonstrate extravasation of contrast material from the urethra, indicating the site and extent of the rupture. Intraoperatively, one would observe a significant perineal hematoma, disruption of the urethral continuity, and potentially a high-riding prostate.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines on Urethral Trauma (2020). These guidelines recommend immediate retrograde urethrogram for suspected urethral injury before attempting catheterization.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Perinael hematoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Bleeding per urethera | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Retention of urine | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Bleeding per rectum | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
