  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Ewing's: Onion-skin, not soap-bubble dreams.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption D is the correct answer because Ewing's sarcoma does not typically present with a \"soap bubble\" appearance. This radiological finding is characteristic of other bone lesions, while Ewing's sarcoma exhibits distinct aggressive features.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEwing's sarcoma is a highly malignant primary bone tumor, predominantly affecting children and young adults. Its aggressive nature leads to rapid cortical destruction and characteristic periosteal reactions. Understanding these specific radiological patterns, such as the \"onion-skin\" (lamellated) periosteal reaction, \"sunburst\" appearance, or Codman's triangle, is crucial for differentiating it from other bone pathologies and guiding appropriate management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): \"It has soap bubbles appearance\" - This statement is incorrect. The \"soap bubble\" or multiloculated appearance is typically associated with benign bone lesions such as fibrous dysplasia, aneurysmal bone cysts, or giant cell tumors, not Ewing's sarcoma.\nOption E (Incorrect): \"It displays Codman's triangle\" - This statement is correct. Codman's triangle is a periosteal reaction formed by the elevation of the periosteum by an aggressive lesion, and it is a recognized feature of Ewing's sarcoma, as well as osteosarcoma and infection.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Type | Typical Age | Common Location | Characteristic Radiographic Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Ewing's Sarcoma | 5-20 years | Diaphysis of long bones, pelvis | Onion-skin periosteal reaction, sunburst, Codman's triangle, permeative lytic lesion |\n| Osteosarcoma | 10-20 years | Metaphysis of long bones (distal femur, proximal tibia) | Sunburst periosteal reaction, Codman's triangle, osteoid matrix formation |\n| Fibrous Dysplasia | Any age (often discovered in childhood) | Long bones, ribs, skull, pelvis | Ground-glass matrix, \"shepherd's crook\" deformity, \"soap bubble\" appearance (less common but can be seen) |\n| Aneurysmal Bone Cyst | <20 years | Metaphysis of long bones, vertebrae | Expansile lytic lesion, thin sclerotic rim, fluid-fluid levels on MRI, \"soap bubble\" appearance |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Ewing's is onion-skin or sunburst, not soap bubbles.\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain radiographs or CT, Ewing's sarcoma typically presents as a permeative lytic lesion with ill-defined margins. Characteristic periosteal reactions include a lamellated (\"onion-skin\") appearance, a spiculated (\"sunburst\") pattern, or Codman's triangle. The \"soap bubble\" appearance, however, is a classic finding for other lesions like aneurysmal bone cysts or fibrous dysplasia.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Bone Cancer (2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis, staging, and treatment of Ewing's sarcoma, emphasizing imaging characteristics for initial assessment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| D | It has soap bubbles appearance | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | It displays codman's triangle | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
