  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pain out of proportion? Think compartment syndrome, act fast!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Severe, unremitting pain in a casted limb is an absolute indication for urgent cast removal, as it is the primary symptom of impending compartment syndrome, a limb-threatening condition requiring immediate intervention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCompartment syndrome occurs when pressure within a closed fascial compartment rises, compromising microcirculation and leading to muscle and nerve ischemia. Pain out of proportion to the injury, especially pain unrelieved by analgesia or worsening with passive stretching, is the most reliable early symptom. Urgent cast removal (bivalving) is the critical first step to relieve external compression and prevent irreversible tissue damage and limb loss.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Edema of the limb alone is not an absolute indication for urgent cast removal; it can often be managed with elevation, though severe edema can contribute to compartment syndrome.\nOption C (Incorrect): Itching is a common, irritating, but non-limb-threatening side effect of cast wear and does not require urgent removal.\nOption D (Incorrect): Absent or weak pulse is indeed a critical sign of severe vascular compromise and an absolute emergency. However, in the context of compartment syndrome, severe pain (Option B) is often the earliest and most reliable clinical sign, preceding pulselessness, and thus warrants urgent cast removal to prevent progression to irreversible damage.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Indication for Cast Removal | Urgency | Underlying Concern |\n| :-------------------------- | :------ | :----------------- |\n| Severe, unremitting pain    | Urgent  | Compartment Syndrome |\n| Absent/weak pulse           | Emergent | Vascular Compromise |\n| Progressive numbness/tingling | Urgent  | Nerve Compression/Ischemia |\n| Significant edema           | Monitor/Urgent | Potential Compartment Syndrome |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unrelenting pain in a casted limb demands immediate investigation for compartment syndrome.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNot applicable as this question focuses on clinical signs and symptoms. No image was provided in the question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Acute Compartment Syndrome (2019) recommends immediate cast bivalving and fasciotomy for confirmed compartment syndrome.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Edema of the limb | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pain in the limb | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Itching of the part | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Absent or weak pulse in involved limb | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
