  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Sling it, don't fix it, for most clavicle breaks!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Broad arm sling with analgesic. This reflects the current standard of care for the vast majority of clavicle fractures, which are managed non-operatively due to their excellent healing potential.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nClavicle fractures, particularly midshaft fractures, typically heal well with conservative management. The broad arm sling provides comfort, immobilizes the fracture site sufficiently to promote callus formation, and allows for early mobilization of the hand and wrist. Analgesics are crucial for pain control, facilitating patient compliance and comfort during the healing process.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Closed reduction is rarely indicated for clavicle fractures as it is difficult to maintain and offers no significant benefit over sling immobilization for most fracture patterns.\nOption B (Incorrect): Internal fixation is reserved for specific indications such as open fractures, neurovascular compromise, significant displacement/shortening, or non-union, not as a first-line treatment.\nOption D (Incorrect): Physiotherapy is important for rehabilitation *after* initial healing, but it is not the first line of treatment for an acute fracture; initial management focuses on immobilization and pain control.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Management Type | Indications |\n|---|---|\n| Non-operative | Most midshaft fractures, minimally displaced fractures, medial/lateral fractures without significant displacement/instability |\n| Operative | Open fractures, neurovascular compromise, significant displacement (>2cm shortening), impending skin compromise, non-union, floating shoulder, lateral end fractures with coracoclavicular ligament disruption |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Most clavicle fractures heal with a sling; surgery is for specific indications.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain radiographs (AP and 45-degree cephalic tilt views), a clavicle fracture will appear as a cortical breach, often with displacement or angulation. The degree of displacement and shortening helps guide management decisions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline (2018) recommends non-operative treatment with a sling for most midshaft clavicle fractures.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Closed reduction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Internal fixation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Broad arm sling with analgesic | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Physiotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
