  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Axillary nerve: the shoulder's vulnerable neighbor.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Axillary nerve. Fractures of the proximal humerus, particularly those involving the surgical neck, frequently compromise the axillary nerve due to its close anatomical proximity and course around this region.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe axillary nerve, originating from the posterior cord of the brachial plexus (C5, C6), courses posteriorly and inferiorly, wrapping around the surgical neck of the humerus as it passes through the quadrangular space. This anatomical relationship makes it highly susceptible to direct injury, traction, or compression during proximal humerus fractures, especially displaced surgical neck fractures. Injury to the axillary nerve typically results in paralysis of the deltoid and teres minor muscles, leading to impaired shoulder abduction and external rotation, along with sensory loss over the lateral aspect of the shoulder (the 'regimental badge' area).\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Ulnar) (Incorrect): The ulnar nerve runs medially in the arm and posterior to the medial epicondyle of the humerus, making it vulnerable to elbow injuries, not proximal humerus fractures.\nOption B (Radial) (Incorrect): The radial nerve spirals around the midshaft of the humerus in the spiral groove, making it susceptible to midshaft humerus fractures, not proximal ones.\nOption D (Spinal accessory) (Incorrect): The spinal accessory nerve (CN XI) innervates the sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles and is located in the neck, far from the humerus.\nOption E (Phrenic) (Incorrect): The phrenic nerve (C3-C5) innervates the diaphragm and is located in the neck and thorax, unrelated to humerus fractures.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Common Injury Site | Clinical Presentation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Axillary | Surgical neck of humerus | Deltoid paralysis, loss of shoulder abduction, sensory loss over 'regimental badge' area |\n| Radial | Midshaft humerus | Wrist drop, loss of elbow/wrist/finger extension, sensory loss over dorsum of hand |\n| Ulnar | Medial epicondyle (elbow) | Claw hand deformity, loss of finger adduction/abduction, sensory loss over medial 1.5 fingers |\n| Median | Supracondylar humerus (elbow), carpal tunnel | Ape hand deformity, loss of thumb opposition, sensory loss over lateral 3.5 fingers |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Proximal humerus fracture = think axillary nerve. Midshaft fracture = think radial nerve.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray or CT, a fracture line through the surgical neck of the humerus would be evident. Intraoperatively, the axillary nerve would be visualized wrapping around the posterior aspect of the surgical neck, potentially contused, stretched, or transected by fracture fragments.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAAOS Clinical Practice Guideline: Management of Proximal Humerus Fractures (2019). Recommends a thorough neurovascular assessment for all proximal humerus fractures.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ulnar | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | .Radial | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Axillary | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Spinal accessory | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Phrenic | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
