  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Posterior hip dislocation: Dashboard injury's classic signature.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Posterior. Posterior hip dislocations are overwhelmingly the most common type of traumatic hip dislocation, primarily due to the typical mechanisms of high-energy injury and the anatomical vulnerability of the posterior capsule.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPosterior hip dislocations account for 85-90% of all traumatic hip dislocations. This prevalence is largely attributed to the 'dashboard injury' mechanism in motor vehicle accidents, where a flexed, adducted, and internally rotated hip impacts the dashboard, driving the femoral head posteriorly. The posterior capsule and ligaments are anatomically weaker than their anterior counterparts, making them more susceptible to rupture under such forces. Clinically, this presents with the classic triad of a shortened, adducted, and internally rotated lower extremity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Anterior): Incorrect. Anterior dislocations are much less common (5-15%) and typically result from forced abduction and external rotation, presenting with an externally rotated, abducted, and slightly flexed limb.\nOption C (Central): Incorrect. Central dislocations are not pure dislocations but rather fracture-dislocations where the femoral head is driven through the acetabulum, often associated with acetabular fractures.\nOption D (Inferior): Incorrect. Inferior dislocations (luxatio erecta) are exceedingly rare and involve extreme flexion and abduction, often with the femoral head inferior to the acetabulum.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Dislocation | Incidence | Mechanism of Injury | Clinical Presentation |\n|---------------------|-----------|---------------------|-----------------------|\n| Posterior           | 85-90%    | Dashboard injury (flexion, adduction, IR) | Shortened, adducted, internally rotated |\n| Anterior            | 5-15%     | Forced abduction, external rotation | Abducted, externally rotated, slightly flexed |\n| Central             | Rare      | Direct lateral impact to hip, often with acetabular fracture | Variable, often with limb shortening |\n| Inferior            | Very Rare | Extreme flexion, abduction | Femoral head inferior to acetabulum, limb often abducted and flexed |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Dashboard injury = posterior hip dislocation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain radiographs (AP pelvis and lateral hip views), a posterior hip dislocation typically shows the femoral head superior and posterior to the acetabulum, often appearing smaller due to internal rotation. CT scan is crucial post-reduction to assess for concentric reduction, incarcerated fragments, and associated fractures (e.g., acetabular, femoral head).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nOrthopaedic Trauma Association (OTA) guidelines for hip dislocations emphasize prompt reduction (within 6 hours) to minimize complications like avascular necrosis and post-traumatic arthritis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Anterior | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Posterior | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Central | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Inferior | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
