  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cortical origin, night pain, NSAID's friend – that's osteoid osteoma's trend!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Cortex. Osteoid osteoma is a benign osteoblastic tumor that characteristically originates from the cortical bone, making this a fundamental anatomical point for diagnosis and understanding its presentation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOsteoid osteomas are small, benign bone tumors defined by a central nidus of osteoid and woven bone. This nidus is most commonly found within the cortical bone, often surrounded by a significant zone of reactive sclerotic bone. This intracortical location is crucial for understanding the tumor's typical presentation, such as localized pain (especially at night, relieved by NSAIDs), and its characteristic radiographic appearance of a lucent nidus with surrounding sclerosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While subperiosteal osteoid osteomas can occur, they are less common than those originating from the cortex and are not considered the primary or most typical origin.\nOption C (Incorrect): Medullary osteoid osteomas are rare; the tumor's characteristic reactive sclerosis is most pronounced and typical when it arises within the dense cortical bone.\nOption D (Incorrect): Since options A and C are not the primary or most common origins, 'All of the above' is incorrect. The cortex is the predominant site.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Osteoid Osteoma | Osteoblastoma |\n| :---------------- | :-------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------ |\n| Size (Nidus) | < 1.5-2 cm | > 2 cm |\n| Location | Predominantly cortical (80-90%) | Predominantly medullary/cancellous, posterior spine |\n| Pain | Worse at night, relieved by NSAIDs | Dull, aching, less responsive to NSAIDs |\n| Reactive Sclerosis | Prominent, especially in cortical lesions | Less prominent, especially in medullary lesions |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Osteoid osteoma: cortical nidus, night pain, NSAID relief.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray or CT, an osteoid osteoma typically appears as a small, lucent nidus (usually <1.5-2 cm) with or without central calcification, surrounded by a dense zone of reactive cortical sclerosis. Intraoperatively, the nidus is often reddish-brown, granular, and distinct from the surrounding sclerotic bone.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNo specific major society guideline for osteoid osteoma; management follows general orthopedic oncology principles for benign bone tumors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Periosteum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cortex | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Medullary cavity | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | All of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
