  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Soft bones, spine groans.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOsteomalacia is characterized by defective mineralization of bone, leading to soft, weakened bones. The spine, as a primary weight-bearing structure, is predominantly affected due to the constant mechanical stress it endures.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOsteomalacia results from impaired mineralization of newly formed osteoid, leading to its accumulation and structurally weak bone. The axial skeleton, particularly the spine, bears significant compressive loads daily. This constant stress on poorly mineralized vertebral bodies makes them highly susceptible to microfractures, pain, and eventual compression deformities, explaining its predominant involvement.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): While the pelvis is a weight-bearing bone and can be affected, the spine typically shows more prominent and symptomatic involvement due to its continuous axial loading.\nOption C (Incorrect): Skull bones are generally less affected by osteomalacia as they are not primary weight-bearing structures and have a different biomechanical role.\nOption D (Incorrect): Metatarsals are peripheral bones; while bone softening can occur systemically, the axial skeleton, especially the spine, is predominantly and symptomatically affected.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Osteomalacia (Adults) | Rickets (Children) | Osteoporosis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Primary Defect | Defective bone mineralization | Defective bone mineralization | Decreased bone mass/density |\n| Predominant Sites | Spine, pelvis, long bones | Growth plates, long bones | Spine, hip, wrist |\n| Key Symptom | Bone pain, muscle weakness | Bone deformities, growth retardation | Fragility fractures |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Osteomalacia weakens axial skeleton, spine first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nX-rays may show generalized osteopenia, cortical thinning, and characteristic Looser's zones (pseudofractures), especially in the pelvis, femoral necks, and scapulae. Vertebral compression fractures are also common in the spine.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Clinical Endocrinologists (AACE) and American College of Endocrinology (ACE) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Treatment of Postmenopausal Osteoporosis (2020) recommends screening for secondary causes of osteoporosis, including osteomalacia, in patients with low bone mineral density or fragility fractures.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Spine | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Pelvis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Skull bone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Metatarsals | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
