  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 FOOSH + kids = posterior displacement.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Extension. The vast majority of supracondylar humerus fractures in children are extension-type injuries, typically resulting from a fall onto an outstretched hand with the elbow in extension.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nExtension-type supracondylar humerus fractures account for approximately 95-98% of all such injuries. This mechanism occurs when a child falls onto an outstretched hand, forcing the olecranon against the olecranon fossa, which then acts as a fulcrum. The distal humerus is hyperextended and displaced posteriorly and proximally relative to the humeral shaft. This common injury pattern is crucial to recognize for appropriate classification and management, as it dictates the reduction maneuver and pin placement.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Flexion-type supracondylar fractures are rare, accounting for only 1-5% of cases, and typically result from a direct blow to the posterior elbow with the elbow in flexion.\nOption C (Incorrect): A combination of flexion and extension mechanisms is not a recognized primary classification for supracondylar humerus fractures; they are distinctly categorized as either extension or flexion.\nOption D (Incorrect): There is a clearly defined most common type, which is the extension type.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Extension Type | Flexion Type |\n|---|---|---|\n| Incidence | ~95-98% | ~1-5% |\n| Mechanism | Fall on outstretched hand (FOOSH) with elbow extended | Direct blow to posterior elbow with elbow flexed |\n| Distal Fragment Displacement | Posterior and proximal | Anterior and proximal |\n| Associated Nerve Injury | Anterior interosseous nerve (AIN) most common | Ulnar nerve most common |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Extension is the rule for supracondylar humerus fractures.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a lateral X-ray, extension-type fractures show posterior displacement of the distal humeral fragment relative to the humeral shaft. Key radiographic signs include disruption of the anterior humeral line and posterior fat pad sign.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline: The Treatment of Pediatric Supracondylar Humerus Fractures (2011, updated 2019). Recommends closed reduction and percutaneous pinning for displaced fractures.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Flextion | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Extension | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Combination of A & B | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | None of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
