  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pavlik: The early bird's hip fix.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe Pavlik Harness is the correct answer because it is the gold standard and most effective initial treatment for developmental dysplasia of the hip (DDH) in infants, particularly when diagnosed early. It promotes proper hip development and stability non-invasively.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Pavlik harness works by maintaining the infant's hips in a position of flexion and abduction, which gently centers the femoral head within the acetabulum. This stable, reduced position encourages the natural remodeling and deepening of the acetabulum, allowing the hip joint to develop normally. It is a dynamic brace, permitting some movement, which is crucial for stimulating physiological development of the hip joint without restricting growth.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Closed reduction under general anesthesia): Incorrect. This is typically reserved for older infants (e.g., 6-18 months) or when Pavlik harness treatment fails, as it is a more invasive procedure with higher risks than initial Pavlik harness use.\nOption C (Surgical reduction + cast): Incorrect. This is a last-resort treatment for irreducible dislocations or failed closed reductions, indicating a more severe or late-presenting case, and is not the primary 'good treatment' for CHD.\nOption D (Observations for 3 months than treatment if needed): Incorrect. Delaying treatment for DDH can lead to worsening dysplasia, increased difficulty in reduction, and a higher likelihood of needing more invasive procedures. Early intervention is critical for optimal outcomes.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Treatment | Indication | Mechanism | Risks/Considerations |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Pavlik Harness | Newborn to 6 months, reducible DDH | Maintains hip flexion and abduction to center femoral head | Avascular necrosis (rare if properly fitted), skin irritation, femoral nerve palsy |\n| Closed Reduction | 6-18 months, Pavlik failure, irreducible DDH | Manual reduction under anesthesia, followed by spica cast | Avascular necrosis, re-dislocation, stiffness |\n| Open Reduction | >18 months, failed closed reduction, severe dysplasia | Surgical exposure and direct reduction of hip | Avascular necrosis, infection, stiffness, leg length discrepancy |\n| Observation | Not a primary treatment for diagnosed DDH | N/A | Worsening dysplasia, need for more invasive treatment, poor long-term outcomes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Early DDH = Pavlik. Late/Failed = Reduction.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor infants under 4-6 months, ultrasound is the primary imaging modality. It assesses the alpha and beta angles (Graf method) to evaluate acetabular coverage and hip stability. For older infants, X-rays are used to visualize the ossified femoral head and acetabulum.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for Developmental Dysplasia of the Hip in Infants (2014). Recommends screening and early treatment with a Pavlik harness for reducible hips in infants.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Closed reduction under general anesthesia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pavlik Harness | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Surgical reduction + cast | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Observations for 3 months than treatment if needed | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
