  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Never tap a head with a mass, or you'll cause a crash.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Lumbar puncture. Performing a lumbar puncture in a patient with head injury and cerebral compression is dangerous because it can precipitate brain herniation due to a sudden pressure gradient change.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCerebral compression often indicates increased intracranial pressure (ICP). The brain and spinal cord are contained within a relatively fixed volume. When ICP is elevated, a lumbar puncture creates a sudden pressure differential between the intracranial compartment and the spinal canal. This pressure gradient can cause the brainstem or cerebellar tonsils to herniate through the foramen magnum, leading to brainstem compression, cardiorespiratory arrest, and death. This phenomenon is particularly risky in the presence of focal mass lesions or diffuse cerebral edema.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (CT scan) (Incorrect): A CT scan is the gold standard diagnostic tool for head injury and cerebral compression. It is safe and crucial for identifying intracranial pathology like hematomas, edema, or hydrocephalus, which cause compression. It does not increase ICP or risk herniation.\nOption C (Electroencephalography) (Incorrect): EEG measures electrical activity in the brain and is used to assess for seizures or diffuse encephalopathy. It is a non-invasive procedure and does not pose a risk of herniation or exacerbate cerebral compression.\nOption D (Carotid angiography) (Incorrect): Carotid angiography (now often CT angiography) is used to evaluate vascular injuries such as dissections or aneurysms. While an invasive procedure, it does not directly increase intracranial pressure or precipitate herniation in the same manner as a lumbar puncture in the setting of cerebral compression.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Investigation | Purpose in Head Injury | Safety in Cerebral Compression |\n|---|---|---|\n| Lumbar Puncture | CSF analysis (infection, SAH) | **Contraindicated** (risk of herniation) |\n| CT Scan | Identify intracranial lesions (hematoma, edema, shift) | **Safe and Essential** (diagnostic) |\n| EEG | Assess for seizures, encephalopathy | Safe (non-invasive) |\n| Angiography | Evaluate vascular injury (dissection, aneurysm) | Safe (invasive but no direct ICP risk) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: LP + increased ICP = herniation risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a CT scan, cerebral compression would manifest as effacement of basal cisterns, sulcal effacement, midline shift, ventricular compression, or signs of herniation (e.g., uncal, tonsillar).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nBrain Trauma Foundation Guidelines (various editions, e.g., 2016, 2019) recommend against lumbar puncture in patients with suspected elevated ICP or focal neurological deficits without prior imaging.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lumber puncture | ✅ Correct |\n| B | CT scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Electroencephalography | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Carotid angiography | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
