  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, think glioblastoma for primary brain malignancy.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Astrocytoma. This is because astrocytomas, particularly glioblastoma (WHO grade IV astrocytoma), are the most prevalent and aggressive primary malignant brain tumors in adults. They originate from astrocytes, a type of glial cell, making them the most common primary malignant brain tumor.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAstrocytomas represent a broad spectrum of glial tumors, with glioblastoma being the most common and lethal. Their prevalence stems from the abundance of astrocytes in the brain, which are susceptible to neoplastic transformation. These tumors are characterized by diffuse infiltration, rapid growth, and significant neovascularization, making complete surgical resection challenging and recurrence common. Understanding their biology is crucial for diagnosis and treatment planning.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Oligodendrogliomas are less common than astrocytomas and typically have a better prognosis, often characterized by 1p/19q co-deletion.\nOption B (Incorrect): Ependymomas arise from ependymal cells lining the ventricles and spinal canal, and are less common than astrocytomas, particularly in adults.\nOption D (Incorrect): Gangliogliomas are rare, typically low-grade tumors composed of both neuronal and glial elements, far less common than astrocytomas.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Type | Origin Cell | Commonality (Adults) | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Astrocytoma (e.g., Glioblastoma) | Astrocytes | Most common primary malignant | Highly infiltrative, aggressive, ring-enhancing |\n| Oligodendroglioma | Oligodendrocytes | Less common | Often 1p/19q co-deletion, calcifications |\n| Ependymoma | Ependymal cells | Less common | Arise from ventricular lining, often posterior fossa in children |\n| Ganglioglioma | Neuronal & Glial | Rare | Often low-grade, cystic with mural nodule, temporal lobe seizures |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Glioblastoma is the king of primary malignant brain tumors.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, glioblastomas typically appear as ring-enhancing lesions with central necrosis and significant surrounding vasogenic edema, often with irregular margins. Intraoperatively, they are poorly demarcated, infiltrative, and often have a variegated appearance, making gross total resection difficult.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Health Organization (WHO) Classification of Tumours of the Central Nervous System (2021) recommends molecular and histological criteria for diagnosis and grading of brain tumors, with Glioblastoma being a Grade 4 astrocytic tumor.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Oligodendroglioma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Ependymoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Astrocytoma | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Ganglioglioma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
