  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Not all brain tumors are *in* the brain.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Schwannomas are correctly identified as the exception because they are tumors of nerve sheaths, primarily affecting cranial or peripheral nerves, rather than being common parenchymal cerebral (supratentorial) tumors.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThis question tests fundamental knowledge of neuro-oncology and tumor localization. Common supratentorial tumors in adults include metastases, gliomas (like glioblastoma), and meningiomas. Ependymomas, while possible supratentorially, are more classically infratentorial. Schwannomas, however, originate from Schwann cells of cranial or peripheral nerves, making them distinct from the other parenchymal or meningeal tumors listed.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Metastasis is the most common adult brain tumor and frequently occurs in the cerebral hemispheres (supratentorial compartment).\nOption B (Incorrect): Gliomas, including astrocytomas and glioblastoma multiforme, are a broad category of primary brain tumors, many of which are very common and arise in the cerebral hemispheres.\nOption C (Incorrect): Meningiomas are common benign tumors that arise from the meninges and frequently occur in the supratentorial compartment, often attached to the dura.\nOption D (Incorrect): Ependymomas can occur supratentorially, but they are more classically associated with the posterior fossa (4th ventricle) in children and the spinal cord. However, they are still considered a type of primary brain tumor, unlike schwannomas which are nerve sheath tumors.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Type | Common Location | Origin | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Metastasis | Supratentorial (cerebral hemispheres) | Systemic cancer spread | Multiple lesions, often at gray-white junction |\n| Gliomas | Supratentorial (cerebral hemispheres) | Glial cells (astrocytes, oligodendrocytes) | Variable grades (e.g., GBM is aggressive) |\n| Meningiomas | Supratentorial (dura-based) | Arachnoid cap cells | Benign, dural tail sign, calcification |\n| Ependymomas | Infratentorial (4th ventricle), Spinal cord, Supratentorial | Ependymal cells | Perivascular pseudorosettes, often in children |\n| Schwannomas | Infratentorial (Cranial Nerves, e.g., CN VIII), Peripheral Nerves | Schwann cells | Benign, slow-growing, associated with nerves |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Location, location, location: Know your brain tumor topography.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, schwannomas typically appear as well-circumscribed, enhancing masses along the course of a cranial nerve (e.g., cerebellopontine angle for vestibular schwannomas). Intraoperatively, they are often encapsulated and can be dissected from the nerve of origin, though preserving nerve function is challenging.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Health Organization (WHO) Classification of Tumours of the Central Nervous System (2021) recommends a comprehensive diagnostic approach based on histology and molecular features for accurate tumor classification and prognosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Metastasis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Gliomas | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Meningaiomas | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Ependymomas | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Schwanomas (neuromas) | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
