  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Lidocaine's magic number: 5 plain, 7 with epi. Don't exceed, or risk a trip to the ICU!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 5 mg/kg. This represents the generally accepted maximum safe dose of lidocaine when administered as a local anesthetic without the addition of epinephrine, balancing efficacy with the risk of systemic toxicity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLidocaine is an amide-type local anesthetic that blocks voltage-gated sodium channels, preventing nerve impulse conduction. Its metabolism occurs primarily in the liver via cytochrome P450 enzymes. Exceeding the maximum safe dose can lead to systemic absorption and toxicity, initially manifesting as central nervous system (CNS) symptoms like circumoral numbness, tinnitus, and seizures, progressing to cardiovascular depression, arrhythmias, and cardiac arrest. The dose limit is crucial to prevent these life-threatening complications.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (10 mg/kg) (Incorrect): This dose significantly exceeds the safe limit for plain lidocaine and would likely result in systemic toxicity.\nOption C (15 mg/kg) (Incorrect): This dose is dangerously high and would almost certainly cause severe CNS and cardiovascular toxicity.\nOption D (20 mg/kg) (Incorrect): This dose is far beyond any therapeutic range and would be lethal.\nOption E (25 mg/kg) (Incorrect): This dose is extremely toxic and would lead to immediate life-threatening systemic effects.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Local Anesthetic | Max Dose (plain) | Max Dose (with epi) | Onset | Duration |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Lidocaine | 4-5 mg/kg | 7 mg/kg | Fast | Medium |\n| Bupivacaine | 2-2.5 mg/kg | 3 mg/kg | Medium | Long |\n| Ropivacaine | 3 mg/kg | 3 mg/kg | Medium | Long |\n| Mepivacaine | 4-5 mg/kg | 7 mg/kg | Fast | Medium |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember 4-5 for plain lido, 7 for lido with epi.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThis question pertains to pharmacology and drug dosing; therefore, there is no direct imaging or intraoperative pearl.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Anesthesiologists (ASA) Practice Guidelines for Local Anesthesia (e.g., 2012, 2020 updates): These guidelines provide recommendations on safe dosing and administration of local anesthetics to minimize systemic toxicity.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 5 mg / kg | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 10 mg/ kg | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 15 mg / kg | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 20 mg / kg | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | 25 mg / kg | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 872068331-Surgery-MCQs.txt**\n",
